 in the Bank ladder match|Money in the Bank]] ([[Money in the Bank (2016)|2016]])<ref name=\"MITB\" />\n**[[Slammy Award]]s (5 times)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/whatsaslammy|title=What is a Slammy?|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116033325/https://www.wwe.com/inside/news/whatsaslammy|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n*** Breakout Star of the Year ([[Slammy Award#2013 Slammy Awards|2013]], [[Slammy Award#2014 Slammy Awards|2014]]) \u2013 {{small|2013 award shared with [[The Shield (professional wrestling)|The Shield]]}}<ref name=\"Slammy2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2013-12-09/full-slammy-award-winners-2013|title=2013 Slammy Award winners|date=December 6, 2013|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116034149/https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2013-12-09/full-slammy-award-winners-2013|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Slammy2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/52052-early-2014-wwe-slammy-award-winners-announced|title=Early 2014 WWE Slammy Award winners announced|date=December 8, 2014|last=Martin|first=Adam|accessdate=December 9, 2014|publisher=WrestleView|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603061054/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/52052-early-2014-wwe-slammy-award-winners-announced|archive-date=June 3, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*** Faction of the Year (2013, 2014) \u2013 {{small|with The Shield}}<ref name=\"Slammy2014\" />\n*** Trending Now (Hashtag) of the Year (2013) \u2013 {{small|#BelieveInTheShield, with The Shield}}<ref name=\"Slammy2013\" />\n** [[WWE Year-End Award]]s (2 times)\n*** Best Reunion (2018) \u2013 {{small|as part of The Shield}}<ref name=\"411mania\">{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/wwe-announces-year-end-awards-instagram-becky-lynch-braun-strowman/|title=WWE Announces Year-End Awards on Instagram|last=Thomas|first=Jeremy|date=December 23, 2018|publisher=411Mania.com|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224024537/https://411mania.com/wrestling/wwe-announces-year-end-awards-instagram-becky-lynch-braun-strowman/|archive-date=December 24, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=December 30, 2018}}</ref>\n***Return of the Year (2018)<ref name=\"411mania\" />\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Dean Ambrose|Jon Moxley}}\n* {{IMDb name|name=Jonathan Good}}\n* {{wwe superstars|name=Dean Ambrose|id=dean-ambrose}}\n* {{NJPW profile|id=51626|name=Jon Moxley|newlink=yes}}\n* {{Chikara profile|id=jon-moxley|name=Jon Moxley}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222090855/http://www.hwaonline.com/Roster/jonmoxley.htm|date=February 22, 2012|title=HWA profile}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100404122003/http://insanityprowrestling.com/roster-jonmoxley.html|date=April 4, 2010|title=IPW profile}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n{{Navboxes|\n|list1=\n{{AEW World Championship}}\n{{All Elite Wrestling}}\n{{New Japan Pro Wrestling personnel}}\n{{IWGP United States Championship}}\n{{Grand Slam-Triple Crown Champions}}\n{{WWE Championship}}\n{{WWE Intercontinental Championship}}\n{{WWE United States Championship}}\n{{WWE Tag Team Championship}}\n{{Money in the Bank winners}}\n{{The Authority}}\n{{TheShield WWE}}\n{{FIP World Heavyweight Championship}}\n{{CZW World Heavyweight Championship}}\n{{WXW World Tag Team Championship}}\n}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moxley, Jon}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:All Elite Wrestling personnel]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:NWA/WCW/WWE United States Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:The Authority (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:WWF/WWE Intercontinental Champions]]\n[[Category:WWF/WWE World Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:WWE Grand Slam champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name=Jon Moxley\n|image=Jon Moxley Oct 2019.jpg\n|image_size=230px\n|caption=Moxley in October 2019\n|birth_name=Jonathan David Good\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1985|12|07}}\n|birth_place=[[Cincinnati, Ohio]], U.S.\n|resides=[[Las Vegas, Nevada]], U.S.\n|spouse={{marriage|[[Renee Young]]<br />|April 9, 2017}}\n|names=Dean Ambrose<ref name=\"WWE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/dean-ambrose|title=Dean Ambrose|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723080607/http://www.wwe.com/superstars/dean-ambrose|archive-date=July 23, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><br>'''Jon Moxley'''<ref name=\"NJPW\">{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/profile/51626|title=Jon Moxley Profile|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=July 20, 2019}}</ref> \n|height=6 ft 2 in<ref name=\"NJPW\"/>\n|weight=224 lb<ref name=\"NJPW\"/>\n|billed=Cincinnati, Ohio<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n|trainer=Cody Hawk<ref name=slam/><br>[[Les Thatcher]]<ref name=slam/>\n|debut=2004<ref name=\"ambroseinde\"/>\n|retired=\n}}\n'''Jonathan David Good''' (born December 7, 1985) is an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] and actor, better known by his [[ring name]] '''Jon Moxley'''. He is currently signed to [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW), where he is the current [[AEW World Championship|AEW World Champion]] in his first reign, and [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW), where he is the current [[IWGP United States Championship|IWGP United States Champion]] in his second reign. He also makes occasional appearances on the [[independent circuit]]. He is well known for tenure with [[WWE]], where he performed under the ring name '''Dean Ambrose''' from 2011 to 2019.<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n\nGood began his professional wrestling career under the Jon Moxley name on the American independent circuit in 2004, working for various regional promotions including [[Full Impact Pro]] (FIP), [[Combat Zone Wrestling]] (CZW), and [[Dragon Gate USA]] (DGUSA). He won several top championships, including the [[FIP World Heavyweight Championship]] once, the [[HWA Heavyweight Championship]] thrice, and the [[CZW World Heavyweight Championship]] twice.\n\nAfter signing with WWE in 2011, he took the name Dean Ambrose and competed in their [[Farm team#Professional wrestling|developmental territories]] [[Florida Championship Wrestling]] (FCW) and [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]]. He joined the main roster in November 2012 as a member of [[The Shield (professional wrestling)|The Shield]], alongside [[Roman Reigns]] and [[Seth Rollins]]. In May 2013, Ambrose won his first championship in WWE, the [[WWE United States Championship|United States Championship]], while in the group, with his 351-day reign being the [[List of WWE United States Champions|longest under the WWE banner]]. Following The Shield's breakup in June 2014, Ambrose went on to become [[List of WWE Champions|a one-time]] [[WWE Championship|WWE Champion]], [[List of WWE Intercontinental Champions|a three-time]] [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Champion]], and [[List of WWE Raw Tag Team Champions|a two-time]] [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|Raw Tag Team Champion]] (with Seth Rollins). He was also the [[Money in the Bank (2016)|2016 Money in the Bank ladder match]] winner. Upon winning the Raw Tag Team Championship in August 2017, Ambrose became WWE's [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)#WWE|27th Triple Crown Champion]] and its [[Grand Slam (professional wrestling)#WWE|16th Grand Slam Champion]].\n\nFollowing his departure from WWE in 2019, Good reverted back to his Jon Moxley moniker and made an unannounced appearance at AEW's premiere event, [[Double or Nothing (2019)|Double or Nothing]]. He also started working in NJPW shortly after his WWE exit and won the IWGP United States Championship in his debut, becoming the first and only wrestler to have held the WWE and IWGP United States championships.\n\nOutside of wrestling, Good made his acting debut as the star of the 2015 action film ''[[12 Rounds 3: Lockdown]]'' and will appear in the upcoming action film ''[[Cagefighter: Worlds Collide]]''.\n\n== Early life ==\nJonathan David Good was born in [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, Ohio]], on December 7, 1985.<ref name=\"RSHerzog\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/about-face-dean-ambrose-is-the-wwes-unlikely-anti-hero-20141024|title=About Face: Dean Ambrose Is the WWE's Unlikely Anti-Hero|last=Herzog|first=Kenny|date=October 24, 2014|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=October 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025173019/http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/about-face-dean-ambrose-is-the-wwes-unlikely-anti-hero-20141024|archive-date=October 25, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"espn prof\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/wwe/story/_/id/17167094|title=WWE Profile - Dean Ambrose|date=July 28, 2016|website=[[ESPN]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102051103/http://www.espn.com/wwe/story/_/id/17167094|archive-date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 1, 2019}}</ref> An avid wrestling fan who idolized [[Bret Hart]] as a child, he used wrestling as an escape from his rough upbringing by watching wrestling videos and reading stories about wrestling's earlier days.<ref name=slam/><ref name=\"JanM\"/> One year after beginning to train as a wrestler, he dropped out of high school.<ref name=\"JanM\"/> He supported himself by working in factories, restaurants, and warehouses, but was constantly getting fired because he would skip work if he was booked to wrestle a match that clashed with his shift.<ref name=\"TMWFP\">''The Major Wrestling Figure Podcast'', episode: \"[https://mwfpod.podbean.com/e/dean-ambrose/ Dean Ambrose Talks...About Wrestling Figures]\" (February 8, 2019). Retrieved December 1, 2019.</ref> He later said that he did not care about getting fired from any of these minimum wage jobs because he could always find another one to replace it.<ref name=\"TMWFP\" />\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n=== Heartland Wrestling Association (2004\u20132011) ===\n[[File:JonMoxley.jpg|thumb|left|Moxley on the [[independent circuit]] in 2010]]\nGood began working for [[Les Thatcher]] in the [[Heartland Wrestling Association]] (HWA) [[professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] as a teenager by selling popcorn and setting up the [[Wrestling ring|ring]]. He began training to become a professional wrestler at the age of 18 under the teaching of Thatcher and HWA wrestler Cody Hawk.<ref name=slam/><ref name=\"JanM\">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/06/25/21765286.html|title=Ambrose not just Good, he's great|date=June 25, 2014|last=Murphy|first=Jan|accessdate=June 29, 2014|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150429172630/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/06/25/21765286.html|archive-date=April 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He made his debut in 2004 under the [[ring name]] Jon Moxley.<ref name=\"ambroseinde\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/wwe-mma-wrestling/dean-ambrose-interview-wwe-intercontinental-champion-talks-new-movie-aj-styles-samoa-joe-and-the-a6810701.html|title=Dean Ambrose speaks to the Independent|last=Hines|first=Martin|date=January 13, 2016|website=[[The Independent]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106163235/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/wwe-mma-wrestling/dean-ambrose-interview-wwe-intercontinental-champion-talks-new-movie-aj-styles-samoa-joe-and-the-a6810701.html|archive-date=January 6, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref> The following year, Moxley won the [[HWA Tag Team Championship]] twice, with Jimmy Turner and [[Ric Byrne]] respectively.<ref name=slam/><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=titles&kategorie=2&liga=70&titel=80&seite=2|title=List of champions - HWA Tag Team Titles|website=Wrestlingdata.com|pages=1\u20132|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106055301/https://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=titles&kategorie=2&liga=70&titel=80&seite=2|archive-date=January 6, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"HWA\"/> He captured the [[HWA Heavyweight Championship]] twice in 2006 by defeating [[Braxton Sutter|Pepper Parks]] on both occasions but lost the title to [[Chad Collyer]] and Brian Jennings respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=titles&aufgabe=matches&titel=78&seite=6|title=The 205 title matches - HWA Heavyweight Title|website=Wrestlingdata.com|pages=5\u20139|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106055208/https://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=titles&aufgabe=matches&titel=78&seite=6|archive-date=January 6, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom mid-2007 to early 2010, Moxley continued to work in the [[tag team]] division and held the HWA tag titles once with his trainer Cody Hawk and twice with King Vu.<ref name=\"slam\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> He won the HWA Heavyweight Championship for the third time from Aaron Williams in January 2010, before losing it to Gerome Phillips six months later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hwaonline.com/results.htm |title=HWA Event Results|publisher=[[Heartland Wrestling Association]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722154638/http://www.hwaonline.com/results.htm|archivedate=July 22, 2012|accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Other promotions (2006\u20132011) ===\n[[File:Jon Moxley vs. Nick Gage.jpg|thumb|Moxley wrestling [[Nick Gage]] in a [[Hardcore wrestling|barbed wire deathmatch]] in October 2010]]\nMoxley made three appearances in [[WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE) from 2006 to 2007, on television shows ''[[WWE Heat|Heat]]'' and ''[[WWE Velocity|Velocity]]'', all of which resulted in losses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=5218|title=WWE Velocity #184|work=cagematch.net|accessdate=March 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302152535/https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=5218|archive-date=March 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=6364|title=WWE Heat #407|work=cagematch.net|accessdate=March 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302152512/https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=6364|archive-date=March 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=9890|title=WWE Heat #443|work=cagematch.net|accessdate=March 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302152545/https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=9890|archive-date=March 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2006, Moxley teamed with Hade Vansen to win the [[IWA World Tag Team Championship]] in the Puerto Rico based [[International Wrestling Association (Puerto Rico)|International Wrestling Association]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070602090025if_/http://www.iwapr.tv:80/noticias/5063.php|title=IWA - Resultados: Aguadilla 09/03/06|last=Santiago|first=Luis|date=September 6, 2006|website=IWAPR.tv|language=Spanish|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref> They lost the titles to [[Carlos Cotto|Chicano]] and Jeff Jeffrey in November, ending their reign at 69 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213030643if_/http://www.iwapr.tv:80/noticias/54.php|title=IWA - Resultados: Carolina 11/11/06|last=Santiago|first=Luis|date=November 12, 2007|website=IWAPR.tv|language=Spanish|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"IWA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=261|title=IWA Puerto Rico Tag Team Championship|work=cagematch.net|accessdate=March 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302210348/https://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=261|archive-date=March 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Moxley also wrestled several [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#dark match|dark matches]] for [[Ring of Honor]] (ROH) between 2007 and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=3940&view=&page=4&gimmick=&year=&promotion=4&region=&location=&arena=&showtype=&constellationType=&worker=|title=Matches wrestled by Dean Ambrose for Ring of Honor (ROH)|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref> Moxley started working for [[Dragon Gate USA]] (DGUSA) in late 2009.<ref name=slam>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2010/05/10/13893011.html|title=Jon Moxley finds mean streets redemption in wrestling|author=Kamchen, Richard|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=May 27, 2010|date=May 27, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914130643/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2010/05/10/13893011.html|archive-date=September 14, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He made his first televised appearance in March, where he defeated [[Tommy Dreamer]] in a [[Hardcore wrestling|hardcore match]] taped for the [[DGUSA Mercury Rising|Mercury Rising]] [[pay-per-view]].<ref name=slam/> At the [[DGUSA Uprising|Uprising]] event in [[Mississauga, Ontario]], [[Canada]], Moxley suffered a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#legit|legitimate]] injury where his left nipple was nearly severed during a match with [[Jimmy Jacobs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=47415|title=Scary Injury at DGUSA PPV Taping Saturday, Lineup For Friday's Mercury Rising PPV, Lots Of Canada News And More|last=Johnson|first=Mike|publisher=PWInsider|date=May 10, 2010|accessdate=March 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427234728/http://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=47415|archive-date=April 27, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> His last match in DGUSA was against [[Homicide (wrestler)|Homicide]] in January 2011, which Moxley won.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/54813/live-ongoing-dragon-gate-usa-united-finale-coverage-akira-tozawa-defeats-bxb-hulk-in-a-career-making-motyc.html?p=1|title=Complete Dragon Gate USA United - Finale coverage: Akira Tazawa defeats BxB Hulk in a career making MOTYC, Homicide and Jon Moxley have another vicious brawl AND homicide tries to mutilate Moxley, Blood Warriors dominate, the finals of the Open the United Gate title tournament|last=Carapola|first=Stuart|date=January 30, 2011|publisher=PWInsider|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105043547/https://www.pwinsider.com/article/54813/live-ongoing-dragon-gate-usa-united-finale-coverage-akira-tozawa-defeats-bxb-hulk-in-a-career-making-motyc.html?p=1|archive-date=January 5, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt [[Full Impact Pro]]'s (FIP) Southern Stampede event on April 17, 2010, Moxley defeated [[Roderick Strong]] to win the [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#vacant|vacant]] [[FIP World Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=southernstampede2010>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/47026/full-impact-pro-southern-stampede-2010-report-new-world-champion-crowned.html?p=1|title=Full Impact Pro Southern Stampede 2010 Report: New World Champion Crowned|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=April 23, 2010|publisher=PWInsider|accessdate=May 5, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100429111445/http://www.pwinsider.com/article/47026/full-impact-pro-southern-stampede-2010-report-new-world-champion-crowned.html?p=1|archive-date=April 29, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> He held the title for 441 days before relinquishing it in July 2011, due to his signing with WWE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=235&page=2|title=Detailed \u00ab FIP World Heavyweight Championship \u00ab Titles Database \u00ab Cagematch - The Internet Wrestling Database|website=Cagematch.net|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190211141649/https://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=235&page=2|archive-date=February 11, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref> Moxley also won [[Combat Zone Wrestling]]'s [[CZW World Heavyweight Championship]] twice in 2010 by defeating [[B-Boy]]<ref name=\"slam\" /> and [[Nick Gage]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1281876168|title=Combat Zone Wrestling 8/14 \"Tangled Web 3\" results|last=Magee|first=Bob|date=August 15, 2010|publisher=WrestleView|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718121731/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1281876168|archivedate=July 18, 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=August 15, 2010}}</ref> respectively.\n\n=== World Wrestling Entertainment/WWE ===\n==== Developmental territories (2011\u20132012) ====\n[[File:Dean Ambrose NXT.JPG|thumb|upright|After signing with WWE in 2011, Ambrose competed in their developmental territory, [[Florida Championship Wrestling]]]]\nGood signed a developmental deal with WWE in April 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_49048.shtml|title=WWE/DGUSA News: Dragon Gate USA wrestler signs developmental deal with WWE|date=April 4, 2011|accessdate=April 5, 2011|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|last2=Radican|first2=Sean|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110407070902/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_49048.shtml|archive-date=April 7, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> and joined its [[Farm team#Professional wrestling|developmental territory]] [[Florida Championship Wrestling]] (FCW) under the name Dean Ambrose.<ref name=FCW>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcwwrestling.info/Roster/Dean-Ambrose.html|title=Dean Ambrose|accessdate=May 27, 2011|publisher=[[NXT Wrestling|Florida Championship Wrestling/NXT Wrestling]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Cg8SdLot?url=http://www.fcwwrestling.info/Roster/Dean-Ambrose.html|archivedate=December 5, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=DeanAmbrose>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_50401.shtml|title=WWE News: Jon Moxley's new ring name revealed in WWE's developmental system|date=May 27, 2011|last=Caldwell|first=James|accessdate=May 27, 2011|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530003130/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_50401.shtml|archive-date=May 30, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAmbrose made his televised debut on the July 3 episode of ''[[FCW (TV series)|FCW]]'' where he challenged [[FCW Jack Brisco 15 Championship|FCW Jack Brisco 15 Champion]] [[Seth Rollins]].<ref name=\"FCW\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/59601/florida-championship-wrestling-television-report-fcw-heavyweight-title-match-fcw-divas-title-match-dean-ambrose-makes-his-debut-with-a-promo-a-rotundo-family-reunion.html?p=1|title=Florida Championship Wrestling television report: FCW Heavyweight title match; FCW Divas title match; Dean Ambrose makes his debut with a promo; a Rotundo family reunion?|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=July 5, 2011|publisher=PWInsider|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225225906/http://www.pwinsider.com/article/59601/florida-championship-wrestling-television-report-fcw-heavyweight-title-match-fcw-divas-title-match-dean-ambrose-makes-his-debut-with-a-promo-a-rotundo-family-reunion.html?p=1|archive-date=February 25, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> The following month, Ambrose and Rollins had a 20-minute non-title [[Iron Man match]]; the match ended in a [[Professional wrestling#Draw|draw]] with neither man scoring a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#fall|fall]].<ref name=\"BlackMoxley\" /> A 30-minute rematch, in which the title was on the line, took place in September which Rollins won through [[Sudden death (sport)|sudden death rules]].<ref name=\"FCW\" /><ref name=\"BlackMoxley\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/61759/florida-championship-wrestling-television-report-how-do-you-top-the-first-two-rollinsambrose-matches-devote-the-entire-show-to-the-third-match-and-let-them-wrestle-for-35-minutes.html?p=|title=Florida Championship Wrestling television report: how do you top the first two Rollins/Ambrose matches? Devote the entire show to the third match and let them wrestle for 35 minutes|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=August 18, 2011|publisher=PWInsider|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603062554/http://www.pwinsider.com/article/61759/florida-championship-wrestling-television-report-how-do-you-top-the-first-two-rollinsambrose-matches-devote-the-entire-show-to-the-third-match-and-let-them-wrestle-for-35-minutes.html?p=|archive-date=June 3, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> Ambrose beat Rollins in a non-title match in the first round of a tournament to crown the new [[FCW Florida Heavyweight Championship|FCW Florida Heavyweight Champion]].<ref name=\"Namako1\"/> However, Ambrose was unsuccessful in the tournament final against [[Adam Rose|Leo Kruger]].<ref name=\"Namako1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/vip/viewnews.php?id=1318277296|title=FCW Results \u2013 10/9/11|date=October 10, 2011|last=Namako|first=Jason|accessdate=December 26, 2011|publisher=WrestleView}}</ref> Ambrose later cost Rollins his FCW 15 Championship by attacking [[Damien Sandow]] during his title match with Rollins, causing a [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualification]] in the deciding fall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1320086876|title=FCW Results \u2013 10/31/11|date=October 31, 2011|last=Namako|first=Jason|accessdate=December 26, 2011|publisher=WrestleView|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111103005410/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1320086876|archivedate=November 3, 2011}}</ref> Ambrose later unsuccessfully challenged Sandow for the championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1323715092|title=FCW Results \u2013 12/12/11|date=December 12, 2011|last=Namako|first=Jason|accessdate=December 26, 2011|publisher=WrestleView}}</ref> At an FCW [[house show]] on October 21, Ambrose challenged WWE wrestler [[CM Punk]], who was making a guest appearance, to a match in which Ambrose was defeated. Punk would later praise Ambrose after the match.<ref name=FCW/><ref>{{cite web|title=10/21 FCW results Kissimmee, Fla.: Punk vs. Moxley main event, NXT Rookies, Brodus discloses TV return, WWE developmental notes|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_54471.shtml|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=November 15, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124033932/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_54471.shtml|archive-date=November 24, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAmbrose would then began a [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] with [[William Regal]], after Ambrose targeted Regal in an unprovoked attack.<ref name=FCW/> They would wrestle on the November 7 episode of ''FCW'', with Regal winning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1320688530|title=FCW Results \u2013 11/7/11|date=November 7, 2011|last=Namako|first=Jason|accessdate=December 26, 2011|publisher=WrestleView}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.profightdb.com/wrestlers/dean-ambrose-3069.html?prom_id=59|title=FCW matches wrestled by Dean Ambrose|website=The Internet Wrestling Database|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107015743/http://www.profightdb.com/wrestlers/dean-ambrose-3069.html?prom_id=59|archive-date=January 7, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 6, 2019}}</ref> For the next year, Ambrose would obsessively request for another match with Regal.<ref name=\"FCW226\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/66275/florida-championship-wrestling-television-report-for-226-sandowsteamboat-for-the-fcw-15-title-dean-ambrose-gets-inside-a-few-peoples-heads.html?p=1|title=Florida Championship Wrestling television report for 2/26: Sandow/Steamboat for the FCW 15 title; Dean Ambrose gets inside a few people's heads|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|date=February 29, 2012|publisher=PWInsider|accessdate=March 16, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225225901/http://www.pwinsider.com/article/66275/florida-championship-wrestling-television-report-for-226-sandowsteamboat-for-the-fcw-15-title-dean-ambrose-gets-inside-a-few-peoples-heads.html?p=1|archive-date=February 25, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 7, Ambrose competed at tapings for an unaired [[Television pilot|pilot]] for ''[[WWE NXT]]'' under the working title ''Full Sail Ahead'' at [[Full Sail University]], where he was defeated by Leo Kruger.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=182859|title=WWE NXT Full Sail Ahead \u00ab Events Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|website=Cagematch.net|access-date=January 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190211141649/https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=182859|archive-date=February 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the February 5, 2012 episode of ''FCW'', Ambrose faced Rollins and [[Roman Reigns|Leakee]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic non-elimination matches|triple threat match]] to determine the number one contender for the FCW Florida Heavyweight Championship; the match however was won by Leakee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/30212-fcw-results-2-6-12/|title=FCW Results \u2013 2/6/12|date=February 6, 2012|last=Namako|first=Jason|accessdate=April 1, 2012|publisher=WrestleView|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321085809/https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/30212-fcw-results-2-6-12/|archive-date=March 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2012, Ambrose had a confrontation with veteran hardcore wrestler [[Mick Foley]], claiming that Foley needed to be held accountable for creating a generation of imitators.<ref>{{cite web|last=Caldwell|first=James|title=Video \u2013 FCW wrestler confronts Foley at WrestleMania Hotel|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/quicknews/article_59969.shtml|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=April 11, 2012}}</ref> Ambrose continued to antagonize Foley through [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Caldwell|first=James|title=Foley-Ambrose \"feud\" continues|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/quicknews/article_60191.shtml|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=April 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Caldwell|first=James|title=Foley had Ambrose sent home?|url= http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/quicknews/article_60239.shtml|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=April 14, 2012}}</ref> According to Ambrose, the [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#angle|angle]] was supposed to culminate in a match between the two, but this never came to fruition due to Foley not being medically allowed to wrestle.<ref>{{cite podcast|url=https://omny.fm/shows/talk-is-jericho/tij-ep99-wwes-dean-ambrose-pt2|title=Dean Ambrose on Talk is Jericho|first=Christopher|last=Irvine|authorlink=Chris Jericho|date=December 13, 2014|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref> Instead, the rivalry was scrapped and Ambrose remained in WWE's developmental system. He competed in a dark match at the first tapings of ''NXT'' on May 17, in a loss to [[Xavier Woods]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=81410|title=WWE NXT #1 \u00ab Events Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|website=Cagematch.net|access-date=January 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016215206/http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=81410|archive-date=October 16, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> On an episode of ''FCW'' in June, Ambrose challenged Rollins for the FCW Florida Heavyweight Championship but lost.<ref>{{cite web|date=June 27, 2012|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|title=Florida Championship Wrestling television report 6/24: Rollins/Ambrose V|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/69670/florida-championship-wrestling-television-report-624-rollinsambrose-v.html?p=1|publisher=PWInsider|accessdate=July 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224102543/http://www.pwinsider.com/article/69670/florida-championship-wrestling-television-report-624-rollinsambrose-v.html?p=1|archive-date=December 24, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Almost a year after their first match, Ambrose and Regal rematched on the final episode of ''FCW'' on July 15. The match would conclude in a [[Professional wrestling#No contest|no contest]] after Ambrose repeatedly kneed Regal's head into a ring [[turnbuckle]], causing Regal to bleed from the ear.<ref>{{cite web|last=Trionfo|first=Richard|title=FCW Television report 7/15: The series ends not with a whimper or a bang... it ends with a Knee Trembler|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=70313|publisher=PWInsider|accessdate=July 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== The Shield (2012\u20132014) ====\n{{Main|The Shield (professional wrestling)|l1=The Shield}}\n[[File:The Shield WWE.jpg|thumb|left|Ambrose (center) debuted on the main roster as part of [[The Shield (professional wrestling)|The Shield]] in 2012]]\nOn November 18, 2012, Ambrose made his WWE main roster debut at the [[Survivor Series (2012)|Survivor Series]] pay-per-view [[List of WWE pay-per-view events|event]] alongside [[Roman Reigns]] and Seth Rollins, as they delivered a [[Professional wrestling double-team maneuvers#Aided powerbomb|triple powerbomb]] through an announce table to [[Ryback]] during the triple threat main event for the [[WWE Championship]], allowing CM Punk to [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pin]] [[John Cena]] and retain the title.<ref>{{cite web|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=November 18, 2012|title=Survivor Series News: NXT stars debut in PPV main event angle, plus other news from annual PPV|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_66716.shtml|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=November 19, 2012|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FLOZEePT?url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_66716.shtml|archive-date=March 23, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The trio declared themselves [[The Shield (professional wrestling)|The Shield]], vowed to rally against \"injustice\" and denied working for Punk, but they routinely emerged from the crowd to attack Punk's adversaries, including Ryback and the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Tag Team Champions]] [[Team Hell No]] ([[Daniel Bryan]] and [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]]), establishing themselves as [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villains]].<ref name=Raw1119>{{cite web|date=November 19, 2012|title=Caldwell's WWE Raw Results 11/19: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live Raw \u2013 Survivor Series fall-out|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_66731.shtml|accessdate=December 5, 2012|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|last=Caldwell|first=James|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FLOaAXH9?url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_66731.shtml|archive-date=March 23, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw1126\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_66855.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE Raw Results 11/26: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live Raw \u2013 The Shield speaks, Cena-Ziggler|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=November 26, 2012|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FLOarUqt?url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_66855.shtml|archive-date=March 23, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=December 5, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_66980.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE Raw Results 12/3: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live Raw \u2013 McMahon returns, Punk takes a Test|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=December 3, 2012|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FLObW5XH?url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_66980.shtml|archive-date=March 23, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=December 5, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_66817.shtml|title=WWE News: WWE officially announces TLC main event change; will Ryback still get a WWE Title shot?|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=December 4, 2012|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FLOcAZSa?url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_66817.shtml|archive-date=March 23, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=December 5, 2012}}</ref> This led to a six-man [[Tables, Ladders, and Chairs match]] being set up for the [[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2012)|TLC]] pay-per-view event on December 16, where Ambrose, Rollins, and Reigns defeated Ryback and Team Hell No in their debut match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_67280.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE TLC PPV Results 12/16: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of final 2012 PPV \u2013 Cena vs. Ziggler main event, Shield makes a statement|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=December 16, 2012|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FLOd3VpD?url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_67280.shtml|archive-date=March 23, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=December 17, 2012}}</ref> The Shield continued to aid Punk after TLC, both on ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' and at the [[Royal Rumble (2013)|Royal Rumble]] in January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_67712.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE Raw Results 1/7: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live Raw \u2013 WWE Title match, The Rock returns, Cena vs. Ziggler (updated w/Box Score)|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=January 7, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FLOdhKPe?url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_67712.shtml|archive-date=March 23, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_68181.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE Royal Rumble PPV Results 1/27: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Punk vs. Rock, 30-man Rumble|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=January 27, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FzQqBFLC?url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_68181.shtml|archive-date=April 19, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> The night after the Royal Rumble, it was revealed through footage that Punk and his manager [[Paul Heyman]] had been paying The Shield to work for them all along.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_68224.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE Raw Results 1/28: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live Raw \u2013 Huge Return ends Raw, Rock's first night as WWE champ, Raw Roulette, Heyman-McMahon|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=January 28, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FLOey3gZ?url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_68224.shtml|archive-date=March 23, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> The Shield then quietly ended their association with Punk. At [[Elimination Chamber (2013)|Elimination Chamber]] in February, The Shield defeated Ryback, John Cena and [[Sheamus]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_68713.shtml|title= CALDWELL'S WWE ELIMINATION CHAMBER PPV RESULTS 2/17: Complete 'virtual-time' coverage of Rock-Punk II, Elimination Chamber match, Shield beats Team Cena|first= James|last= Caldwell|work= pwtorch.com|date= February 17, 2013|accessdate= November 27, 2015|archive-url= https://www.webcitation.org/6FzQrbGkR?url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_68713.shtml|archive-date= April 19, 2013|url-status= live|df= mdy-all}}</ref> At [[WrestleMania 29]] in April, The Shield won their first [[WrestleMania]] match against Sheamus, [[Randy Orton]] and [[Big Show]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_69509.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE Raw Results 3/25: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live Raw \u2013 Rock returns for Q&A debate with Cena, Hunter punts Barrett, latest WM29 hype|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=March 25, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526014154/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_69509.shtml|archive-date=May 26, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_69830.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE WrestleMania 29 PPV Results: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live PPV from MetLife Stadium \u2013 Rock-Cena II, Taker-Punk, Lesnar-Hunter, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=April 7, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6GGIbi9oY?url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_69830.shtml|archive-date=April 30, 2013|url-status=live|access-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref> Ambrose made his singles debut against [[The Undertaker]] on the April 26 episode of [[WWE SmackDown|''SmackDown'']], which he lost by [[Professional wrestling#Submission|submission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2013/04/26/20774066.html|title=Smackdown!:The Undertaker returns to Friday night action|last=Plummer|first=Dale|date=April 26, 2013|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724212830/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2013/04/26/20774066.html|archive-date=July 24, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=May 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/why-has-the-shield-been-unbeatable-26112192/page-3|title=Why hasn't The Shield been beaten yet? They work cohesively|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=May 2, 2013|publisher=[[WWE]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Gr3wApze?url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/why-has-the-shield-been-unbeatable-26112192/page-3|archivedate=May 24, 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref> On the May 13 episode of ''Raw'', The Shield's undefeated streak as a team ended in a disqualification loss against WWE Champion John Cena and Team Hell No.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_70573.shtml|title=Raw News: Shield loses first match, Lesnar's \"mystique\" now in-play, Dolph off TV, Miz returns, Dance-Off, App overload, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=May 13, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608055731/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_70573.shtml|archive-date=June 8, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=May 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United States Champion Dean Ambrose 2.jpg|thumb|right|upright|From May 2013 to May 2014, Ambrose held the [[WWE United States Championship|United States Championship]] and became the longest reigning champion under the WWE banner]]\nAt [[Extreme Rules (2013)|Extreme Rules]], Ambrose won the [[WWE United States Championship|United States Championship]] by defeating [[Kofi Kingston]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2013/05/19/20834561.html|title=Lesnar finishes off Triple H at Extreme Rules|last=Bishop|first=Matt|date=May 19, 2013|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607041734/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2013/05/19/20834561.html|archive-date=June 7, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}</ref> He would successfully defend the title in the following weeks with the help of Reigns and Rollins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwesmackdownreport/article_70839.shtml|title=Parks' WWE SmackDown Report 5/24: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Friday show, including the Intercontinental and U.S. Titles on the line, plus PPV fall-out|last=Parks|first=Greg|date=May 24, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401093528/https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwesmackdownreport/article_70839.shtml|archive-date=April 1, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_70879.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE Raw Results 5/27 (Hour 1): Ongoing \"virtual-time\" coverage of live Memorial Day Raw \u2013 Cena returns, U.S. Title match, Bret Hart cameo|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=May 27, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401093518/https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_70879.shtml|archive-date=April 1, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> On the June 14 episode of ''SmackDown'', The Shield was given their first decisive loss, against Randy Orton and Team Hell No, when Daniel Bryan made Rollins submit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_71216.shtml|title=WWE News: Significant Smackdown Spoiler for Friday's episode (w/Analysis of potential fall-out scenarios)|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=June 11, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615235321/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_71216.shtml|archive-date=June 15, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=June 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2013/06/14/20901596.html|title=Smackdown!: The Shield handed their first loss heading into Payback|last=Plummer|first=Dale|date=June 14, 2013|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054444/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2013/06/14/20901596.html|archive-date=September 21, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=June 15, 2013}}</ref> Two days later, Ambrose made his first pay-per-view defense of the United States Championship at [[Payback (2013)|Payback]], where he defeated Kane by [[Professional wrestling#Countout|countout]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2013/06/16/20904366.html|title=WWE hits home run with Payback|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canoe.com|Canadian Online Explorer]]|first=Matt|last=Bishop|date=June 16, 2013|accessdate=March 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306043146/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2013/06/16/20904366.html|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The following month at [[Money in the Bank (2013)|Money in the Bank]], he competed in the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]] [[Money in the Bank ladder match]] but failed to win despite interference from Reigns and Rollins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_71942.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE MITB PPV Results 7/14 (Hour 1): Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of World Title MITB ladder match, IC Title match, Divas Title match|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=July 24, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718070326/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_71942.shtml|archive-date=July 18, 2013|url-status=live|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> In August, The Shield allied themselves with [[Triple H]] and joined his group [[The Authority (professional wrestling)|The Authority]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2013/08/20/21059971.html|title=Raw: Daniel Bryan faces an even bigger uphill climb|date=August 20, 2013|last=Tylwalk|first=Nick|accessdate=June 30, 2014|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2013/08/26/21076926.html|title=Raw: Bryan's road through Hell continues|date=August 26, 2013|last=Asher|first=Matthew|accessdate=June 30, 2014|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref>\n\nAmbrose continued to retain his United States Championship against [[Rob Van Dam]] at [[SummerSlam (2013)|SummerSlam]],<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2013/08/18/21055921.html|title=Live coverage: WWE SummerSlam 2013|last=Bishop|first=Matt|work=Slam! Sports|accessdate=August 31, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725020314/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2013/08/18/21055921.html|archive-date=July 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Dolph Ziggler]] at [[Night of Champions (2013)|Night of Champions]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/43820-wwe-night-of-champions-ppv-results-9-15-13-orton-vs-bryan|title=WWE Night of Champions PPV Results \u2013 9/15/13 (Orton vs Bryan)|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=September 13, 2013|publisher=WrestleView|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130917223915/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/43820-wwe-night-of-champions-ppv-results-9-15-13-orton-vs-bryan|archive-date=September 17, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=September 18, 2013}}</ref> and [[Big E (wrestler)|Big E Langston]] at [[Hell in a Cell (2013)|Hell in a Cell]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_74178.shtml#.XEYPbWlRfIU|title=Caldwell's WWE HIAC PPV Review (Hour 1): Tag Title match opens the PPV, U.S. Title match, Summer Rae debut|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=October 27, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121233128/https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_74178.shtml#.XEYPbWlRfIU|archive-date=January 21, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 21, 2019}}</ref> At the [[Survivor Series (2013)|Survivor Series]] pay-per-view, The Shield teamed with [[Cesaro (wrestler)|Antonio Cesaro]] and [[Jack Swagger]] to take on [[Rey Mysterio]], [[The Usos]], [[Cody Rhodes and Goldust]] in a traditional [[Survivor Series match]]; although Ambrose was the first man eliminated, Reigns would ultimately win the match for the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_74736.shtml|title=WWE S. Series PPV results 11/24 (Hour 1): Team Shield vs. Team Rhodes & Rey Survivor Series match, IC Title match|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=November 24, 2013|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131128004231/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_74736.shtml|archive-date=November 28, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=November 25, 2013}}</ref> At [[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2013)|TLC]] in December, CM Punk defeated The Shield in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|handicap match]] after Ambrose was accidentally [[Professional wrestling attacks#Spear|speared]] by Reigns.<ref>{{cite web|last=Howell|first=Nolan|title=TLC: Randy Orton crowned new WWE World Heavyweight Champion|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2013/12/15/21339031.html|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=December 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219075253/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2013/12/15/21339031.html|archive-date=February 19, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[Royal Rumble (2014)|Royal Rumble]] on January 26, 2014, Ambrose entered his first [[Royal Rumble match]] at number 11 and eliminated three participants, before being eliminated by Reigns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/2014/royal-rumble-match|title=Batista won the 30-Man Royal Rumble Match|last=Linder|first=Zach|publisher=[[WWE]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112020046/http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/2014/royal-rumble-match|archive-date=January 12, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', The Shield faced Daniel Bryan, John Cena, and Sheamus in order to earn their spot in the [[Elimination Chamber|Elimination Chamber match]] for the WWE World Heavyweight Championship. The Shield lost after [[The Wyatt Family]] ([[Bray Wyatt]], [[Erick Rowan]], and [[Luke Harper]]) interfered, thus starting a feud between the two factions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_75919.shtml|title=WWE Royal Rumble PPV results 1/26 (Hour 3): Royal Rumble vs. The Crowd main event match|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=January 26, 2014|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201005455/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_75919.shtml|archive-date=February 1, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=January 28, 2014}}</ref> The Shield would lose to The Wyatt Family at the [[Elimination Chamber (2014)|Elimination Chamber]] pay-per-view, due to Ambrose abandoning the match midway through.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_76567.shtml|title=WWE E. Chamber PPV results 2/23 (Hour 2): Shield vs. Wyatts big six-man tag, Batista vs. Del Rio, Divas Title|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=February 23, 2014|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227060017/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_76567.shtml|archive-date=February 27, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=February 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter their feud with The Wyatt Family, The Shield moved on to a rivalry with Kane, turning into [[Face (professional wrestling)|heroic characters]] in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/kellerstake/article_77088.shtml|title=Keller's Six Pack: Raw thoughts including Hunter-Bryan beat down, Batista, Shield's turn, Bray's gimmick shift, more|last=Keller|first=Wade|date=March 12, 2014|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326055728/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/kellerstake/article_77088.shtml|archive-date=March 26, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=March 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwesmackdownreport/article_77164.shtml|title=Parks's WWE SmackDown Report 3/21: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Friday show, including Cena vs. Harper|last=Parks|first=Greg|date=March 21, 2014|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322140659/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwesmackdownreport/article_77164.shtml|archive-date=March 22, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=March 22, 2014}}</ref> The group defeated Kane and [[New Age Outlaws]] ([[Road Dogg]] and [[Billy Gunn]]) at [[WrestleMania XXX]] on April 6.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_77520.shtml|title=WrestleMania 30 PPV results: (Hour 2): Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Cena vs. Bray, big moment for Cesaro in the Andre Battle Royal, Shield vs. Outlaws|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=April 6, 2014|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410073537/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_77520.shtml|archive-date=April 10, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> The feud with Kane also prompted The Shield to cease working for Triple H, who reformed [[Evolution (professional wrestling)|Evolution]] with himself, [[Dave Bautista|Batista]] and Randy Orton to battle them.<ref>{{cite web|last=McCarron|first=Rob|title=WWE Raw TV report \u2013 April 14, 2014|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/36482|accessdate=May 23, 2014}}</ref> On April 28, Ambrose surpassed [[Montel Vontavious Porter|MVP]] as the longest-reigning United States Champion under the WWE banner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/dean-ambrose-longest-reigning-united-states-champions/page-9|title=Ambrose's record U.S. Title reign|last=Melok|first=Bobby|date=January 31, 2014|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617182136/http://www.wwe.com/inside/dean-ambrose-longest-reigning-united-states-champions/page-9|archive-date=June 17, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> The Shield defeated Evolution in a six-man tag team match at [[Extreme Rules (2014)|Extreme Rules]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_78185.shtml|title=Caldwell's Extreme Rules PPV results 5/4: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live PPV \u2013 Bryan vs. Kane, Evolution vs. Shield, Cena vs. Wyatt steel cage match|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=May 4, 2014|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506113832/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_78185.shtml|archivedate=May 6, 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=May 6, 2014}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Triple H forced Ambrose to defend his United States Championship in a 20-man [[battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]], which saw Ambrose surviving until the final two before ultimately being eliminated by Sheamus, thus ending his title reign at 351 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_78209.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE Raw results 5/5: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live Raw \u2013 PPV fall-out, U.S. Title battle royal, IC Title re-match, Shield vs. Wyatts, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=May 5, 2014|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140510013806/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_78209.shtml|archive-date=May 10, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=May 23, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Asher|first=Matthew|title=Mat Matters: Temporarily shelving the YES! Movement IS what's best for business|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/MatMatters/2014/05/21/21687231.html|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=May 23, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523225709/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/MatMatters/2014/05/21/21687231.html|archive-date=May 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The Shield once again defeated Evolution at [[Payback (2014)|Payback]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#No Holds Barred match|No Holds Barred]] [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Elimination tag team matches|elimination match]] in June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2014/06/01/21710506.html|title=WWE Payback: The Shield Evolved, Cena stood tall and Brie dropped a bombshell|last=Asher|first=Matthew|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703173917/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2014/06/01/21710506.html|archive-date=July 3, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=June 8, 2014}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Rollins betrayed Ambrose and Reigns and aligned himself with The Authority, breaking up the group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/06/03/21714336.html|title=Raw: Changing of the Shield|date=June 3, 2014|last=Waldman|first=Jon|accessdate=June 23, 2014|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706052937/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/06/03/21714336.html|archive-date=July 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Feud with Seth Rollins (2014\u20132015) ====\n[[File:Ambrose-Rollins NoC14.jpg|thumb|After The Shield's split in June 2014, Ambrose began a prolonged feud with Seth Rollins]]\nAmbrose promptly began feuding with Rollins, which included the duo interfering in each other's matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/06/17/21745461.html|title=Raw: Money in the Bank title match gets its last two participants|last=Tylwalk|first=Nick|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706070057/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/06/17/21745461.html|archive-date=July 6, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=June 23, 2014}}</ref> During this period, Ambrose and Reigns amicably separated as a team, with Ambrose debuting new ring attire and new entrance music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/06/20/21756216.html|title=Smackdown!: Money in the Bank challengers prepare with a 7 man tag match|last=Plummer|first=Dale|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706071218/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/06/20/21756216.html|archive-date=July 6, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=June 23, 2014}}</ref> Ambrose competed the [[Money in the Bank (2014)|2014 Money in the Bank ladder match]] on June 29, which Rollins would win after Kane attacked Ambrose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2014/06/29/21774111.html|title=Cena takes authority of the WWE title at Money in the Bank|last=Howell|first=Nolan|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140706124750/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2014/06/29/21774111.html|archive-date=July 6, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref> Ambrose was scheduled to face Rollins at [[Battleground (2014)|Battleground]] on July 20, but he was ejected from the arena by Triple H after a pre-match brawl with Rollins. Rollins was later announced as the winner via [[Professional wrestling#Forfeit|forfeit]], prompting Ambrose to return to the arena and attack Rollins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwebattleground/2014/dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-26462754|title=Seth Rollins def. Dean Ambrose by forfeit|last=Wortman|first=James|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714173012/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwebattleground/2014/dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-26462754|archive-date=July 14, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=June 29, 2014}}</ref> Ambrose and Rollins eventually wrestled at [[SummerSlam (2014)|SummerSlam]] on August 17 in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Lumberjack match|lumberjack match]], which Ambrose lost after Kane again interfered and Rollins hit Ambrose with his Money in the Bank briefcase.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/08/18/21880261.html|title=Heels rule, Lesnar runs rampant at SummerSlam 2014|last=Plummer|first=Dale|last2=Tylwalk|first2=Nick|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331042759/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/08/18/21880261.html|archive-date=March 31, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Ambrose faced Rollins in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls Count Anywhere match|Falls Count Anywhere match]], which Ambrose lost by knockout after interference from Kane once again. After the match, Rollins [[Professional wrestling attacks#Curb stomp|curb stomped]] his head through cinder blocks, giving Ambrose [[kayfabe]] \"head and spine trauma\" and causing him to take a hiatus from WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2014-08-18/wwe-raw-results-26579583/page-10|title=Seth Rollins def. Dean Ambrose in a WWE App Vote Match|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822083846/http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2014-08-18/wwe-raw-results-26579583/page-10|archive-date=August 22, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=August 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/50264-wwe-raw-results-8-18-14-live-results-from-las-vegas|title=WWE Raw Results \u2013 8/18/14 (Fallout from SummerSlam)|last1=Nemar|first1=Paul|date=August 19, 2014|publisher=WrestleView|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140825001414/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/50264-wwe-raw-results-8-18-14-live-results-from-las-vegas|archive-date=August 25, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2014-08-18/dean-ambrose-injured-on-raw-refuses-treatment|title=Dean Ambrose injured on Raw, refuses treatment|publisher=WWE|date=August 19, 2014}}</ref> Ambrose returned at [[Night of Champions (2014)|Night of Champions]] in September and attacked Rollins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/09/22/21956636.html|title=Night of Champions, recycled goods|last=Powell|first=Jason|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626220759/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/09/22/21956636.html|archive-date=June 26, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=September 22, 2014}}</ref> The duo faced off in a [[Hell in a Cell|Hell in a Cell match]] the following month at the [[Hell in a Cell (2014)|namesake event]], where Ambrose lost again when the returning Bray Wyatt interfered and attacked him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/10/26/22031761.html|title=Cena and Rollins survive Cell stipulations|last=Asher|first=Matthew|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626233204/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2014/10/26/22031761.html|archive-date=June 26, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=October 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dean Ambrose 2015.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Ambrose in January 2015]]\nAfter consecutive losses to Wyatt at the [[Survivor Series (2014)|Survivor Series]] and [[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2014)|TLC]] pay-per-views,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2014/11/24/22091341.html|title=WWE Survivor Series: The Authority feels the Sting of defeat|last=Kapur|first=Bob|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627065019/http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/PPVReports/2014/11/24/22091341.html|archive-date=June 27, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=November 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_82280.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE TLC PPV Report 12/14: Ongoing \"virtual-time\" coverage of Cena vs. Rollins, Ambrose vs. Wyatt, more|author=Caldwell, James|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=December 14, 2014|accessdate=December 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141215063101/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_82280.shtml|archive-date=December 15, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Ambrose defeated Wyatt in a [[Professional wrestling match types#No Disqualification Match|Boot Camp Match]] at [[WWE Tribute to the Troops results#2014|''Tribute to the Troops'']],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/52199-wwe-tribute-to-the-troops-results-12-17-14-usa-special/|title=WWE Tribute to the Troops Results \u2013 12/17/14 (USA Special)|publisher=WrestleView|first=Mike|last=Tedesco|date=December 17, 2014|accessdate=December 17, 2014}}</ref> before losing to Wyatt yet again in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Miracle on 34th Street Fight|Miracle on 34th Street Fight]] on the December 22 episode of ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_82416.shtml|title=CALDWELL'S WWE RAW RESULTS 12/22: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live Raw - Hulk Hogan guest-hosts, Piper's Pit, IC Title, Cena vs. Rollins, Street Fight re-re-re-match, more|date=December 22, 2014|accessdate=December 22, 2014|website=Pro Wrestling Torch|last=Caldwell|first=James|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224174007/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_82416.shtml|archive-date=December 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The feud between the two concluded when Wyatt defeated Ambrose in an [[Professional wrestling match types#Ambulance match|ambulance match]] on the January 5, 2015 episode of ''Raw''.<ref name=\"shouldmore\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_82604.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE Raw results 1/5: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live Raw \u2013 Ambrose vs. Wyatt ambulance match, The Authority returns, Cena Appreciation Night, more|date=January 5, 2015|accessdate=January 26, 2015|author=Caldwell, James|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106074618/http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_82604.shtml|archive-date=January 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[Royal Rumble (2015)|Royal Rumble]] on January 25, Ambrose participated in the Royal Rumble match, but was eliminated by Big Show and Kane.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_82945.shtml|title=Caldwell's Royal Rumble PPV report 1/25: Ongoing \"virtual-time\" coverage of Lesnar vs. Cena vs. Rollins for WWE Title, annual Royal Rumble match, more|date=January 25, 2015|accessdate=January 25, 2015|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|author=Caldwell, James|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150127230727/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_82945.shtml|archive-date=January 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Ambrose then began a feud with [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Champion]] [[Wade Barrett|Bad News Barrett]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tedesco|first1=Mike|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 2/16/15 (Bryan and Reigns in action)|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/53063-wwe-raw-results-2-16-15-live-results-from-orlando|publisher=WrestleView.com|accessdate=February 17, 2015|date=February 17, 2015}}</ref> He failed to win the championship from Barrett at [[Fastlane (2015)|Fastlane]] and [[WrestleMania 31]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_83486.shtml|title=Caldwell's WWE Fast Lane PPV Results 2/22|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=February 22, 2015|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=February 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223050336/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_83486.shtml|archive-date=February 23, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_84175.shtml|title=Caldwell's WM31 PPV results 3/29: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of WWE World Title match, Taker's return, Sting vs. Triple H, Cena vs. Rusev, Rock/UFC surprise, more|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=March 29, 2015|accessdate=March 30, 2015|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331225800/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_84175.shtml|archive-date=March 31, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Ambrose defeated Luke Harper at [[Extreme Rules (2015)|Extreme Rules]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Street fight|Chicago Street Fight]] on April 26, his first singles victory on a pay-per-view event since The Shield split up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_84687.shtml#.VT2oBZPm6aE|title=Caldwell's Extreme Rules PPV Report 4/26: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of live PPV - Rollins vs. Orton steel cage, Cena vs. Rusev, Last Man Standing, more|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|date=April 26, 2015|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427183338/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_84687.shtml#.VT2oBZPm6aE|archive-date=April 27, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Ambrose competed in the [[King of the Ring (2015)|2015 King of the Ring]] tournament, but was disqualified from the competition during his quarterfinal match with Sheamus, after interference from Dolph Ziggler.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tedesco|first1=Mike|title=WWE RAW Results - 4/27/15 (Payback main event set)|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/54206-wwe-raw-results-4-27-15-live-results-from-green-bay|website=wrestleview.com|accessdate=April 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802170339/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/54206-wwe-raw-results-4-27-15-live-results-from-green-bay/|archive-date=August 2, 2017|url-status=live|date=April 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAmbrose returned to feud with Rollins over the WWE World Heavyweight Championship, defeating him in a non-title match on the May 4 episode of ''Raw''. As a result of this, he was added to Rollins's championship defense at [[Payback (2015)|Payback]] against Randy Orton and Roman Reigns.<ref name=\"raw5042015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/54301-wwe-raw-results-5-4-15-live-results-from-montreal|title=WWE Raw Results - 5/4/15 (Changes to Payback main event)|last1=Nemer|first1=Paul|date=May 5, 2015|publisher=WrestleView|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505061441/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/54301-wwe-raw-results-5-4-15-live-results-from-montreal|archive-date=May 5, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> Rollins would retain his championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwepayback/2015/wwe-world-heavyweight-champion-seth-rollins-roman-reigns-randy-orton-dean-ambrose-27335106|title=WWE World Heavyweight Champion Seth Rollins won a Fatal 4-Way Match|last1=Murphy|first1=Ryan|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205173502/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwepayback/2015/wwe-world-heavyweight-champion-seth-rollins-roman-reigns-randy-orton-dean-ambrose-27335106|archive-date=December 5, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> At [[Elimination Chamber (2015)|Elimination Chamber]] on May 31, Ambrose faced Rollins in a singles match for the championship. He won the match by disqualification after Rollins shoved the [[Referee (professional wrestling)|referee]], but did not win the title, as championships cannot change hands by disqualification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/eliminationchamber/2015/seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-27407200|title=Dean Ambrose def. WWE World Heavyweight Champion Seth Rollins via Disqualification|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527030706/http://www.wwe.com/shows/eliminationchamber/2015/seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-27407200|archive-date=May 27, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=May 31, 2015}}</ref> Regardless, Ambrose stole the [[championship belt]] from him and challenged Rollins to a [[ladder match]] for the title at [[Money in the Bank (2015)|Money in the Bank]] on June 14, which he narrowly lost.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/moneyinthebank/2015/seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-ladder-match-27453310|title=WWE World Heavyweight Champion Seth Rollins def. Dean Ambrose|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617083909/http://www.wwe.com/shows/moneyinthebank/2015/seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-ladder-match-27453310|archive-date=June 17, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter Money in the Bank, Ambrose teamed up with Roman Reigns to defeat Wyatt and Harper at [[SummerSlam (2015)|SummerSlam]].<ref name=\"SSlam2015\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_87122.shtml|title=Caldwell's SummerSlam Report 8/23: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Lesnar vs. Taker, Title vs. Title, more matches|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|date=August 23, 2015|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904175855/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_87122.shtml|archive-date=September 4, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=August 23, 2015}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Ambrose and Reigns fought Wyatt and Harper in a SummerSlam rematch, during which [[Braun Strowman]] made his WWE debut, helping Harper and Wyatt.<ref name=\"RAW8242015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/55897-wwe-raw-results-8-24-15-live-results-from-brooklyn|title=WWE Raw Results - 8/24/15 (The Dudleys, Sting return)|last1=Namako|first1=Jason|date=August 25, 2015|publisher=WrestleView|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150825151407/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/55897-wwe-raw-results-8-24-15-live-results-from-brooklyn|archive-date=August 25, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref> At [[Night of Champions (2015)|Night of Champions]] on September 20, Ambrose, Reigns and a returning [[Chris Jericho]] were defeated by Wyatt, Harper, and Strowman in a six-man tag team match.<ref>{{cite web|last=Keller|first=Wade|authorlink=Wade Keller|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_87597.shtml|title=Keller's WWE Night of Champions PPV Report 9/20|date=September 20, 2015|accessdate=September 25, 2015|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923222739/http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_87597.shtml|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> After Rollins legitimately injured his knee on November 3, the WWE World Heavyweight Championship was declared vacant; Ambrose entered a 16-man tournament to determine a new champion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seth Rollins suffers knee injury, new WWE World Heavyweight Champion to be crowned at Survivor Series|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/seth-rollins-injury-title-tournament-survivor-series-28164051|publisher=[[WWE]]|author=WWE Staff|accessdate=November 5, 2015|date=November 5, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106023300/http://www.wwe.com/inside/seth-rollins-injury-title-tournament-survivor-series-28164051|archivedate=November 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> After defeating [[Tyler Breeze]] in the first round,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tedesco|first1=Mike|title=WWE Raw Results - 11/9/15 (WWE Title Tournament starts)|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/56836-wwe-raw-results-11-9-15-full-coverage-from-manchester|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=November 11, 2015|date=November 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151112083914/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/56836-wwe-raw-results-11-9-15-full-coverage-from-manchester|archive-date=November 12, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Dolph Ziggler in the quarterfinals<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tedesco|first1=Mike|title=WWE Raw Results - 11/16/15 (Final Survivor Series hype)|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/56905-wwe-raw-results-11-16-15-live-results-from-greenville|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=November 17, 2015|date=November 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117192549/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/56905-wwe-raw-results-11-16-15-live-results-from-greenville|archive-date=November 17, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Kevin Owens]] in the semifinals,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Melok|first1=Bobby|title=Dean Ambrose def. Kevin Owens (WWE World Heavyweight Championship Tournament Semifinals)|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2015/dean-ambrose-kevin-owens-28201140|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=November 22, 2015|date=November 22, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120003038/http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2015/dean-ambrose-kevin-owens-28201140|archive-date=November 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Ambrose ultimately made it to the finals at the [[Survivor Series (2015)|Survivor Series]] main event on November 22 but lost to Reigns.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murphy|first1=Ryan|title=Roman Reigns def. Dean Ambrose in the WWE World Heavyweight Championship Tournament Final Match; Sheamus cashed in his Money in the Bank contract to become WWE World Heavyweight Champion|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2015/wwe-world-heavyweight-championship-tournament-finals-28164052|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=November 22, 2015|date=November 22, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121050307/http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2015/wwe-world-heavyweight-championship-tournament-finals-28164052|archive-date=November 21, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Championship reigns (2015\u20132017) ====\n[[File:Dean Ambrose December 2016.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Ambrose in December 2016]]\n{{quote box\n| width = 25%\n| align = right\n| quote = \"Crowd was more into Ambrose than [Roman] Reigns... Why does Ambrose continue to do more [[Job (professional wrestling)|job]]s when he's the most [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#over|over]] [[Face (professional wrestling)|babyface]] they have?\".\n| source = ''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'' writer Jeff Hamlin on Ambrose's recent losses in relation to his popularity with WWE audiences<ref>{{cite web|title=WWE Raw live results 11-30: the build towards TLC with Roman Reigns and Sheamus|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-raw-live-results-11-30-build-towards-tlc-roman-reigns-and-sheamus-202706|date=November 30, 2015|accessdate=December 24, 2015|work=[[Wrestling Observer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225033645/http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-raw-live-results-11-30-build-towards-tlc-roman-reigns-and-sheamus-202706|archive-date=December 25, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}\nIn December, Ambrose won the Intercontinental Championship for the first time after defeating Owens at [[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2015)|TLC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwetlc/2015/wwe-tlc-2015-results-28352302|title=WWE TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs 2015 results|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151215124114/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwetlc/2015/wwe-tlc-2015-results-28352302|archive-date=December 15, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> He successfully defended the title against Owens and Ziggler multiple times between December and January 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-smackdown-results/57235-wwe-smackdown-results-12-22-15-live-from-des-moines|title=WWE SmackDown results - 12/22/15 (IC Title Main event)|last1=Martin|first1=Adam|date=December 23, 2015|publisher=WrestleView|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112104635/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-smackdown-results/57235-wwe-smackdown-results-12-22-15-live-from-des-moines|archive-date=January 12, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=January 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-smackdown-results/57364-wwe-smackdown-results-1-7-16-ambrose-vs-owens|title=WWE SmackDown results - 1/7/16 (Ambrose vs. Owens)|last1=Martin|first1=Adam|date=January 8, 2016|publisher=WrestleView|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109063403/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-smackdown-results/57364-wwe-smackdown-results-1-7-16-ambrose-vs-owens|archive-date=January 9, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=January 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/2016/intercontinental-champion-dean-ambrose-kevin-owens-last-man-standing-28502828|title=Intercontinental Champion Dean Ambrose vs. Kevin Owens (Last Man Standing Match)|last1=Pappolla|first1=Ryan|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160118052914/http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/2016/intercontinental-champion-dean-ambrose-kevin-owens-last-man-standing-28502828|archive-date=January 18, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=January 15, 2016}}</ref> Ambrose competed in the [[Royal Rumble (2016)|2016 Royal Rumble match]] for the WWE World Heavyweight Championship, which he lost after being lastly eliminated by eventual winner Triple H.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/01/24/caldwell2016rumblereport/|title=1/24 WWE Royal Rumble PPV Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live PPV Report|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|date=January 24, 2016|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128011920/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/01/24/caldwell2016rumblereport/|archive-date=January 28, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=January 24, 2016}}</ref> Ambrose would later lose the Intercontinental Championship back to Owens in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic non-elimination matches|five-way match]] on the February 15 episode of ''Raw'', after Owens pinned Tyler Breeze.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/57788-wwe-raw-results-2-15-16-live-results-from-anaheim|title=WWE Raw Results - 2/15/16 (Big Show vs. Braun Strowman)|last1=Tedesco|first1=Mike|date=February 16, 2016|publisher=WrestleView|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160217015325/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/57788-wwe-raw-results-2-15-16-live-results-from-anaheim|archive-date=February 17, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt [[Fastlane (2016)|Fastlane]] on February 21, Ambrose faced Reigns and [[Brock Lesnar]] in a triple threat match to determine the number one contender for the WWE World Heavyweight Championship at [[WrestleMania 32]], but lost after he was pinned by Reigns.<ref>{{cite web|last=Caldwell|first=James|title=2/21 WWE Fast Lane Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live PPV Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/02/21/caldwellfastlaneppvreport/|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=February 21, 2016|accessdate=February 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223051511/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/02/21/caldwellfastlaneppvreport/|archive-date=February 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Ambrose challenged Lesnar to a No Holds Barred [[Professional wrestling match types#Location-based variations|street fight]] match at WrestleMania 32, which Paul Heyman accepted on Lesnar's behalf.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/02/22/feb22rawcaldwell/|title=2/22 WWE Raw Results|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=February 22, 2016|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=February 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225211049/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/02/22/feb22rawcaldwell/|archive-date=February 25, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He then failed to capture the WWE World Heavyweight Championship from Triple H at the [[Roadblock (March 2016)|Roadblock]] event in March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/roadblock/march-12-2016-matches|title=WWE World Heavyweight Champion Triple H battles Dean Ambrose|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305143450/http://www.wwe.com/shows/roadblock/march-12-2016-matches|archive-date=March 5, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=March 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Roadblock\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/03/12/march12roadblockresults/|title=3/12 WWE Roadblock Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=March 12, 2016|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313061858/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/03/12/march12roadblockresults/|archive-date=March 13, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=March 12, 2016}}</ref> He was also unsuccessful in defeating Lesnar at WrestleMania 32.<ref name=\"WrestleMania32\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/03/wm32liveresults/|title=4/3 WrestleMania 32 PPV Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report on Main PPV|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|date=April 3, 2016|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404040347/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/03/wm32liveresults/|archive-date=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=April 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/32/dean-ambrose-brock-lesnar-street-fight-results|title=Brock Lesnar def. Dean Ambrose|last=Burdick|first=Michael|date=April 3, 2016|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414223020/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/32/dean-ambrose-brock-lesnar-street-fight-results|archive-date=April 14, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref> Following WrestleMania, Ambrose began a rivalry with Chris Jericho.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/04/april4rawresults/|title=4/4 WWE Raw Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Report on post-WM32|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|date=April 4, 2016|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405065827/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/04/april4rawresults/|archive-date=April 5, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=April 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/05/02/may2rawresults/|title=5/2 WWE Raw Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live TV Report|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|date=May 2, 2016|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506040211/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/05/02/may2rawresults/|archive-date=May 6, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref> He defeated Jericho at [[Payback (2016)|Payback]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/05/01/payback2016results/|title=5/1 WWE Payback Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|date=May 1, 2016|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503115647/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/05/01/payback2016results/|archive-date=May 3, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=May 1, 2016}}</ref> and again at [[Extreme Rules (2016)|Extreme Rules]] in an [[Professional wrestling match types#Asylum match|Asylum match]] later that month to end the feud.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/62068-wwe-raw-results-51616-live-greensboro-usos-vs-luke-gallows-karl-anderson-extreme-rules-go-home/|title=WWE Raw Results \u2013 5/16/16 (Live from Greensboro, The Usos vs. Luke Gallows and Karl Anderson, Extreme Rules)|last1=Tedesco|first1=Mike|date=May 16, 2016|publisher=WrestleView|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519003927/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/62068-wwe-raw-results-51616-live-greensboro-usos-vs-luke-gallows-karl-anderson-extreme-rules-go-home/|archive-date=May 19, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/extremerules/2016/dean-ambrose-chris-jericho-asylum-match-results|title=Dean Ambrose def. Chris Jericho (Asylum Match)|last=Murphy|first=Ryan|date=May 22, 2016|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620232636/http://www.wwe.com/shows/extremerules/2016/dean-ambrose-chris-jericho-asylum-match-results|archive-date=June 20, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=June 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box\n| width = 25%\n| align = right\n| quote = \"To this point, Ambrose had lost almost every big match he has been in with Rollins, Wyatt, Reigns, Triple H and Lesnar all getting their hands raised at the end [...] We already knew that Dean Ambrose had the ability to be the biggest star of The Shield. Maybe now, especially in light of recent news, he will be\".\n| source = ''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'' writer Steve Khan on Ambrose's WWE World Heavyweight title cash-in at Money in the Bank<ref>{{cite web|last1=Khan|first1=Steve|date=June 23, 2016|title=Examining Dean Ambrose's roller coaster ride to the top of WWE|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/examining-dean-ambroses-roller-coaster-ride-top-wwe-215041|work=[[Wrestling Observer]]|accessdate=June 26, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625132404/http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/examining-dean-ambroses-roller-coaster-ride-top-wwe-215041|archive-date=June 25, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}\nIn May, Ambrose qualified for the [[Money in the Bank (2016)|2016 Money in the Bank ladder match]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/05/23/may23rawresults/|title=5/23 WWE Raw TV Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|date=May 23, 2016|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=May 23, 2016}}</ref> which he would win.<ref name=\"MITB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/moneyinthebank/2016/money-bank-ladder-match-results|title=Dean Ambrose won the Money in the Bank Ladder Match|last=Powers|first=Kevin|date=June 19, 2016|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622051823/http://www.wwe.com/shows/moneyinthebank/2016/money-bank-ladder-match-results|archive-date=June 22, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=June 19, 2016}}</ref> Later that same night, he would cash in his Money in the Bank contract and defeat Rollins to win the WWE World Heavyweight Championship for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/06/19/619-wwe-mitb-ppv-results-caldwells-ongoing-live-report/|title=6/19 WWE MITB PPV Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=June 19, 2016|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160621185909/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/06/19/619-wwe-mitb-ppv-results-caldwells-ongoing-live-report/|archive-date=June 21, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=June 19, 2016}}</ref> Ambrose made his first title defense against Rollins on the July 18 episode of ''Raw'', which ended in a draw after a double pinfall.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title=7/18 WWE Raw Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live TV Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/18/july18rawresultsfinal/|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=July 18, 2016|accessdate=July 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722124007/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/18/july18rawresultsfinal/|archive-date=July 22, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=WWE Title match Update \u2013 WWE rules on double pin finish|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/18/718-raw-update-wwe-title-match-result/|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=July 18, 2016|accessdate=July 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721053707/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/18/718-raw-update-wwe-title-match-result/|archive-date=July 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/2016-07-19/article/ambrose-rollins|title=Dean Ambrose def. Seth Rollins \u2013 WWE Championship Match|last=Burdick|first=Michael|date=July 19, 2016|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116023738/https://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/2016-07-19/article/ambrose-rollins|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=January 9, 2019}}</ref> The following night at the [[2016 WWE draft]], Ambrose was drafted to [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]], being the brand's first draft pick and bringing the WWE Championship with him; that same night, he pinned Rollins to retain the championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/2016-wwe-draft-results|title=2016 WWE Draft results: WWE officially ushers in New Era|date=July 19, 2016|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720044640/http://www.wwe.com/2016-wwe-draft-results|archive-date=July 20, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=July 19, 2016}}</ref> At [[Battleground (2016)|Battleground]], Ambrose retained his title against Reigns and Rollins after pinning Reigns.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title=7/24 WWE Battleground Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/24/jcbattlegroundppvreport/|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=July 24, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727004908/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/24/jcbattlegroundppvreport/|archive-date=July 27, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwebattleground/2016/dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-roman-reigns-triple-threat-results|title=WWE Champion Dean Ambrose def. Roman Reigns & Seth Rollins (Triple Threat Match)|last1=Melok|first1=Bobby|date=July 24, 2016|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160728021126/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwebattleground/2016/dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-roman-reigns-triple-threat-results|archive-date=July 28, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=July 24, 2016}}</ref> Ambrose then successfully defended the renamed \"WWE World Championship\" against Dolph Ziggler at [[SummerSlam (2016)|SummerSlam]] in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/2016/dean-ambrose-dolph-ziggler|title=WWE World Champion Dean Ambrose vs. Dolph Ziggler|last1=Clapp|first1=John|date=August 10, 2016|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806162824/http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/2016/dean-ambrose-dolph-ziggler|archive-date=August 6, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=August 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/2016/wwe-world-champion-dean-ambrose-vs-dolph-ziggler-result|title=WWE World Champion Dean Ambrose def. Dolph Ziggler|last1=Powers|first1=Kevin|date=August 21, 2016|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823124809/http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/2016/wwe-world-champion-dean-ambrose-vs-dolph-ziggler-result|archive-date=August 23, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=August 21, 2016}}</ref> At [[Backlash (2016)|Backlash]] on September 11, he lost the title to [[A.J. Styles|AJ Styles]] after Styles performed a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Low blow|low blow]] and [[Facebuster#Belly-to-back inverted mat slam|''Styles Clash'']] while the referee was incapacitated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/backlash/2016/dean-ambrose-vs-aj-styles-results|title=AJ Styles def. Dean Ambrose to win the WWE World Championship|last1=Pappolla|first1=Ryan|date=September 11, 2016|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915062142/http://www.wwe.com/shows/backlash/2016/dean-ambrose-vs-aj-styles-results|archive-date=September 15, 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref> Ambrose was unsuccessful in regaining the championship at [[No Mercy (2016)|No Mercy]] on October 9 in a triple threat match also involving John Cena, who was pinned by Styles.<ref>{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=Powell's WWE No Mercy 2016 live review: AJ Styles vs. John Cena vs. Dean Ambrose for the WWE Championship opens the show, The Miz vs. Dolph Ziggler for the IC Title or Ziggler's career|url=http://prowrestling.net/site/2016/10/09/powells-wwe-no-mercy-2016-live-review-aj-styles-vs-john-cena-vs-dean-ambrose-for-the-wwe-championship-the-miz-vs-dolph-ziggler-for-the-ic-title-or-zigglers-career/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|accessdate=October 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011163415/http://prowrestling.net/site/2016/10/09/powells-wwe-no-mercy-2016-live-review-aj-styles-vs-john-cena-vs-dean-ambrose-for-the-wwe-championship-the-miz-vs-dolph-ziggler-for-the-ic-title-or-zigglers-career/|archive-date=October 11, 2016|url-status=live|date=October 9, 2016}}</ref> The following month at [[Survivor Series (2016)|Survivor Series]], Ambrose made up part of Team SmackDown alongside Styles, Bray Wyatt, Randy Orton and [[Shane McMahon]] in a winning effort over Team Raw.<ref>{{cite web|title=Keller's WWE Survivor Series PPV Report11/20: Goldberg vs. Lesnar, Raw vs. Smackdown, The Miz vs. Sami Zayn, more|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/11/20/kellers-wwe-survivor-series-ppv-report-1120-goldberg-vs-lesnar-raw-vs-smackdown-miz-vs-sami-zayn/|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=November 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123063722/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/11/20/kellers-wwe-survivor-series-ppv-report-1120-goldberg-vs-lesnar-raw-vs-smackdown-miz-vs-sami-zayn/|archive-date=November 23, 2016|url-status=live|date=November 21, 2016}}</ref> He would face Styles once again in a Tables, Ladders, and Chairs match at [[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2016)|TLC]] for the WWE title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/69058-aj-styles-vs-dean-ambrose-wwe-world-championship-headline-tlc-ppv-december-4/|title=AJ Styles vs. Dean Ambrose for the WWE World Championship to headline TLC PPV on December 4 in Dallas|last=Martin|first=Adam|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=November 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105033326/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/69058-aj-styles-vs-dean-ambrose-wwe-world-championship-headline-tlc-ppv-december-4/|archive-date=November 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> During the match, [[James Ellsworth (wrestler)|James Ellsworth]] interfered and pushed Ambrose off a ladder through multiple tables, allowing Styles to retain the title.<ref>{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=Powell's WWE TLC 2016 live review: AJ Styles vs. Dean Ambrose in a TLC match for the WWE Championship, The Miz vs. Dolph Ziggler in a ladder match for the Intercontinental Championship|url=http://prowrestling.net/site/2016/12/04/powells-wwe-survivor-series-2016-live-review-aj-styles-vs-dean-ambrose-in-a-tlc-match-for-the-wwe-championship-the-miz-vs-dolph-ziggler-in-a-ladder-match-for-the-intercontinental-championship/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|accessdate=December 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206155040/http://prowrestling.net/site/2016/12/04/powells-wwe-survivor-series-2016-live-review-aj-styles-vs-dean-ambrose-in-a-tlc-match-for-the-wwe-championship-the-miz-vs-dolph-ziggler-in-a-ladder-match-for-the-intercontinental-championship/|archive-date=December 6, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Ambrose would then fail to become the number one contender for the reverted WWE Championship<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/wwe-championship|title=WWE Championship|publisher=[[WWE]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161214011819/http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/wwe-championship|archivedate=December 14, 2016|accessdate=December 13, 2016}}</ref> in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic elimination matches|fatal four-way elimination match]] involving Dolph Ziggler, Luke Harper, and [[The Miz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/12/13/1213-wwe-smackdown-live-parkss-ongoing-real-time-report/|title=12/13 WWE Smackdown Live \u2013 Parks's Ongoing, Real-Time Report|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=December 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220121147/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/12/13/1213-wwe-smackdown-live-parkss-ongoing-real-time-report/|archive-date=December 20, 2016|url-status=live|date=December 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Intercontinental Champion Dean Ambrose 2017.jpg|thumb|upright|After feuding for the [[WWE Championship]], Ambrose won his second [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]] in January 2017 and held it throughout the first half of that year]]\nOn the January 3, 2017 episode of ''SmackDown'', Ambrose defeated The Miz to win the Intercontinental Championship for the second time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/01/03/13-wwe-smackdown-live-parkss-ongoing-real-time-report-including-miz-vs-ambrose-c-title/|title=1/3 WWE Smackdown Live \u2013 Parks's Ongoing, Real-Time Report, including Miz vs. Ambrose for the I.C. Title|last=Parks|first=Greg|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=January 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104233731/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/01/03/13-wwe-smackdown-live-parkss-ongoing-real-time-report-including-miz-vs-ambrose-c-title/|archive-date=January 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He participated in the [[Royal Rumble (2017)|2017 Royal Rumble match]] in which he lasted almost 27 minutes before being eliminated by Brock Lesnar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/article/2017-royal-rumble-statistics-entrants-eliminations|title=Full 2017 Royal Rumble Match statistics: entrants, eliminations, times and more|date=January 30, 2017|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201203305/http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/article/2017-royal-rumble-statistics-entrants-eliminations|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> On February 12, Ambrose took part in the WWE Championship Elimination Chamber match at the [[Elimination Chamber (2017)|event of the same name]], where he eliminated [[Baron Corbin]] with a [[Pin (professional wrestling)#Roll-up|roll-up]] pin only for Corbin to attack him afterward, allowing Miz to eliminate Ambrose.<ref name=\"EC2017\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=2/12 Powell's WWE Elimination Chamber 2017 live review: John Cena vs. AJ Styles vs. Dean Ambrose vs. The Miz vs. Baron Corbin vs. Bray Wyatt in an Elimination Chamber match for the WWE Championship|url=http://prowrestling.net/site/2017/02/12/212-powells-wwe-elimination-chamber-2017-live-review-john-cena-vs-aj-styles-vs-dean-ambrose-vs-miz-vs-baron-corbin-vs-bray-wyatt-elimination-chamber-match-wwe/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|accessdate=February 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213060952/http://prowrestling.net/site/2017/02/12/212-powells-wwe-elimination-chamber-2017-live-review-john-cena-vs-aj-styles-vs-dean-ambrose-vs-miz-vs-baron-corbin-vs-bray-wyatt-elimination-chamber-match-wwe/|archive-date=February 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A match was set between Ambrose and Corbin at the [[WrestleMania 33]] pre-show on April 2, where Ambrose retained his Intercontinental Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestling.net/site/2017/04/02/powells-wrestlemania-33-kickoff-show-live-review-neville-vs-austin-aries-wwe-cruiserweight-championship-andre-giant-memorial-battle-royal/|title=Powell's WrestleMania 33 Kickoff Show live review: Neville vs. Austin Aries for the WWE Cruiserweight Championship, Andre the Giant Memorial Battle Royal|last=Powell|first=Jason|date=April 2, 2017|accessdate=April 3, 2017|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402224312/http://prowrestling.net/site/2017/04/02/powells-wrestlemania-33-kickoff-show-live-review-neville-vs-austin-aries-wwe-cruiserweight-championship-andre-giant-memorial-battle-royal/|archive-date=April 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Two nights later on ''SmackDown'', Ambrose wrestled in his final match for the brand, in a losing effort to Corbin in a non-title match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/04/04/kellers-wwe-smackdown-report-44-wrestlemania-33-fallout-including-celebration-interview-orton-rematches-miz-maryse-call-cena-nikki/|title=KELLER'S WWE SMACKDOWN REPORT 4/4: WrestleMania 33 fallout including celebration interview with Orton, rematches, Miz & Maryse, and some NXT call-ups!|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Wade|last=Keller|authorlink=Wade Keller|date=April 4, 2017|accessdate=April 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406201303/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/04/04/kellers-wwe-smackdown-report-44-wrestlemania-33-fallout-including-celebration-interview-orton-rematches-miz-maryse-call-cena-nikki/|archive-date=April 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Following that, Ambrose was moved to the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw brand]] as a result of the [[2017 WWE Superstar Shake-up|Superstar Shake-up]].<ref name=\"Raw04102017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/04/10/kellers-wwe-monday-night-raw-410-superstar-shakeup-begins-two-smackdown-wrestlers-coming-ring-full-report/|title=Keller's WWE Monday Night Raw 4/10: Superstar Shakeup begins with two Smackdown wrestlers coming to the ring, full report|last1=Keller|first1=Wade|date=April 10, 2017|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170411140814/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/04/10/kellers-wwe-monday-night-raw-410-superstar-shakeup-begins-two-smackdown-wrestlers-coming-ring-full-report/|archive-date=April 11, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=April 10, 2017}}</ref> He would then continue his feud with The Miz, who was also drafted to the aforementioned brand in the Superstar Shake-up,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/05/01/kellers-wwe-raw-report-51-coverage-live-post-payback-event-including-latest-alexa-braun-reigns/|title=Keller's WWE Raw Report 5/1: Coverage of live post-Payback event including latest with Alexa, Braun, Reigns|date=May 1, 2017|last=Keller|first=Wade|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=May 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505100254/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/05/01/kellers-wwe-raw-report-51-coverage-live-post-payback-event-including-latest-alexa-braun-reigns/|archive-date=May 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Keller|first=Wade|title=Keller's WWE Raw Report 5/15: Ongoing coverage including Miz vs. Dean Ambrose, latest on Strowman-Reigns, Sheamus & Cesaro|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/05/15/kellers-wwe-raw-report-515-ongoing-coverage-including-miz-vs-dean-ambrose-latest-strowman-reigns-sheamus-cesaro/|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=May 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519114252/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/05/15/kellers-wwe-raw-report-515-ongoing-coverage-including-miz-vs-dean-ambrose-latest-strowman-reigns-sheamus-cesaro/|archive-date=May 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> eventually losing the Intercontinental title to him at [[Extreme Rules (2017)|Extreme Rules]] in June, thus ending his reign at 152 days.<ref name=\"ER2017\">{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=6/4 Powell's WWE Extreme Rules Live Review: Finn Balor vs. Samoa Joe vs. Bray Wyatt vs. Roman Reigns vs. Seth Rollins in a five-way to become No. 1 contender to the WWE Universal Championship, The Hardys vs. Sheamus and Cesaro in a cage match for the Raw Tag Titles|url=http://prowrestling.net/site/2017/06/04/64-powells-wwe-extreme-rules-live-review-finn-balor-vs-samoa-joe-vs-bray-wyatt-vs-roman-reigns-vs-seth-rollins-five-way-become-no-1-contender-wwe-universal-championshi/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=June 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605004029/http://prowrestling.net/site/2017/06/04/64-powells-wwe-extreme-rules-live-review-finn-balor-vs-samoa-joe-vs-bray-wyatt-vs-roman-reigns-vs-seth-rollins-five-way-become-no-1-contender-wwe-universal-championshi/|archive-date=June 5, 2017|url-status=live|date=June 4, 2017}}</ref> Ambrose continued to feud with The Miz, leading up to a rematch for the Intercontinental Championship at [[WWE Great Balls of Fire|Great Balls of Fire]] on July 9, where he lost after interference by The Miztourage ([[Curtis Axel]] and [[Bo Dallas]]).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Intercontinental Champion The Miz def. Dean Ambrose|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/great-balls-of-fire/wwe-great-balls-of-fire-2017/the-miz-dean-ambrose-results|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713012834/http://www.wwe.com/shows/great-balls-of-fire/wwe-great-balls-of-fire-2017/the-miz-dean-ambrose-results|archive-date=July 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== The Shield reunion (2017\u20132018) ====\n[[File:Ambrose and Rollins 2017.jpg|thumb|left|In August 2017, Ambrose reunited with Seth Rollins to reform part of [[The Shield (professional wrestling)|The Shield]]]]\nOn the July 10 episode of ''Raw'', Seth Rollins saved Ambrose from an attack by The Miz and The Miztourage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/07/10/kellers-wwe-raw-report-710-fallout-great-balls-fire-including-strowman-reigns/|title=KELLER'S WWE RAW REPORT 7/10: Fallout from Great Balls of Fire including Strowman-Reigns, Cass gloats, more|last=Keller|first=Wade|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=July 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714155538/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/07/10/kellers-wwe-raw-report-710-fallout-great-balls-fire-including-strowman-reigns/|archive-date=July 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> After failing to gain Ambrose's trust for several weeks,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/07/17/kellers-wwe-raw-report-717-reigns-vs-joe-earn-universal-title-shot-summerslam-angle-mystery-revealed/|title=KELLER'S WWE RAW REPORT 7/17: Reigns vs. Joe to earn Universal Title shot at Summerslam, Angle mystery revealed|last=Keller|first=Wade|date=July 17, 2017|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=July 17, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721010550/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/07/17/kellers-wwe-raw-report-717-reigns-vs-joe-earn-universal-title-shot-summerslam-angle-mystery-revealed/|archive-date=July 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=WWE Raw results, recap: Main event set for SummerSlam, mini Shield reunion|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-raw-results-recap-main-event-set-for-summerslam-mini-shield-reunion/|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|accessdate=July 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728075333/https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-raw-results-recap-main-event-set-for-summerslam-mini-shield-reunion/|archive-date=July 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 7/31/17 (Reigns vs. Strowman vs. Joe)|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/87587-wwe-raw-results-july-31-2017/|website=WrestleView|accessdate=August 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804002331/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/87587-wwe-raw-results-july-31-2017/|archive-date=August 4, 2017|url-status=live|date=July 31, 2017}}</ref> the two argued in the ring on the August 14 episode of ''Raw'' and eventually brawled with each other before fighting off [[The Bar (professional wrestling)|Cesaro and Sheamus]], reuniting the team in the process.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=WWE Raw Live Results: SummerSlam Go-Home Show|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-results/wwe-raw-live-results-summerslam-go-home-show-240941|magazine=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|accessdate=August 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815025059/http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-results/wwe-raw-live-results-summerslam-go-home-show-240941|archive-date=August 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> At [[SummerSlam (2017)|SummerSlam]] on August 20, Ambrose and Rollins defeated Cesaro and Sheamus to win the WWE Raw Tag Team Championship, making Ambrose both a [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)#WWE|Triple Crown]] and [[Grand Slam (professional wrestling)#WWE|Grand Slam]] champion in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/article/new-grand-slam-winners|title=The new Grand Slam winners: The eight Superstars who have won every active championship|date=August 27, 2017|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=November 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102115711/http://www.wwe.com/article/new-grand-slam-winners|archive-date=November 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Dean Ambrose & Seth Rollins def. Cesaro & Sheamus to become the new Raw Tag Team Champions|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/2017/cesaro-sheamus-dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-results|work=WWE|date=August 20, 2017|accessdate=August 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821092135/http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/2017/cesaro-sheamus-dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-results|archive-date=August 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=Powell's WWE SummerSlam 2017 live review: Brock Lesnar vs. Braun Strowman vs. Samoa Joe vs. Roman Reigns for the WWE Universal Championship, Jinder Mahal vs. Shinsuke Nakamura for the WWE Championship, Sheamus and Cesaro vs. Dean Ambrose and Seth Rollins for the Raw Tag Titles|url=http://prowrestling.net/site/2017/08/20/powells-wwe-summerslam-2017-live-review-brock-lesnar-vs-braun-strowman-vs-samoa-joe-vs-roman-reigns-wwe-universal-championship-jinder-mahal-vs-shinsuke-nakamura-wwe-champio/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=August 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821024325/http://prowrestling.net/site/2017/08/20/powells-wwe-summerslam-2017-live-review-brock-lesnar-vs-braun-strowman-vs-samoa-joe-vs-roman-reigns-wwe-universal-championship-jinder-mahal-vs-shinsuke-nakamura-wwe-champio/|archive-date=August 21, 2017|url-status=live|date=August 20, 2017}}</ref> Ambrose and Rollins successfully defended the titles against Cesaro and Sheamus at [[No Mercy (2017)|No Mercy]], after Ambrose pinned Sheamus.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Raw Tag Team Champions Dean Ambrose & Seth Rollins def. Cesaro & Sheamus|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nomercy/2017/seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-cesaro-sheamus-results|work=WWE|accessdate=September 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925132200/http://www.wwe.com/shows/nomercy/2017/seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-cesaro-sheamus-results|archive-date=September 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the October 9 episode of ''Raw'', Ambrose and Rollins reunited with Roman Reigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/10/09/kellers-wwe-raw-report-109-shield-reunion-continues-miz-tv-sheamus-cesaro-tlc-build-continues/|title=Keller's WWE Raw Report 10/9: Shield reunion continues, Miz TV with Sheamus & Cesaro, TLC build up continues|last=Keller|first=Wade|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=October 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010155546/https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2017/10/09/kellers-wwe-raw-report-109-shield-reunion-continues-miz-tv-sheamus-cesaro-tlc-build-continues/|archive-date=October 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The newly reformed Shield was due to face the team of Braun Strowman, Cesaro, Kane, The Miz and Sheamus at [[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2017)|TLC]] in a 5-on-3 handicap Tables, Ladders and Chairs match,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwetlc/2017/kurt-angle-5-on-3-handicap-tables-ladders-chairs-match|title=Kurt Angle & Raw Tag Team Champions Dean Ambrose & Seth Rollins vs. Intercontinental Champion The Miz, Cesaro, Sheamus, Braun Strowman & Kane (5-on-3 Handicap Tables, Ladders and Chairs Match)|last1=Burdick|first1=Michael|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=October 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021060319/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwetlc/2017/kurt-angle-5-on-3-handicap-tables-ladders-chairs-match|archive-date=October 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> but Reigns was replaced by [[Kurt Angle]] over an illness concern.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwetlc/article/kurt-angle-returns-replace-roman-reigns-at-wwe-tlc-aj-styles-the-demon?sf123717574=1|title=Breaking News: Kurt Angle will return to action and replace Roman Reigns at WWE TLC; AJ Styles to battle \"The Demon\" Finn B\u00e1lor|date=October 20, 2017|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=October 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021033901/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwetlc/article/kurt-angle-returns-replace-roman-reigns-at-wwe-tlc-aj-styles-the-demon?sf123717574=1|archive-date=October 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Ambrose, Rollins, and Angle would go on to win the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwetlc/2017/kurt-angle-dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-braun-strowman-miz-kane-cesaro-sheamush|title=Kurt Angle & Raw Tag Team Champions Dean Ambrose & Seth Rollins def. Intercontinental Champion The Miz, Cesaro, Sheamus, Braun Strowman & Kane (3-on-5 Handicap Tables, Ladders and Chairs Match)|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=October 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104162513/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwetlc/2017/kurt-angle-dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-braun-strowman-miz-kane-cesaro-sheamush|archive-date=November 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Ambrose and Rollins were scheduled to face [[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship|SmackDown Tag Team Champions]] The Usos in an interbrand match at [[Survivor Series (2017)|Survivor Series]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2017/dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-vs-the-usos|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024113251/http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2017/dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-vs-the-usos|url-status=dead|title=Raw Tag Team Champions Dean Ambrose and Seth Rollins vs. SmackDown Tag Team Champions The Usos|last1=Taylor|first1=Scott|work=WWE|archivedate=October 24, 2017|accessdate=October 23, 2017}}</ref> but lost the tag titles back to Cesaro and Sheamus on the November 6 episode of ''Raw'' after a distraction from SmackDown's [[The New Day (professional wrestling)|The New Day]] (Big E, Kofi Kingston, and Xavier Woods),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2017/11/06/116-powells-wwe-raw-live-tv-review-seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-vs-sheamus-cesaro-raw-tag-titles-kurt-angle-miz-tv-elias-vs-jason-jordan-guitar-pole-match/|title=11/6 Powell's WWE Raw Live TV Review: Seth Rollins and Dean Ambrose vs. Sheamus and Cesaro for the Raw Tag Titles, Kurt Angle on Miz TV, Elias vs. Jason Jordan|last=Powell|first=Jason|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=November 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107053312/https://prowrestling.net/site/2017/11/06/116-powells-wwe-raw-live-tv-review-seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-vs-sheamus-cesaro-raw-tag-titles-kurt-angle-miz-tv-elias-vs-jason-jordan-guitar-pole-match/|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> thus ending their reign at 78 days.<ref>WWE recognizes their reign as lasting 79 days. Source: {{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/raw-tag-team-championships|title=Raw Tag Team Championships|access-date=August 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828125145/http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/raw-tag-team-championships|archive-date=August 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> This led to a match between The Shield and The New Day at Survivor Series two weeks later,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2017/the-shield-the-new-day|title=The Shield vs. The New Day|last1=Burdick|first1=Michael|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=November 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115223050/http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2017/the-shield-the-new-day|archive-date=November 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> which the former won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2017/the-shield-the-new-day-results|title=The Shield def. The New Day|last1=Wortman|first1=James|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=November 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122234351/http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2017/the-shield-the-new-day-results|archive-date=November 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2017, Ambrose suffered a triceps injury, reportedly rendering him out of action for nine months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/article/dean-ambrose-right-arm-injury|title=Dean Ambrose suffers arm injury on Raw|publisher=[[WWE]]|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=March 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321152622/https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/article/dean-ambrose-right-arm-injury|archive-date=March 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/article/dean-ambrose-surgery-update-dec-2017|title=Dean Ambrose injury will keep him out approximately nine months|last1=Wortman|first1=James|publisher=[[WWE]]|date=December 20, 2017|accessdate=March 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322175814/http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/article/dean-ambrose-surgery-update-dec-2017|archive-date=March 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/wwe/news/14203/11502075/wwe-star-dean-ambrose-reveals-he-nearly-died-due-to-staph-infection|title=WWE star Dean Ambrose reveals he 'nearly died' due to staph infection|date=September 19, 2018|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112044309/https://www.skysports.com/wwe/news/14203/11502075/wwe-star-dean-ambrose-reveals-he-nearly-died-due-to-staph-infection|archive-date=January 12, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/other-sports/wrestling/wwe-star-dean-ambrose-says-13253475|title=WWE star Dean Ambrose says he \"nearly died\" from a Staph infection|last=Docking|first=Neil|date=September 15, 2018|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111232817/https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/other-sports/wrestling/wwe-star-dean-ambrose-says-13253475|archive-date=January 11, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn the August 13, 2018 episode of ''Raw'', Ambrose returned to assist Rollins against an attack from [[Drew McIntyre]] and Dolph Ziggler.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/08/13/8-13-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-final-summerslam-hype-heyman-lesnar-follow-up-rousey-bliss-hype-ziggler-seth-contract-signing/|title=8/13 WWE RAW RESULTS: Keller's report on final Summerslam hype, Heyman-Lesnar follow-up, Rousey-Bliss hype, Ziggler-Seth contract signing|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Wade|last=Keller|date=August 13, 2018|accessdate=February 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815201207/https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/08/13/8-13-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-final-summerslam-hype-heyman-lesnar-follow-up-rousey-bliss-hype-ziggler-seth-contract-signing/|archive-date=August 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Six days later, he assisted Rollins in winning the Intercontinental Championship at [[SummerSlam (2018)|SummerSlam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/08/19/wwe-summerslam-results-8-19-kellers-report-on-lesnar-vs-reigns-bliss-vs-rousey-styles-vs-joe-ziggler-vs-rollins-carmella-vs-charlotte-vs-becky-braun-vs-owens/|title=WWE Summerslam Results 8/19: Keller's report on Lesnar vs. Reigns, Bliss vs. Rousey, Styles vs. Joe, Ziggler vs. Rollins, Carmella vs. Charlotte vs. Becky, Braun vs. Owens|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=August 19, 2018|accessdate=October 6, 2018|first=Wade|last=Keller|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006195107/https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/08/19/wwe-summerslam-results-8-19-kellers-report-on-lesnar-vs-reigns-bliss-vs-rousey-styles-vs-joe-ziggler-vs-rollins-carmella-vs-charlotte-vs-becky-braun-vs-owens/|archive-date=October 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Ambrose and Rollins aided [[WWE Universal Championship|Universal Champion]] Roman Reigns in attacking Braun Strowman when the latter attempted to cash-in his Money in the Bank contract, once again reuniting The Shield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/08/20/8-20-wwe-raw-results-kellers-full-run-down-and-analysis-of-post-summerslam-episode-including-reigns-stepping-out-in-brooklyn-as-new-champion/|title=8/20 WWE Raw Results: Keller's full run-down and analysis of post-Summerslam episode including Reigns stepping out in Brooklyn as new champion|last=Keller|first=Wade|date=August 20, 2018|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121220645/https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/08/20/8-20-wwe-raw-results-kellers-full-run-down-and-analysis-of-post-summerslam-episode-including-reigns-stepping-out-in-brooklyn-as-new-champion/|archive-date=January 21, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 21, 2019}}</ref> At [[Hell in a Cell (2018)|Hell in a Cell]], Ambrose and Rollins were unsuccessful in defeating Ziggler and McIntyre for the Raw Tag Team Championship.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Raw Tag Team Champions Dolph Ziggler & Drew McIntrye def. Dean Ambrose & Seth Rollins|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/hellinacell/2018/dolph-ziggler-drew-mcIntrye-seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-results|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=September 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917143516/https://www.wwe.com/shows/hellinacell/2018/dolph-ziggler-drew-mcintrye-seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-results|archive-date=September 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In October, The Shield defeated Ziggler, McIntyre, and Strowman at [[Super Show-Down (2018)|Super Show-Down]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwe-super-show-down/article/wwe-super-show-down-2018-results|title=WWE Super Show-Down 2018 results|publisher=[[WWE]]|date=October 6, 2018|accessdate=October 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006115745/https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwe-super-show-down/article/wwe-super-show-down-2018-results|archive-date=October 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Two nights later on ''Raw'', they were defeated by the same trio in a rematch. After the match, a frustrated Ambrose walked away from his teammates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/10/08/10-8-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-super-show-down-fallout-as-they-head-to-evolution-and-crown-jewel-in-saudi-arabia/|title=10/8 WWE Raw Results: Keller's report on Super Show-down fallout as they head to Evolution and Crown Jewel in Saudi Arabia|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Wade|last=Keller|date=October 8, 2018|accessdate=October 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013014250/https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/10/08/10-8-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-super-show-down-fallout-as-they-head-to-evolution-and-crown-jewel-in-saudi-arabia/|archive-date=October 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Final storylines and departure (2018\u20132019) ====\n[[File:Dean Ambrose December 2018.jpg|thumb|right|Ambrose in December 2018]]\nOn the October 22 episode of ''Raw'', after Reigns announced his real-life [[leukemia]] and relinquished the Universal Championship, Ambrose and Rollins defeated Ziggler and McIntyre to capture the Raw Tag Team Championship for the second time. However, Ambrose immediately attacked Rollins after the match, turning [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] for the first time since 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=10/22 Powell's WWE Raw Live TV Review: Roman Reigns announces he has leukemia, forfeits the WWE Universal Championship, Drew McIntyre and Dolph Ziggler vs. Seth Rollins and Dean Ambrose for the Raw Tag Titles, Ronda Rousey and Nikki Bella contract signing for WWE Evolution, Triple H and Shawn Michaels appear|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/10/22/10-22-powells-wwe-raw-live-tv-review-drew-mcintyre-and-dolph-ziggler-vs-seth-rollins-and-dean-ambrose-for-the-raw-tag-titles-ronda-rousey-and-nikki-bella-contract-signing-for-wwe-evolution/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|accessdate=October 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023042808/https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/10/22/10-22-powells-wwe-raw-live-tv-review-drew-mcintyre-and-dolph-ziggler-vs-seth-rollins-and-dean-ambrose-for-the-raw-tag-titles-ronda-rousey-and-nikki-bella-contract-signing-for-wwe-evolution/|archive-date=October 23, 2018|url-status=live|date=October 22, 2018}}</ref> Two weeks later on ''Raw'', Ambrose attacked Rollins again, after the latter lost the tag titles in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|handicap match]] against [[The Authors of Pain|AOP]] ([[Akam (wrestler)|Akam]] and [[Rezar (wrestler)|Rezar]]).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=11/05 Powell's WWE Raw Live TV Review: Survivor Series developments, Raw Tag Title match, Riott Squad vs. Sasha Banks, Bayley, and Natalya, Dolph Ziggler vs. Elias, Nia Jax vs. Ember Moon, Bobby Lashley vs. Finn Balor|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/11/05/11-05-powells-wwe-raw-live-tv-review-survivor-series-developments-raw-tag-title-match-riott-squad-vs-sasha-banks-bayley-and-natalya-dolph-ziggler-vs-elias-nia-jax-vs-ember-moon-bobby-lash/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|accessdate=November 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106051359/https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/11/05/11-05-powells-wwe-raw-live-tv-review-survivor-series-developments-raw-tag-title-match-riott-squad-vs-sasha-banks-bayley-and-natalya-dolph-ziggler-vs-elias-nia-jax-vs-ember-moon-bobby-lash/|archive-date=November 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The following week, Ambrose burned his Shield vest and explained that being part of the group had made him weak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/11/12/11-12-powells-wwe-raw-live-tv-review-brock-lesnar-and-stephanie-mcmahon-appear-alexa-bliss-names-the-womens-team-raw-last-two-men-announced-for-mens-team-raw-final-hype-for-ww/|title=11/12 Powell's WWE Raw Live TV Review: Brock Lesnar and Stephanie McMahon appear, Alexa Bliss names the women's Team Raw, last two men announced for men's Team Raw, final hype for WWE Survivor Series|date=November 12, 2018|last=Powell|first=Jason|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=November 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114060543/https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/11/12/11-12-powells-wwe-raw-live-tv-review-brock-lesnar-and-stephanie-mcmahon-appear-alexa-bliss-names-the-womens-team-raw-last-two-men-announced-for-mens-team-raw-final-hype-for-ww/|archive-date=November 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He would continue to taunt Rollins over the following weeks by stalking him,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/11/19/11-19-powells-wwe-raw-live-tv-review-the-night-after-survivor-series-braun-strowman-finds-out-when-hell-get-his-matches-with-brock-lesnar-and-baron-corbin-the-build-to-wwe-tlc-be/|title=11/19 Powell's WWE Raw Live TV Review: The night after Survivor Series, Braun Strowman finds out when he'll get his matches with Brock Lesnar and Baron Corbin, the build to WWE TLC begins|date=November 19, 2018|last=Powell|first=Jason|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=November 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120051526/https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/11/19/11-19-powells-wwe-raw-live-tv-review-the-night-after-survivor-series-braun-strowman-finds-out-when-hell-get-his-matches-with-brock-lesnar-and-baron-corbin-the-build-to-wwe-tlc-be/|archive-date=November 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> getting [[Vaccine|vaccinated]] against what he perceived to be Rollins's \"illness\",<ref name=\"Raw20181126\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/11/26/11-26-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-lashley-vs-elias-seth-rollins-ic-title-open-challenge-latest-on-tlc-ppv-hype/|title=11/26 WWE Raw Results: Keller's report on Lashley vs. Elias, Seth Rollins' IC Title open challenge, latest on TLC PPV hype|date=November 26, 2018|last=Keller|first=Wade|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=November 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222173634/https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/11/26/11-26-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-lashley-vs-elias-seth-rollins-ic-title-open-challenge-latest-on-tlc-ppv-hype/|archive-date=December 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and ordering his own personal [[SWAT]] team to attack Rollins, subsequently proclaiming himself as \"The Moral Compass of WWE\".<ref name=\"Wrestling Observer Newsletter\">{{cite web |title=WWE Raw Live Results: Vince McMahon Returns |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-results/wwe-raw-live-results-vince-mcmahon-returns-272636 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] |accessdate=December 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181218193447/https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-results/wwe-raw-live-results-vince-mcmahon-returns-272636 |archive-date=December 18, 2018 |url-status=live |date=December 18, 2018 }}</ref> Ambrose defeated Rollins at [[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2018)|TLC]] in December to win the Intercontinental Championship, beginning his third reign with title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwetlc/2018/seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-results|title=Dean Ambrose def. Seth Rollins to become the new Intercontinental Champion|last1=Beningo|first1=Anthony|date=December 16, 2018|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217202228/https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwetlc/2018/seth-rollins-dean-ambrose-results|archive-date=December 17, 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=December 16, 2018}}</ref> Throughout the following weeks, he successfully defended his title against Tyler Breeze,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/amp/shows/raw/2018-12-17/article/intercontinental-champion-dean-ambrose-def-tyler-breeze-open-challenge|title=Intercontinental Champion Dean Ambrose def. Tyler Breeze (Open Challenge)|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=December 17, 2018|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108145553/https://www.wwe.com/amp/shows/raw/2018-12-17/article/intercontinental-champion-dean-ambrose-def-tyler-breeze-open-challenge|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> [[Apollo Crews]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/amp/shows/raw/2018-12-31/article/intercontinental-champion-dean-ambrose-def-apollo-crews|title=Intercontinental Champion Dean Ambrose def. Apollo Crews|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=December 31, 2018|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108145604/https://www.wwe.com/amp/shows/raw/2018-12-31/article/intercontinental-champion-dean-ambrose-def-apollo-crews|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> and Rollins,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/amp/shows/raw/2019-01-07/article/dean-ambrose-def-seth-rollins-falls-count-anywhere-match-bobby-lashley|title=Intercontinental Champion Dean Ambrose def. Seth Rollins (Falls Count Anywhere Match)|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|date=January 7, 2019|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108145540/https://www.wwe.com/amp/shows/raw/2019-01-07/article/dean-ambrose-def-seth-rollins-falls-count-anywhere-match-bobby-lashley|archive-date=January 8, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> before losing the championship to [[Bobby Lashley]] on the January 14, 2019 episode of ''Raw'', in a triple threat match also involving Rollins, ending his reign at 29 days.<ref name=\"Raw01142019\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=1/14 Powell's WWE Raw TV Review: Dean Ambrose vs. Bobby Lashley vs. Seth Rollins in a Triple Threat for the Intercontinental Championship, Ronda Rousey and Sasha Banks vs. Nia Jax and Tamina, the Royal Rumble build continues|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/01/14/1-14-powells-wwe-raw-tv-review-dean-ambrose-vs-bobby-lashley-vs-seth-rollins-in-a-triple-threat-for-the-intercontinental-championship-ronda-rousey-and-sasha-banks-vs-nia-jax-and-tamina-the-roy/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=January 14, 2019|accessdate=January 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115083430/https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/01/14/1-14-powells-wwe-raw-tv-review-dean-ambrose-vs-bobby-lashley-vs-seth-rollins-in-a-triple-threat-for-the-intercontinental-championship-ronda-rousey-and-sasha-banks-vs-nia-jax-and-tamina-the-roy/|archive-date=January 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAmbrose entered the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|2019 Royal Rumble match]] at number 14, but was eliminated by [[Aleister Black]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=WWE Royal Rumble 2019 Kickoff Show live review: Rusev vs. Shinsuke Nakamura for the U.S. Championship, Buddy Murphy vs. Hideo Itami vs. Kalisto vs. Akira Tozawa for the WWE Cruiserweight Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/01/27/wwe-royal-rumble-2019-kickoff-show-live-review-rusev-vs-shinsuke-nakamura-for-the-u-s-championship-buddy-murphy-vs-hideo-itami-vs-kalisto-vs-akira-tozawa-for-the-wwe-cruiserweight-championship/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=January 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190128083409/https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/01/27/wwe-royal-rumble-2019-kickoff-show-live-review-rusev-vs-shinsuke-nakamura-for-the-u-s-championship-buddy-murphy-vs-hideo-itami-vs-kalisto-vs-akira-tozawa-for-the-wwe-cruiserweight-championship/|archive-date=January 28, 2019|url-status=live|date=January 27, 2019}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', he interrupted Royal Rumble winner Rollins and Triple H, proclaiming that Rollins never defeated him clean without interference and provoking Triple H into booking them in a match, which Ambrose subsequently lost.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/01/28/12-28-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-post-royal-rumble-episode-including-seth-rollins-rumble-victory/|title=1/28 WWE Raw Results: Keller's report on post-Royal Rumble episode including Seth Rollins Rumble victory|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Wade|last=Keller|date=January 28, 2019|accessdate=February 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202153914/https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/01/28/12-28-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-post-royal-rumble-episode-including-seth-rollins-rumble-victory/|archive-date=February 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A few hours after ''Raw'' went off the air, it was reported that Ambrose had informed WWE officials that he would not be renewing his contract and would be leaving the company shortly after [[WrestleMania 35]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/dean-ambrose-finishing-with-wwe/|title=Dean Ambrose Reportedly Finishing Up With WWE After WrestleMania|first=Ryan|last=Satin|date=January 29, 2019|access-date=January 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130110510/http://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/dean-ambrose-finishing-with-wwe/|archive-date=January 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-news-rumors-dean-ambrose-will-leave-the-company-after-wrestlemania-35/|title=WWE news, rumors: Dean Ambrose will leave the company after WrestleMania 35|website=CBSSports.com|access-date=January 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130111753/https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-news-rumors-dean-ambrose-will-leave-the-company-after-wrestlemania-35/|archive-date=January 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> WWE subsequently confirmed his decision in a statement.<ref name=\"wwedeparture\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/01/29/wwe-confirms-pwtorch-report-that-dean-ambrose-is-leaving-wwe-in-april-when-his-contract-expires-aew-speculation/ |title=WWE confirms PWTorch report that Dean Ambrose may be leaving WWE in April when his contract expires, AEW speculation |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130110222/https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/01/29/wwe-confirms-pwtorch-report-that-dean-ambrose-is-leaving-wwe-in-april-when-his-contract-expires-aew-speculation/ |archive-date=January 30, 2019 |url-status=live |date=January 29, 2019 }}</ref> It was reported that he had been offered an improved contract by WWE, which he turned down due to long-standing frustration with the creative direction of his character and a particular dislike of the \"[[wikt:hokey|hokey]]\" material he had been given.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/01/29/dean-ambrose-leaving-wwe-shortly-after-wrestlemania-when-his-contract-expires-in-april/ |title=Dean Ambrose leaving WWE shortly after WrestleMania when his contract expires in April |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129221743/https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/01/29/dean-ambrose-leaving-wwe-shortly-after-wrestlemania-when-his-contract-expires-in-april/ |archive-date=January 29, 2019 |url-status=live |date=January 29, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nAfter weeks of teasing a reunion,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/02/11/2-11-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-becky-lynch-invited-back-seth-rollins-responds-to-brock-lesnar-angles-next-step-riot-wants-ronda/|title=2/11 WWE Raw Results: Keller's report on Becky Lynch invited back, Seth Rollins responds to Brock Lesnar, Angle's next step, Riot wants Ronda|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Wade|last=Keller|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212190342/https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/02/11/2-11-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-becky-lynch-invited-back-seth-rollins-responds-to-brock-lesnar-angles-next-step-riot-wants-ronda/|archive-date=February 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=WWE RAW REPORT: GOOD NEWS FROM ROMAN REIGNS, ARE BIRTHDAY CELEBRATIONS THE NEW CONTRACT SIGNINGS?, A REUNION?, AND MORE|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=124452&p=3|publisher=PWInsider|accessdate=February 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226111419/https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=124452&p=3|archive-date=February 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ambrose reunited with Rollins and the recently returned Reigns on the March 4 episode of ''Raw'', after they assisted Ambrose from an attack by Baron Corbin, Bobby Lashley, Drew McIntyre, and [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias]] the previous week, reverting Ambrose to a face once again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/03/04/3-4-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-batista-follow-up-rouseys-championship-status-shield-reunion-che-jost-from-snl-weekend-update-guest-host/|title=3/4 WWE Raw Results: Keller's report on Batista follow-up, Rousey's championship status, Shield reunion, Che & Jost from SNL Weekend Update guest host|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Wade|last=Keller|authorlink=Wade Keller|date=March 4, 2019|accessdate=March 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306043026/https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/03/04/3-4-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-batista-follow-up-rouseys-championship-status-shield-reunion-che-jost-from-snl-weekend-update-guest-host/|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At [[Fastlane (2019)|Fastlane]] on March 10, The Shield defeated the team of McIntyre, Lashley, and Corbin.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=The Shield def. Drew McIntyre, Bobby Lashley & Baron Corbin|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwefastlane/2019/the-shield-vs-baron-corbin-drew-mcintyre-bobby-lashley-results|work=WWE|accessdate=March 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327092631/https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwefastlane/2019/the-shield-vs-baron-corbin-drew-mcintyre-bobby-lashley-results|archive-date=March 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In his final singles matches in WWE, Ambrose would subsequently lose to McIntyre several times on ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/03/11/3-11-powells-wwe-raw-tv-review-the-shields-farewell-batista-and-triple-h-finn-balor-vs-bobby-lashley-for-the-intercontinental-championship-all-roads-lead-to-wrestlemania-coming-out-of-wwe-fas/|title=3/11 Powell's WWE Raw TV Review: The Shield's farewell, Batista and Triple H, Finn Balor vs. Bobby Lashley for the Intercontinental Championship, all roads lead to WrestleMania coming out of WWE Fastlane|date=March 11, 2019|last=Powell|first=Jason|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=March 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327091750/https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/03/11/3-11-powells-wwe-raw-tv-review-the-shields-farewell-batista-and-triple-h-finn-balor-vs-bobby-lashley-for-the-intercontinental-championship-all-roads-lead-to-wrestlemania-coming-out-of-wwe-fas/|archive-date=March 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw03252019\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/03/25/3-25-powells-wwe-raw-tv-review-ronda-rousey-becky-lynch-and-charlotte-flair-face-riott-squad-in-beat-the-clock-challenge-matches-kurt-angle-vs-samoa-joe-the-penultimate-edition-before-wrestlem/|title=3/25 Powell's WWE Raw TV Review: Ronda Rousey, Becky Lynch, and Charlotte Flair face Riott Squad in Beat The Clock Challenge matches, Kurt Angle vs. Samoa Joe, the penultimate edition before WrestleMania 35|date=March 25, 2019|last=Powell|first=Jason|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn the April 8 episode of ''Raw'', Ambrose was scheduled to face Bobby Lashley in what was billed as Ambrose's last match on ''Raw''. However, the match never took place as Lashley insulted Ambrose's wife, [[Renee Young]], resulting in a brawl that ended with Ambrose being slammed through the announce table.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/04/08/4-8-powells-wwe-raw-tv-review-the-night-after-wrestlemania-35-edition-featuring-new-raw-and-smackdown-womens-champion-becky-lynch-new-wwe-universal-champion-seth-rollins-new-intercontinental-ch/|title=4/8 Powell's WWE Raw TV Review: The night after WrestleMania 35 edition featuring new Raw and Smackdown Women's Champion Becky Lynch, new WWE Universal Champion Seth Rollins, new Intercontinental Champion Finn Balor, and new Raw Tag Champions Zack Ryder and Curt Hawkins|date=April 8, 2019|last=Powell|first=Jason|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=April 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409081336/https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/04/08/4-8-powells-wwe-raw-tv-review-the-night-after-wrestlemania-35-edition-featuring-new-raw-and-smackdown-womens-champion-becky-lynch-new-wwe-universal-champion-seth-rollins-new-intercontinental-ch/|archive-date=April 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After ''Raw'' went off the air, Ambrose joined Rollins and Reigns to address the fans, thank them for their support, and comment on his past accomplishments before celebrating with his Shield teammates.<ref>{{cite web|title=DEAN AMBROSE SAYS GOODBYE AFTER RAW|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/125576/dean-ambrose-says-goodbye-after-raw.html?p=1|first=Andru|last=Edwards|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=April 9, 2019|work=PWInsider}}</ref> The following week on ''Raw'', he made another appearance after the show went off the air.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/post-raw-fight-size-update-aj-styles-joins-raw-wwe-spoils-usos-switch-lars-lays-out-rey-more|title=Post-Raw Fight Size Update: Ambrose After Raw, WWE Spoils Usos Switch, Lars Lays Out Rey, More|work=Fightful|first=Jeremy|last=Lambert|date=April 15, 2019|accessdate=April 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416055411/https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/post-raw-fight-size-update-aj-styles-joins-raw-wwe-spoils-usos-switch-lars-lays-out-rey-more|archive-date=April 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> His final contractual match occurred at a special event called [[WWE The Shield's Final Chapter|The Shield's Final Chapter]] on April 21, where he, Reigns, and Rollins defeated the team of Corbin, Lashley, and McIntyre.<ref name=\"ShieldFinal\">{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=WWE \"The Shield's Final Chapter\" results: Powell's live review of Roman Reigns, Seth Rollins, and Dean Ambrose vs. Drew McIntyre, Bobby Lashley, and Baron Corbin, Finn Balor defends the Intercontinental Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/04/21/wwe-the-shields-final-chapter-results-powells-live-review-of-roman-reigns-seth-rollins-and-dean-ambrose-vs-drew-mcintyre-bobby-lashley-and-baron-corbin-finn-balor-defends-the-interconti/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=April 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422014100/https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/04/21/wwe-the-shields-final-chapter-results-powells-live-review-of-roman-reigns-seth-rollins-and-dean-ambrose-vs-drew-mcintyre-bobby-lashley-and-baron-corbin-finn-balor-defends-the-interconti/|archive-date=April 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> His contract expired on April 30.<ref name=TIJpodcast>{{cite web |last1=Rush |first1=Jeff |title=Podcast Recap: Talk Is Jericho with Jon Moxley \u2013 a detailed account of the final year of Dean Ambrose in WWE, how and why his departure took place, his future in AEW |url=https://www.pwpodcasts.com/2019/05/30/podcast-recap-talk-is-jericho-with-jon-moxley-a-detailed-account-of-the-final-year-of-dean-ambrose-in-wwe-how-and-why-his-departure-took-place-his-future-in-aew/ |website=pwpodcasts.com |accessdate=June 5, 2019|date=May 30, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOn Chris Jericho's ''Talk is Jericho'' podcast in May 2019, Good recounted his departure from WWE, though he began by saying he was grateful for his time there, and cited achieving success. He decided to leave WWE after Vince McMahon made him give a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#promo|promo]] on ''Raw'' where his character would get inoculated from various diseases out of fear of catching a virus from the fans.<ref name=\"Raw20181126\"/> Good felt after this segment that his character was irreparably damaged.<ref name=TIJpodcast/> He left WWE citing the cause as mental and emotional exhaustion after six years of explaining to McMahon how his ideas for Good's character were \"stupid\". Due to McMahon's control over the company, Good had to follow McMahon's writing, which left him unhappy. Good came to dread promos, which were previously his favorite part of performing as a wrestler, to the point of feeling physically ill.<ref name=TIJpodcast/> His experience was corroborated by both Jericho and various anonymous WWE wrestlers and staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/exclusives/exclusive-backstage-wwe-news-reactions-jon-moxley-talk-jericho-interview|title=Exclusive: Backstage WWE News On Reactions To Jon Moxley Talk Is Jericho Interview|work=Fightful|first=Sean Ross|last=Sapp|date=June 3, 2019|accessdate=June 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== All Elite Wrestling (2019\u2013present) ===\nOn May 1, Good posted a video on Twitter, promoting the return of his Jon Moxley gimmick.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JonMoxley/status/1123438186410205184|title=Jon Moxley on Twitter|date=May 1, 2019|accessdate=May 1, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501105817/https://twitter.com/JonMoxley/status/1123438186410205184|archivedate=May 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On May 25, Moxley made his unannounced debut for [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW) during their [[ Double or Nothing (2019)| Double or Nothing]] event, attacking Chris Jericho, [[Kenny Omega]], and the referee after Jericho and Omega's main event match.<ref>{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=AEW Double Or Nothing results: Powell's live review of Kenny Omega vs. Chris Jericho, The Young Bucks vs. Pentagon Jr. and Fenix for the AAA Tag Titles, Cody vs. Dustin Rhodes, Britt Baker vs. Nyla Rose vs. Kylie Rae|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/05/25/aew-double-or-nothing-results-powells-live-review-of-kenny-omega-vs-chris-jericho-the-young-bucks-vs-pentagon-jr-and-fenix-for-the-aaa-tag-titles-cody-vs-dustin-rhodes-britt-baker-vs-nyla-r/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=May 25, 2019|date=May 25, 2019}}</ref> Shortly after, it was announced that Moxley had signed a multi-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allelitewrestling.com/post/aew-signs-superstar-jon-moxley-to-multi-year-deal|title=AEW Signs Superstar Jon Moxley to Multi-Year Deal|publisher=[[All Elite Wrestling]]|date=May 26, 2019|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref> Moxley had his AEW debut match at the [[AEW Fyter Fest|Fyter Fest]] pay-per-view in June, where he defeated [[Joey Janela]] in an [[Professional wrestling match types#No Disqualification match|unsanctioned match]].<ref name=\"Fyter Fest\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=6/29 AEW Fyter Fest results: Powell's live review of Kenny Omega and The Young Bucks vs. Pentagon Jr., Fenix, and Laredo Kid, Jon Moxley vs. Joey Janela in an unsanctioned match, Cody vs. Darby Allin, Cima vs. Christopher Daniels|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/06/29/6-29-aew-fyter-fest-results-powells-live-review-of-kenny-omega-and-the-young-bucks-vs-pentagon-jr-fenix-and-laredo-kid-jon-moxley-vs-joey-janela-in-an-unsanctioned-match-cody-vs-darby-allin/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=June 29, 2019|date=June 29, 2019}}</ref> After the match, Moxley was attacked by Omega in retaliation for his previous assault.<ref name=\"Fyter Fest\"/> A match between the two was scheduled for [[AEW All Out|All Out]] on August 31.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-news/jon-moxley-vs-kenny-omega-set-aew-all-out-285921|title=Jon Moxley vs. Kenny Omega set for AEW All Out|first=Joseph|last=Currier|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|website=F4WOnline.com|date=June 13, 2019|accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref> However, on August 23, Moxley was forced to pull out from the event after being diagnosed with a [[Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus|MRSA]] staph infection in his elbow, and would undergo surgery to remove it. AEW subsequently revealed [[Neville (wrestler)|Pac]] as Moxley's replacement at All Out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/129003/jon-moxley-off-aew-all-out-ppv.html?p=1|title=Moxley Off AEW All Out PPV|publisher=PWInsider|first=Mike|last=Johnson|date=August 23, 2019|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/129004/the-former-neville-pac-vs-kenny-omega-set-for-all-aew-all-out.html?p=1|title=The Former Neville, Pac Vs. Kenny Omega Set For AEW All Out|first=Mike|last=Johnson|publisher=PWInsider|date=August 23, 2019|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref> The match was subsequently rescheduled for the [[AEW Full Gear|Full Gear]] event on November 9.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tedesco|first=Mike|title=Jon Moxley vs. Kenny Omega made official for AEW Full Gear on November 9 from Baltimore|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/misc-news/137218-jon-moxley-vs-kenny-omega-made-official-for-aew-full-gear-on-november-9-from-baltimore/|publisher=WrestleView|date=September 4, 2019|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref> Moxley made his return on October 2, during the inaugural episode of ''[[AEW Dynamite]]'', attacking Omega during the latter's main event match.<ref>{{cite web|title=AEW Dynamite results, recap, grades: Jon Moxley returns, Jack Hager debuts in first TNT episode|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/aew-dynamite-results-recap-grades-jon-moxley-returns-jack-hager-debuts-in-first-tnt-episode/|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|date=October 2, 2019|accessdate=October 3, 2019}}</ref> On the following episode of ''Dynamite'', Moxley competed in his first official AEW match, defeating [[Shawn Spears]].{{efn|In AEW, unsanctioned matches do not count towards a wrestler's official win-loss record.}}<ref>{{cite web|url= https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/10/09/10-09-aew-dynamite-tv-results-barnetts-live-review-of-chris-jericho-and-sammy-guevara-vs-hangman-page-and-dustin-rhodes-jon-moxley-vs-shawn-spears-the-young-bucks-vs-private-party-in-an-a/|title= 10/09 AEW Dynamite TV results: Barnett's live review of Chris Jericho and Sammy Guevara vs. Hangman Page and Dustin Rhodes, Jon Moxley vs. Shawn Spears, The Young Bucks vs. Private Party in an AEW Tag Title tournament match, Riho and Britt Baker vs. Bea Priestly and Emi Sakura|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jake|last=Barnett|accessdate=October 10, 2019|date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> On November 9 at Full Gear, Moxley defeated Omega in an unsanctioned [[Lights Out match]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-results/aew-dynamite-live-results-tag-team-title-tournament-finals-296166|title=AEW DYNAMITE LIVE RESULTS: TAG TEAM TITLE TOURNAMENT FINALS|publisher=Wrestling Observer|website=f4wonline.com|first=Ethan|last=Renner|date=October 30, 2019|accessdate=October 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Full Gear\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/11/09/aew-full-gear-results-powells-live-review-of-chris-jericho-vs-cody-for-the-aew-championship-kenny-omega-vs-jon-moxley-hangman-page-vs-pac-riho-vs-emi-sakura-for-the-aew-womens-championship/|title=AEW Full Gear results: Powell's live review of Chris Jericho vs. Cody for the AEW Championship, Kenny Omega vs. Jon Moxley, Hangman Page vs. Pac, Riho vs. Emi Sakura for the AEW Women's Championship, The Young Bucks vs. Santana and Ortiz|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jason|last=Powell|date=November 9, 2019|accessdate=November 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December, Moxley began a storyline with [[AEW World Championship|AEW World Champion]] Chris Jericho and his stable [[The Inner Circle (professional wrestling)|The Inner Circle]] when Jericho invited Moxley to join the group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allelitewrestling.com/post/aew-dynamite-results-december-11-2019|title=AEW DYNAMITE Results December 11, 2019|work=www.allelitewrestling.com|date=December 11, 2019|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allelitewrestling.com/post/aew-dynamite-results-december-18-2019|title=AEW DYNAMITE Results December 18, 2019|work=www.allelitewrestling.com|date=December 18, 2019|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref> On the January 7, 2020 episode of ''Dynamite'', Moxley initially accepted the proposal and seemingly joined the group, before revealing it was a ploy and turning on them moments later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allelitewrestling.com/post/aew-dynamite-results-january-8-2020|title=AEW DYNAMITE Results January 8, 2020|work=allelitewrestling.com|date=January 8, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> On the January 22 episode of ''Dynamite'', Moxley defeated Pac to become the number one contender for Jericho's championship at [[AEW Revolution|Revolution]] on February 29,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-news/spoiler-notes-and-results-jericho-cruise-aew-dynamite-taping-302301|title=Spoiler notes and results from Jericho cruise AEW Dynamite taping|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|first=Bryan|last=Rose|date=January 21, 2020|accessdate=January 22, 2020}}</ref> where he defeated Jericho to win the AEW World Championship, becoming the first person to be champion in both AEW and NJPW simultaneously.<ref name=\"Revolution\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/02/29/aew-revolution-results-powells-live-review-of-chris-jericho-vs-jon-moxley-for-the-aew-championship-kenny-omega-and-hangman-page-vs-the-young-bucks-for-the-aew-tag-titles-cody-vs-mjf-nyla-rose/|title=AEW Revolution results: Powell's live review of Chris Jericho vs. Jon Moxley for the AEW Championship, Kenny Omega and Hangman Page vs. The Young Bucks for the AEW Tag Titles, Cody vs. MJF, Nyla Rose vs. Kris Statlander for the AEW Women's Championship, Pac vs. Orange Cassidy|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jason|last=Powell|date=February 29, 2020|accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> On the following episode of ''Dynamite'', Moxley was attacked and thrown off the stage by The Inner Circle, giving him a [[kayfabe]] injury.<ref name=\"Dynamite03042020\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/03/04/3-4-aew-dynamite-tv-results-powells-live-review-of-jon-moxley-and-darby-allin-vs-chris-jericho-and-sammy-guevara-pac-vs-chuck-taylor-colt-cabana-and-scu-vs-the-dark-order-jake-hager-vs-qt-ma/|title=3/4 AEW Dynamite TV results: Powell's live review of Jon Moxley and Darby Allin vs. Chris Jericho and Sammy Guevara, Pac vs. Chuck Taylor, Colt Cabana and SCU vs. The Dark Order, Jake Hager vs. QT Marshall, Big Swole vs. Leva Bates|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jason|last=Powell|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/03/11/3-11-aew-dynamite-tv-results-powells-live-review-of-hangman-page-and-a-mystery-partner-vs-chris-jericho-and-sammy-guevara-cody-vs-ortiz-mjf-the-butcher-and-the-blade-vs-jurassic-express/|title=3/11 AEW Dynamite TV results: Powell's live review of Hangman Page and a mystery partner vs. Chris Jericho and Sammy Guevara, Cody vs. Ortiz, MJF, The Butcher, and The Blade vs. Jurassic Express, \"Death Triangle\" Pac, Pentagon, and Fenix vs. Private Party and Joey Janela|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jason|last=Powell|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Moxley returned on the March 25 episode of ''Dynamite'', confronting Inner Circle member [[Jake Hager]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/03/25/3-25-aew-dynamite-tv-results-barnetts-live-review-of-chris-jericho-and-matt-hardy-confrontation-kenny-omega-vs-sammy-guevara-for-the-aaa-mega-championship-cody-vs-jimmy-havoc-br/|title=3/25 AEW Dynamite TV results: Barnett's live review of Chris Jericho and Matt Hardy confrontation, Kenny Omega vs. Sammy Guevara for the AAA Mega Championship, Cody vs. Jimmy Havoc, Brodie Lee makes his in-ring debut|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jason|last=Powell|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> resulting in a [[Empty arena match|empty arena]] no holds barred match for the AEW World Championship being arranged for the April 15 episode of ''Dynamite'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-news/no-holds-barred-aew-title-match-announced-april-15th-dynamite-307906|title=No holds barred AEW title match announced for April 15th Dynamite|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|first=Bryan|last=Rose|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> which Moxley won in his first championship defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/15/4-15-aew-dynamite-tv-results-barnetts-live-review-of-jon-moxley-vs-jake-hager-in-a-no-holds-barred-empty-arena-match-for-the-aew-title-colt-cabana-vs-lance-archer-in-a-tnt-title-tournament-quart/|title=4/15 AEW Dynamite TV results: Barnett\u2019s live review of Jon Moxley vs. Jake Hager in a No Holds Barred empty arena match for the AEW Title, Colt Cabana vs. Lance Archer in a TNT Title tournament quarterfinal match, Chuck Taylor vs. Kip Sabian, Sammy Guevara vs. Sugar D|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jason|last=Powell|date=April 15, 2020|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== New Japan Pro-Wrestling (2019\u2013present) ===\nAfter weeks of [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW) airing videos of a mystery man targeting [[IWGP United States Championship|IWGP United States Champion]] [[Juice Robinson]], Moxley was revealed as the culprit in May 2019, challenging Robinson for a title match at the final night of the [[Best of the Super Juniors#2019|Best of the Super Juniors 26]] tournament on June 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/51628|title=Jon Moxley to challenge Juice Robinson for the IWGP US Heavyweight Championship!|date=May 28, 2019|publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/51588|title=Jon Moxley to make first NJPW appearance on June 5|date=May 27, 2019|publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref> At the event, he defeated Robinson in his NJPW in-ring debut to win the IWGP United States Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/44585?showResult=1|title=2019.06.03 BEST OF THE SUPER Jr.26 FINAL Night15 {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|accessdate=June 5, 2019|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=English}}</ref> Following Moxley's original challenge, AEW CEO [[Tony Khan (sports executive)|Tony Khan]] stated that Moxley will be able to take independent and international bookings during the summer before AEW's television deal started in the fall of that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/jon-moxley-revealed-njpw-mystery-man-targeting-juice-robinson|title=Jon Moxley Revealed As NJPW Mystery Man Targeting Juice Robinson|last=Lambert|first=Jeremy|date=May 27, 2019|publisher=Fightful.com|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref> However during an interview with ''[[Nikkan Sports]]'', Good clarified that \"[translated] there is no problem in fighting in New Japan while belonging to AEW. In the future, I can always show up in Japan and have matches.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nikkansports.com/battle/column/pwrestling/news/201908020000048.html?Page=1|title=\u30e2\u30af\u30b9\u30ea\u30fc\u300c\u771f\u5263\u52dd\u8ca0\u306e\u5834\u300d\u4ffa\u306e\u539f\u70b9\uff0f\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc|work=[[Nikkan Sports]]|date=August 8, 2019|accessdate=August 8, 2019|language=Japanese}}</ref> At [[Dominion 6.9 in Osaka-jo Hall (2019)|Dominion 6.9 in Osaka-jo Hall]] on June 9, Moxley defeated [[Shota Umino]] before declaring himself as an entrant in the [[G1 Climax (2019)|2019 G1 Climax]] tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/jon-moxley-shingo-takagi-declare-themselves-njpw-g1-climax-285611|last=Currier|first=Joseph|title=Jon Moxley, Shingo Takagi declare themselves for NJPW G1 Climax|date=June 9, 2019|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|accessdate=June 9, 2019}}</ref> From July to August, Moxley competed in the B Block of the G1 Climax, which he ended with five wins<ref name=\"NJPW071319\">{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/47796?showResult=1|title=2019.07.13 G1 CLIMAX 29 Night 2 {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|accessdate=July 22, 2019|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"NJPW071519\">{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/47800?showResult=1|title=2019.07.15 G1 CLIMAX 29 Night 4 {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|accessdate=July 22, 2019|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"NJPW071919\">{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/47810?showResult=1|title=2019.07.19 G1 CLIMAX 29 Night 6 {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|accessdate=July 22, 2019|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"NJPW072419\">{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/47802?showResult=1|title=2019.07.24 G1 CLIMAX 29 Night 8 {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|accessdate=July 24, 2019|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=English}}</ref> and four losses,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/47807?showResult=1|title=2019.08.01 G1 CLIMAX 29 Night 12 {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|accessdate=August 2, 2019|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-results/njpw-g1-climax-29-night-14-results-tetsuya-naito-vs-shingo-takagi-289366|title=NJPW G1 Climax 29 Night 14 Results: Tetsuya Naito vs. Shingo Takagi|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|first=Ethan|last=Renner|date=August 4, 2019|accessdate=August 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/47809?showResult=1|title=2019.08.08 G1 CLIMAX Night 16 {{!}} NEW JAPAN PRO-WRESTLING|publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|date=August 8, 2019|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-results/njpw-g1-climax-29-night-18-results-tetsuya-naito-vs-jay-white-289826|title=NJPW G1 Climax 29 Night 18 Results: Tetsuya Naito vs. Jay White|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|first=Ethan|last=Renner|date=August 11, 2019|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> failing to advance to the tournament finals with a final standing of 10 points.\n\nOn October 13, Moxley was stripped of the United States Championship as he was unable to wrestle in a scheduled championship defense against Robinson due to travel issues stemming from [[Typhoon Hagibis (2019)|Typhoon Hagibis]]. He was replaced by [[Lance Archer]], who defeated Robinson to win the vacant title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/62455|title=Jon Moxley unable to compete at Sumo Hall, US Championship vacated|publisher=New Japan Pro-Wrestling|website=njpw1972.com|date=October 14, 2019|accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/full-card-announced-njpw-king-pro-wrestling-293111 |title=Full card announced for NJPW King of Pro Wrestling |last=Rose |first=Bryan |date=September 23, 2019 |website=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.njpw1972.com/62458 |title=Card changes made to King of Pro Wrestling |publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] |access-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> On December 9, Moxley returned and interrupted Archer after his final match in the [[World Tag League (NJPW)#2019|2019 World Tag League]] tournament, attacking both Archer and his [[Suzuki-gun]] teammate [[Minoru Suzuki]] and challenging Archer to a [[Texas Deathmatch]] for the IWGP United States Heavyweight Championship at [[Wrestle Kingdom 14]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-results/njpw-world-tag-league-finals-live-results-winners-are-crowned-299041|title=NJPW World Tag League finals live results: Winners are crowned|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|first=Ethan|last=Renner|date=December 7, 2019|accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref> During the first night of Wrestle Kingdom on January 4, 2020, Moxley defeated Archer to win the championship for the second time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/49954?showResult=1|title=2020.01.04 WRESTLE KINGDOM in TOKYO DOME {{!}} Night 1|publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|date=January 4, 2020|accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref> The following night, Moxley successfully retained the championship against Robinson, ending their long-running feud. After the match, he was confronted and beaten down by Suzuki.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/49956?showResult=1|title=2020.01.05 WRESTLE KINGDOM in TOKYO DOME night 2|publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|date=January 5, 2020|accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref> Moxley successfully defended the championship against Suzuki at [[The New Beginning in Osaka (2020)|The New Beginning in Osaka]] in February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/63551?showResult=1|title=2020.02.09 THE NEW BEGINNING in OSAKA|work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Return to the independent circuit (2019\u20132020)===\nFrom June 2019 onwards, Moxley has made sporadic appearances on several [[Independent circuit|independent]] promotions such as [[Northeast Wrestling]] (NEW)<ref name=\"NEW\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/jon-moxley-battles-big-cass-and-enzo-new-six-flags-slam-fest|title=Jon Moxley Battles Big Cass And Enzo At NEW Six Flags Slam Fest|work=Fightful|first=Jeremy|last=Lambert|date=June 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/results/new-prison-break-live-results-and-discussion-816|title=NEW Prison Break Results (8/16): Moxley vs. Pentagon Jr, Matt Taven Surprise, Enzo & Cass, More|work=Fightful|first=Jeremy|last=Lambert|date=August 16, 2019|accessdate=August 16, 2019}}</ref> and Future Stars of Wrestling (FSW).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/jon-moxley-surprise-killer-kross/#.XVQUd4o_WhA|title=Jon Moxley Makes Surprise Indie Appearance To Answer Killer Kross' Challenge|first=Ryan|last=Satin|authorlink=Ryan Satin|date=July 6, 2019|accessdate=July 6, 2019|work=Pro Wrestling Sheet}}</ref>\n\n== Professional wrestling style, persona, and reception ==\n{{multiple image\n|align=right\n|width=145\n|direction=vertical\n|image1=Ambrose Dirty Deeds.jpg\n|image2=Dirty Deeds Raw 2015.jpg\n|footer=Good's finishing move, the ''Dirty Deeds'', later known as the ''Death Rider'' and ''Paradigm Shift'', has been used in two different variations, first utilzing a [[Professional wrestling throws#Headlock driver|headlock driver]] (top), before changing it to a [[DDT (professional wrestling)#Double underhook DDT|double underhook DDT]] in 2014 (bottom)\n}}\n{{quote box|width=25%|align=left|quote=\"Unfortunately for the company, the same fans that rejected Reigns ''love'' Ambrose. [...] Ambrose, as a physically smaller performer in a land where giants are preferred, is the true [[dark horse]], both on camera and behind the scenes.\"|source=<small>[[CNET]] writer Daniel Van Boom on Ambrose's popularity compared to main event star Roman Reigns<ref>{{cite web|last1=Van Boom|first1=Daniel|title=This weekend WWE will face its toughest opponent: The wrestling audience|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/wwe-network-roadblock-how-to-watch|website=[[CNET]]|accessdate=December 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311235402/http://www.cnet.com/news/wwe-network-roadblock-how-to-watch/|archive-date=March 11, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref></small>}}\n\nAfter debuting on WWE television with The Shield, Good, as Dean Ambrose, utilized a [[Professional wrestling throws#Headlock driver|headlock driver]], dubbed ''Dirty Deeds'', as a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#finisher|finishing maneuver]].<ref name=vsWyattsIII>{{cite web|title=Main Event: Wyatts and Shield complete a trilogy|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2014/04/09/21593101.html|date=April 9, 2014|last=Howell|first=Nolan|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=April 27, 2014|quote=Ambrose with the Dirty Deeds headlock driver. Winners by pinfall: The Shield|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427145059/http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2014/04/09/21593101.html|archive-date=April 27, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwesmackdownreport/article_77321.shtml|title=Parks's WWE SmackDown report 3/28: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Friday show, including Bray Wyatt vs. Big Show|date=March 28, 2014|last=Parks|first=Greg|accessdate=October 25, 2014|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140713102654/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwesmackdownreport/article_77321.shtml|archive-date=July 13, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Soon after The Shield's initial split in 2014, Ambrose didn't feel confortable using a headlock driver on some wrestlers, so he began using a [[DDT (professional wrestling)#Double underhook DDT|double underhook DDT]] as his ''Dirty Deeds'' finisher.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beas |first1=Iv\u00e1n |title=Jon Moxley, sobre su finisher: 'Para m\u00ed es un maldito DDT' |url=https://solowrestling.mundodeportivo.com/new/87198-jon-moxley-finisher-wwe-ddt |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |publisher=[[Solowrestling.com]]|date=February 1, 2020 |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=October 27, 2014|title=Oct, 27, 2014 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: Latest D-Day for WWE Network, Velasquez down, life and times of Ox Baker, more!|journal=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|issn=1083-9593|page=48|quote=Ambrose has been using the double arm DDT instead of the headlock DDT for his go-to move of late. The idea, at least right now, is to make the double arm DDT his finisher since nobody is doing it. Right now the idea is that it would still be called ''Dirty Deeds''.|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/39544-oct-27-2014-wrestling-observer-newsletter-latest-d-day-for-wwe-network-velasquez-down-life-and-times-of-ox-baker-more}}</ref> Upon his departure from WWE, Good renamed his finisher the ''Death Rider'' and debuted a [[DDT (professional wrestling)#Lifting DDT|lifting]] variant of the move.<ref name=\"NJPW\"/> Said lifting variant is dubbed the ''Paradigm Shift'' in AEW.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Radican|first1=Sean|title=RADICAN'S 6/29 AEW Fyter Fest report: Janela vs. Moxley, Cody vs. Allin, Young Bucks & Omega vs. Lucha Bros. & Kid main event|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/06/29/radicans-6-29-aew-fyter-fest-report-janela-vs-moxley-cody-vs-allin-young-bucks-omega-vs-lucha-bros-kid-main-event/|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=June 29, 2019|accessdate=June 29, 2019|quote=Moxley went back into the bucket. He got another bag and dumped more tacks into the ring. He then hit the Death Rider into the tacks. It's called the Paradigm Shift in AEW.}}</ref> During Ambrose's tenure in WWE's developmental territory Florida Championship Wrestling, he used William Regal's finishing moves the ''Knee Trembler'' (a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Knee lift|running knee lift]]) and the ''Regal Stretch'' (a [[Professional wrestling holds#Cross-legged STF|cross-legged arm trap STF]]) as a way to mock Regal during their feud.<ref name=\"FCW226\"/> Good's ring name of Jon Moxley was given to him by a promoter who had misheard the name of [[James Van Der Beek]]'s character Jon Moxon in the 1999 film ''[[Varsity Blues (film)|Varsity Blues]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/wrestling/2020/02/20/jonathan-good-jon-moxley-name-origin|title=How did Jon Moxley get his name? AEW wrestler explains|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|first=Dan|last=Gartland|accessdate=February 26, 2020|date=February 20, 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\nReferred to as \"The Lunatic Fringe\" since his time in The Shield,<ref name=\"espn prof\" /> Ambrose's WWE gimmick has seen him characterized as a mentally unstable and unpredictable wildcard.<ref name=HortonWho>{{cite web|title=Dean Ambrose, Seth Rollins and Roman Reigns: Who are they and why did they help CM Punk?|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2012/dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-and-roman-reigns-who-are-they-and-why-did-they-help-punk|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=December 2, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917031635/http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/2012/dean-ambrose-seth-rollins-and-roman-reigns-who-are-they-and-why-did-they-help-punk|archive-date=September 17, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> His gimmick has been compared to [[Heath Ledger]]'s [[Joker (The Dark Knight)|portrayal of The Joker]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Radican|first=Sean|title=Radican's Take: Who is Dean Ambrose and how far can he go in WWE?|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/radicanstake/article_67047.shtml|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=December 6, 2012|access-date=February 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006014308/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/radicanstake/article_67047.shtml|archive-date=October 6, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Johnson|first=Mike|title=Why Talents Get Burnt Out, Extreme Rules, Ambrose the Joker and More|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/77633/why-talents-get-burnt-out-extreme-rules-ambrose-the-joker-and-more.html?p=1|publisher=PWInsider|date=May 18, 2013|access-date=February 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310180600/http://www.pwinsider.com/article/77633/why-talents-get-burnt-out-extreme-rules-ambrose-the-joker-and-more.html?p=1|archive-date=March 10, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> After becoming a villain in late 2018, Ambrose began proclaiming himself to be \"The Moral Compass of WWE\".<ref name=\"Wrestling Observer Newsletter\"/> His revamped character invited comparisons to [[Tom Hardy]]'s portrayal of [[Bane (DC Comics)|Bane]] from the 2012 film ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/wwe/news/14203/11571250/wwe-raw-dean-ambroses-swat-team-attacks-seth-rollins|title=WWE Raw: Dean Ambrose's SWAT team attacks Seth Rollins|last=Lake|first=Jefferson|date=December 4, 2018|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121220644/https://www.skysports.com/wwe/news/14203/11571250/wwe-raw-dean-ambroses-swat-team-attacks-seth-rollins|archive-date=January 21, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAmbrose's booking during his feuds with Seth Rollins and Bray Wyatt in 2014 was criticized by commentators, including James Caldwell of the ''Pro Wrestling Torch'', who stated that although \"he's a utility [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#main eventer|main eventer]]\", his lack of victories indicated that he was not a guy that WWE was positioning \"for a 2-3 year sustained run on top\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/caldwellstake/article_83364.shtml|title=DVD review: \"Destruction of The Shield\" \u2013 Historically Significant glimpse into WWE's next decade|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|date=February 17, 2015|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218043544/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/caldwellstake/article_83364.shtml|archive-date=February 18, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=February 18, 2015}}</ref> Ambrose's post-Shield run as a heroic character gained significant popularity, with him being cheered over fellow heroic character Roman Reigns when they faced off in three world title matches (Payback and Survivor Series in 2015 and Fastlane in 2016).<ref name=FL16>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-fastlane-2016-live-results-brock-lesnar-vs-roman-reigns-vs-dean-ambrose-207716|title=WWE Fastlane 2016 Live Results: Brock Lesnar vs. Roman Reigns vs. Dean Ambrose|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|first=Dave|last=Meltzer|date=February 21, 2016|accessdate=April 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160222091501/http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-fastlane-2016-live-results-brock-lesnar-vs-roman-reigns-vs-dean-ambrose-207716|archive-date=February 22, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_85054.shtml|title=Caldwell's Payback PPV Report 5/17: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of four-way WWE Title match, I Quit War, more|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=James|last=Caldwell|date=May 17, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304064943/http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wweppvs/article_85054.shtml|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title=11/22 Survivor Series Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete PPV Report ongoing-report/|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2015/11/22/1122-survivor-series-live-results-caldwells-ongoing-report/|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=November 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123083638/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2015/11/22/1122-survivor-series-live-results-caldwells-ongoing-report/|archive-date=November 23, 2015|url-status=live|date=November 23, 2015}}</ref> Ambrose was voted as the [[List of Pro Wrestling Illustrated awards#Most Popular Wrestler of the Year|Most Popular Wrestler of the Year]] by ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'' readers in 2014 and 2015.<ref name=PWI2014>{{cite journal|year=2015|title=Most Popular Wrestler of the Year|journal=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|volume=36|issue=2|pages=24\u201325}}</ref>\n\nGood's reversion to his Jon Moxley gimmick and subsequent debut at AEW's Double or Nothing after leaving WWE in 2019 was widely praised, with Phillip Martinez of ''[[Newsweek]]'' commenting that Good had caused \"the wrestling world to erupt\" after his surprise appearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/jon-moxley-injury-update-aew-all-out-replacement-kenny-omega-1455994|title=Jon Moxley Pulls Out Of AEW'S 'All Out' Due to Injury; Pac to Face Kenny Omega|work=[[Newsweek]]|first=Phillip|last=Martinez|date=August 23, 2019|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref> During this time, he was described by ''[[FanSided]]'' writer J.D. Olivia as \"the biggest star in the wrestling world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fansided.com/2019/07/29/the-resurrection-of-jon-moxley-njpw-g1-29-aew-dean-ambrose/|title=The resurrection of Jon Moxley|work=[[FanSided]]|first=J.D.|last=Olivia|date=July 29, 2019|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Moxley's match with [[Tomohiro Ishii]] during the G1 Climax in July 2019 was met with critical acclaim. ''[[Deadspin]]''{{'}}s Luis Paez-Pumar noted how the tournament offered an excellent platform for him to shine following his departure from WWE; he notably singled out his match against Ishii, calling it \"almost certainly Moxley's best singles match ever, under any name, but it felt significant in another sense. It was good, brutal fun to watch, but it also pointed a way forward for Moxley not just as An Attraction {{sic}}, but rather as a brilliant and brilliantly violent wrestler.\"<ref name=\"AmbroseIsDead\">{{cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/dean-ambrose-is-dead-but-jon-moxley-is-alive-and-well-1836599294|title=Dean Ambrose Is Dead, But Jon Moxley Is Alive And Well|last=Paez-Pumar|first=Luis|date=July 22, 2019|work=[[Deadspin]]|language=English|accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref> The match was also awarded [[List of professional wrestling matches rated 5 or more stars by Dave Meltzer|five stars]] by [[Dave Meltzer]] of the ''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://members.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-newsletter/july-29-2019-observer-newsletter-aew-announces-tv-details-more-97515|title=Wrestling Observer Newsletter July 29, 2019: AEW announces TV details and more|journal=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|first=Dave|last=Meltzer|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=July 29, 2019|accessdate=July 29, 2019}} {{subscription required}}</ref> with Meltzer remarking that \"I think this was the first time I ever saw a match where at the 17 second mark I already felt it was going to be a four star match\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/other-wrestling/dave-meltzers-2019-5-star-matches-okada-ospreay-moxley-300501|title=Dave Meltzer's 2019 5-star matches: Okada, Ospreay, Moxley|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|first=Josh|last=Nason|date=December 29, 2019|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Other media ==\nGood, as Dean Ambrose, appears as a playable character in the video games ''[[WWE 2K14]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/2k/wwe-2k14/wwe-2k14-full-roster-revealed|title='WWE 2K14' full roster revealed|date=September 19, 2013|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116034433/https://www.wwe.com/inside/2k/wwe-2k14/wwe-2k14-full-roster-revealed|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=January 6, 2019}}</ref> ''[[WWE 2K15]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/wikis/wwe-2k15/Rosters|title=Rosters - WWE 2K15 Wiki Guide|date=December 16, 2014|website=[[IGN]]|access-date=January 6, 2019}}</ref> ''[[WWE 2K16]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/2k/wwe-2k16/wwe-2k16-roster-playable-characters-superstars-divas|title=Superstars and Divas featured on WWE 2K16 roster list|date=August 10, 2015|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321095326/https://www.wwe.com/inside/2k/wwe-2k16/wwe-2k16-roster-playable-characters-superstars-divas|archive-date=March 21, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 6, 2019}}</ref> ''[[WWE 2K17]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k17/gallery/wwe-2k17-roster-art-photos|title=Photos: Find out who made the WWE 2K17 roster|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401063820/https://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k17/gallery/wwe-2k17-roster-art-photos|archive-date=April 1, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 6, 2019}}</ref> ''[[WWE 2K18]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k18/article/wwe-2k18-roster-playable-character-list|title=WWE 2K18 roster: Meet the Superstars joining the list of playable characters|last=Artus|first=Matthew|date=September 27, 2017|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107162419/http://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k18/article/wwe-2k18-roster-playable-character-list|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=November 4, 2017}}</ref> and ''[[WWE 2K19]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/wwe-2k19-roster-full-list-200-confirmed-wrestlers-/2900-2163/|title=WWE 2K19 Roster Full List: 200+ Confirmed Wrestlers & DLC Superstars|website=[[GameSpot]]|first=Mat|last=Elfring|date=October 11, 2018|accessdate=October 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013014404/https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/wwe-2k19-roster-full-list-200-confirmed-wrestlers-/2900-2163/|archive-date=October 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Smart Mark Video released ''Stories From the Streets: The Jon Moxley Story'', a DVD featuring several of Good's matches in CZW, HWA, and IPW, as well as a two-and-a-half hour [[Shoot (professional wrestling)#Shoot interview|shoot interview]] with Good.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://smartmarkvideo.com/jon-moxley-dvd-stories-the-streets-the-jon-moxley-story|title=Jon Moxley DVD \"Stories From The Streets: The Jon Moxley Story\"|work=smartmarkvideo.com|accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nUnder the Dean Ambrose name, Good made his acting debut in the 2015 [[action film]] ''[[12 Rounds 3: Lockdown]]'', in which he played detective John Shaw.<ref name=\"lockdown\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/dean-ambrose-wwe-studios-lionsgate-greenlight-actioner-lockdown-exclusive-1201283414/|title=WWE's Dean Ambrose to Star in Action Movie 'Lockdown' (Exclusive)|last=Graser|first=Marc|date=August 14, 2014|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140917202848/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/dean-ambrose-wwe-studios-lionsgate-greenlight-actioner-lockdown-exclusive-1201283414/|archive-date=September 17, 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/07/wwe-dean-ambrose-12-rounds-3-trailer|title=So many bullets fly in the trailer for '12 Rounds 3: Lockdown,' starring WWE's Dean Ambrose|work=[[USA Today]]|first=Nick|last=Schwartz|date=July 28, 2015|accessdate=February 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021253/https://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/07/wwe-dean-ambrose-12-rounds-3-trailer|archive-date=February 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The following year, Good made an uncredited [[cameo appearance]] in the WWE produced film ''[[Countdown (2016 film)|Countdown]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/wwe/254318/countdown-review|title=Countdown Review|work=[[Den of Geek]]|first=Gavin|last=Jasper|date=April 6, 2016|accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref> In May 2019, it was reported by ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' that Good had been cast as Randy Stone in ''[[Cagefighter: Worlds Collide]]'',<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/wwe/1125438/Dean-Ambrose-WWE-news-Harry-Potter-EastEnders-Roman-Reigns-Seth-Rollins-John-Cena |title = Dean Ambrose future REVEALED: WWE hero to co-star with Harry Potter and EastEnders stars|date = May 10, 2019}}</ref> an \"MMA-themed\" action film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/wwe-dean-ambrose-joins-cast-of-mma-movie-cagefighter-cannes-1202609736/|title=Former WWE Star Dean Ambrose Joins Cast Of MMA Movie 'Cagefighter'|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Andreas|last=Wiseman|date=May 8, 2019|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref> The film is scheduled for release on May 16, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fite.tv/watch/cagefighter-worlds-collide/2p715/|title=Cagefighter: Worlds Collide Movie Premeire|publisher=[[FITE TV]]|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Filmography===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[12 Rounds 3: Lockdown]]''\n|John Shaw\n|Credited as Dean Ambrose\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Countdown (2016 film)|Countdown]]''\n|Himself\n|Uncredited\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Cagefighter: Worlds Collide]]''\n|Randy Stone\n|Upcoming\n|-\n|}\n\n== Personal life ==\nGood began dating WWE backstage interviewer and on-air personality Renee Young in 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/wwe/blog/wwes-renee-young-confirms-she-is-dating-dean-ambrose|title=WWE's Renee Young Confirms She IS Dating Dean Ambrose!|publisher=[[MTV]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306072403/http://www.mtv.co.uk/wwe/blog/wwes-renee-young-confirms-she-is-dating-dean-ambrose|archive-date=March 6, 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=March 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-s-Dean-Ambrose-comments-on-dating-Renee-Young-43882|title=WWE's Dean Ambrose comments on dating Renee Young|date=September 2, 2015|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|access-date=September 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923195650/http://prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-s-Dean-Ambrose-comments-on-dating-Renee-Young-43882|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and they were married at their [[Las Vegas]] home<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/article/renee-young-raw-announce-team|title=Renee Young joins Raw announce team full-time|date=September 10, 2018|publisher=[[WWE]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181117132935/https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/article/renee-young-raw-announce-team|archive-date=November 17, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=January 25, 2019}}</ref> in an impromptu ceremony in the early hours of April 9, 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2017/04/12/renee-young-dean-ambrose-married-wwe|title=WWE's Renee Young and Dean Ambrose recently got married|last=Traina|first=Jimmy|date=April 12, 2017|magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413153602/https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2017/04/12/renee-young-dean-ambrose-married-wwe|archive-date=April 13, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGood has described himself as a [[Simple living|minimalist]]; after accepting a WWE contract offer, he drove to their Florida Championship Wrestling with nothing but some bags of clothes and the money in his pocket.<ref name=\"TMWFP\" /> He was roommates with fellow wrestler [[Big Cass]] during this time and later moved out when he was promoted to the main roster, leaving behind thousands of dollars worth of WWE merchandise sent by the company and telling Cass to \"give it to charity or something\".<ref name=\"TMWFP\" /> He then moved into his new apartment in Las Vegas, which he left unfurnished because he did not see the point of furnishing it when he would be away with WWE most of the time.<ref name=\"TMWFP\" />\n\nGood moved to [[Birmingham, Alabama]] for a time in 2018 in order to be closer to doctors during his recovery from his torn biceps, after which he contracted a [[Staphylococcal infection|staph infection]] that nearly killed him.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n{{multiple image\n|align=right\n|width=170\n|direction=vertical\n|image1=Dean Ambrose with belt.jpg\n|caption1=Moxley (as Dean Ambrose) is a former [[WWE Championship|WWE Champion]]...\n|image2=Ambrose USA Champion.jpg\n|caption2=...a former [[WWE United States Championship|United States Champion]], with his 351-day reign being the longest under the WWE banner...\n|image3=Dean Ambrose IC Champ 2017.jpg\n|caption3=...and a three-time [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Champion]]\n}}\n* '''[[All Elite Wrestling]]'''\n** [[AEW World Championship]] (1 time, current)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allelitewrestling.com/aew-world-championship-history|title=AEW World Championship Title History|publisher=All Elite Wrestling|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n* '''[[Combat Zone Wrestling]]'''\n**[[CZW World Heavyweight Championship]] ([[List of CZW World Heavyweight Champions|2 times]])<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=2067&bild=1&details=3|title=Dean Ambrose - Titles|website=Wrestlingdata.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105201948/https://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=2067&bild=1&details=3|archive-date=January 5, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.czwrestling.com/titlehistory/ |title=CZW World Heavyweight Championship reign history |publisher=CZWrestling.com |accessdate=May 17, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222162338/http://www.czwrestling.com/titlehistory/ |archivedate=December 22, 2010 }}</ref>\n* '''[[Full Impact Pro]]'''\n**[[FIP World Heavyweight Championship]] ([[FIP World Heavyweight Championship#Reigns|1 time]])<ref name=slam/><ref name=southernstampede2010/><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fullimpactpro.com/history/heavyweighthistory.htm|title=FIP World Heavyweight Championship title history|accessdate=April 10, 2010|publisher=[[Full Impact Pro]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006160130/http://fullimpactpro.com/history/heavyweighthistory.htm|archivedate=October 6, 2010}}</ref>\n* '''[[Heartland Wrestling Association]]'''\n**[[HWA Heavyweight Championship]] ([[HWA Heavyweight Championship#Title history|3 times]])<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/oh/hwa/hwa-h.html |title=HWA Heavyweight Championship History (Ohio) |access-date=March 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214164201/http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/oh/hwa/hwa-h.html |archive-date=December 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n** [[HWA Tag Team Championship]] ([[HWA Tag Team Championship#Title history|5 times]]) \u2013 with Jimmy Turner (1), [[Ric Byrne]] (1), Cody Hawk (1) and King Vu (2)<ref name=\"HWA\">{{cite web|url=http://hwaonline.com/hwatagteamtitles.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001003213/http://hwaonline.com/hwatagteamtitles.htm|title=Official HWA Tag Team Championship History|publisher=HWAOnline|archivedate=October 1, 2011|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n** Drake Younger Invitational Tournament (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=26&nr=1420|title=HWA Drake Younger Invitational Tournament (2009)|work=cagematch.net|accessdate=March 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302152523/https://www.cagematch.net/?id=26&nr=1420|archive-date=March 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* '''Mad-Pro Wrestling'''\n** MPW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=\":1\" />\n** MPW Tag Team Championship (1 times) \u2013 with Dustin Rayz<ref name=\":1\" />\n* '''Insanity Pro Wrestling'''\n** IPW World Heavyweight Championship{{efn|During Moxley's first reign, the title was called the IPW Grand Championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=titles&titel=1596|title=IPW World Heavyweight Title - List of champions|website=Wrestlingdata.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105202002/https://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=titles&titel=1596|archive-date=January 5, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref>}} (2 times)<ref name=\":1\" />\n** IPW Mid-American Championship (1 time)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* '''[[International Wrestling Association (Puerto Rico)|International Wrestling Association]]'''\n**[[IWA World Tag Team Championship|IWA Tag Team Championship]] ([[IWA World Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with Hade Vansen<ref name=\"IWA\"/><ref name=\":1\"/>\n*'''[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]'''\n**[[IWGP United States Championship]] (2 times, current)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/champions/iwgpus|title=IWGP United States Championship History|date=June 5, 2019|publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]|accessdate=June 5, 2019|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n* '''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** [[List of Pro Wrestling Illustrated awards#Feud of the Year|Feud of the Year]] (2014) {{small|vs. [[Seth Rollins]]}}<ref>{{cite journal|year=2015|journal=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|title=Feud of the Year|volume=36|issue=2|pages=22\u201323}}</ref> \n** [[List of Pro Wrestling Illustrated awards#Most Popular Wrestler of the Year|Most Popular Wrestler of the Year]] (2014, 2015)<ref name=PWI2014/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwi-online.com/pages/PWIawards.html#awards-most-popular-wrestler-of-the-year|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Awards|publisher=PWI-Online.com|accessdate=March 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121172943/http://www.pwi-online.com/pages/PWIawards.html#awards-most-popular-wrestler-of-the-year|archive-date=January 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n** Ranked No. 8 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|PWI 500]]'' in 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profightdb.com/pwi-500/2017.html|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2017|accessdate=August 30, 2017|work=The Internet Wrestling Database|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831132846/http://profightdb.com/pwi-500/2017.html|archive-date=August 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* '''''[[Sports Illustrated]]'''''\n** Wrestler of the Year (2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/wrestling/2019/12/27/best-wrestlers-of-the-year-2019|title=The Top 10 Male Wrestlers of 2019|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|first=Justin|last=Barrasso|date=December 28, 2019|accessdate=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''[[Westside Xtreme Wrestling]]'''\n**[[wXw World Tag Team Championship]] (1 time) \u2013 with [[Sami Callihan]]<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wxw-wrestling.com/index2.php?content=title_history&id=2|title=wXw World Tag Team Championship history|accessdate=September 11, 2010|publisher=[[Westside Xtreme Wrestling]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718124557/http://www.wxw-wrestling.com/index2.php?content=title_history&id=2|archivedate=July 18, 2011}}</ref>\n** wXw World Tag Team Title Tournament (2009) with Sami Callihan<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=35474|title=wXw True Colors|work=cagematch.net|accessdate=January 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190211141649/https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=35474|archive-date=February 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n*'''[[WWE]]'''\n**[[WWE Championship]]{{efn|When Ambrose won the title, it was known as the WWE World Heavyweight Championship. It was then shortened to WWE Championship in the lead up to the 2016 WWE draft, where he was drafted to SmackDown with the championship. After the Raw brand created the [[WWE Universal Championship]], the WWE Championship was again renamed to WWE World Championship.}} ([[List of WWE Champions|1 time]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/wwe-championship|title=WWE Championship|publisher=[[WWE]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629011310/http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/wwe-championship|archivedate=June 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**[[WWE Intercontinental Championship]] ([[List of WWE Intercontinental Champions|3 times]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/intercontinental|title=Intercontinental Championship|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116121547/https://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/intercontinental|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n**[[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of WWE Raw Tag Team Champions|2 times]]) \u2013 with Seth Rollins<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/raw-tag-team-championships|title=Raw Tag Team Championships|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116021122/https://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/raw-tag-team-championships|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n**[[WWE United States Championship]] ([[List of WWE United States Champions|1 time]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/unitedstates|title=United States Championship|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113024140/http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/unitedstates/5192013-dean-ambrose|archive-date=January 13, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n**[[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)#List of WWE Triple Crown winners|Twenty-seventh Triple Crown Champion]]<ref name=\"GrandSlam1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/wrestling/2017/8/21/16179254/wwe-summerslam-2017-results-dean-ambrose-grand-slam|title=Dean Ambrose is WWE's latest Grand Slam champion after SummerSlam win|date=August 21, 2017|accessdate=August 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826025850/https://www.sbnation.com/wrestling/2017/8/21/16179254/wwe-summerslam-2017-results-dean-ambrose-grand-slam|archive-date=August 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GrandSlam2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cagesideseats.com/wwe/2017/8/21/16179052/dean-ambrose-wwe-grand-slam-champ-youngest-summerslam-2017-seth-rollins-raw-tag|title=Dean Ambrose is a WWE Grand Slam champ|date=August 21, 2017|accessdate=August 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825234728/https://www.cagesideseats.com/wwe/2017/8/21/16179052/dean-ambrose-wwe-grand-slam-champ-youngest-summerslam-2017-seth-rollins-raw-tag|archive-date=August 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**[[Grand Slam (professional wrestling)#WWE|Eighth Grand Slam Champion]] ([[Grand Slam (professional wrestling)#Current format|under current format]]; [[Grand Slam (professional wrestling)#Guide|sixteenth overall]])<ref name=\"GrandSlam1\" /><ref name=\"GrandSlam2\" />\n**[[Money in the Bank ladder match|Money in the Bank]] ([[Money in the Bank (2016)|2016]])<ref name=\"MITB\" />\n**[[Slammy Award]]s (5 times)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/whatsaslammy|title=What is a Slammy?|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116033325/https://www.wwe.com/inside/news/whatsaslammy|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n*** Breakout Star of the Year ([[Slammy Award#2013 Slammy Awards|2013]], [[Slammy Award#2014 Slammy Awards|2014]]) \u2013 {{small|2013 award shared with [[The Shield (professional wrestling)|The Shield]]}}<ref name=\"Slammy2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2013-12-09/full-slammy-award-winners-2013|title=2013 Slammy Award winners|date=December 6, 2013|publisher=[[WWE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116034149/https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2013-12-09/full-slammy-award-winners-2013|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Slammy2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/52052-early-2014-wwe-slammy-award-winners-announced|title=Early 2014 WWE Slammy Award winners announced|date=December 8, 2014|last=Martin|first=Adam|accessdate=December 9, 2014|publisher=WrestleView|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603061054/http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/52052-early-2014-wwe-slammy-award-winners-announced|archive-date=June 3, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*** Faction of the Year (2013, 2014) \u2013 {{small|with The Shield}}<ref name=\"Slammy2014\" />\n*** Trending Now (Hashtag) of the Year (2013) \u2013 {{small|#BelieveInTheShield, with The Shield}}<ref name=\"Slammy2013\" />\n** [[WWE Year-End Award]]s (2 times)\n*** Best Reunion (2018) \u2013 {{small|as part of The Shield}}<ref name=\"411mania\">{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/wwe-announces-year-end-awards-instagram-becky-lynch-braun-strowman/|title=WWE Announces Year-End Awards on Instagram|last=Thomas|first=Jeremy|date=December 23, 2018|publisher=411Mania.com|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224024537/https://411mania.com/wrestling/wwe-announces-year-end-awards-instagram-becky-lynch-braun-strowman/|archive-date=December 24, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=December 30, 2018}}</ref>\n***Return of the Year (2018)<ref name=\"411mania\" />\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Dean Ambrose|Jon Moxley}}\n* {{IMDb name|name=Jonathan Good}}\n* {{wwe superstars|name=Dean Ambrose|id=dean-ambrose}}\n* {{NJPW profile|id=51626|name=Jon Moxley|newlink=yes}}\n* {{Chikara profile|id=jon-moxley|name=Jon Moxley}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222090855/http://www.hwaonline.com/Roster/jonmoxley.htm|date=February 22, 2012|title=HWA profile}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100404122003/http://insanityprowrestling.com/roster-jonmoxley.html|date=April 4, 2010|title=IPW profile}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n{{Navboxes|\n|list1=\n{{AEW World Championship}}\n{{All Elite Wrestling}}\n{{New Japan Pro Wrestling personnel}}\n{{IWGP United States Championship}}\n{{Grand Slam-Triple Crown Champions}}\n{{WWE Championship}}\n{{WWE Intercontinental Championship}}\n{{WWE United States Championship}}\n{{WWE Tag Team Championship}}\n{{Money in the Bank winners}}\n{{The Authority}}\n{{TheShield WWE}}\n{{FIP World Heavyweight Championship}}\n{{CZW World Heavyweight Championship}}\n{{WXW World Tag Team Championship}}\n}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moxley, Jon}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:All Elite Wrestling personnel]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:NWA/WCW/WWE United States Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:The Authority (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:WWF/WWE Intercontinental Champions]]\n[[Category:WWF/WWE World Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:WWE Grand Slam champions]]\n", "name_user": "Crash Underride", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHeartland Wrestling Association (2004\u20132011)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Moxley"}
{"title_page": "The Doon School", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|Boys' boarding school in Dehradun, India}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | image                   = The Doon School.jpg\n | caption                 = Main Building at The Doon School\n | image_size              = 300px\n | name                    = The Doon School\n | logo                    = The Doon School, Dehradun - logo.png\n | logo_size               = 150px\n | colours                 = Blue & White {{color box|#005293}} {{color box|white}}\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30.333|78.030|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n | pushpin_map             = India Uttarakhand#India\n | location                = The Doon School<br>Mall Road<br>[[Dehradun]]&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;248001<br>India<br>([https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/The+Doon+School/@30.3350253,78.0298105,17z Google Map], [https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/158385701 OpenStreetMap])\n | specialist              = \n | schooltype              = Private [[boarding school]]\n | motto                   = '' Knowledge our Light''\n | sister_school           = [[Welham Girls' School]]\n | established             = \n | founded                 = {{Start date and age|1935|09|10}}\n | founder                 = [[Satish Ranjan Das]]\n | head_name               = Founder Headmaster\n | head                    = [[Arthur Foot|Arthur Edward Foot]]\n | gender                  = Boys\n | lower_age               = 12\n | upper_age               = 18\n | headmaster              = Post vacant \n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governors\n | chair                   = [[Sunil Kant Munjal]]\n | pupils                  = c. 600\n | faculty                 = 70\n | houses                  = 5 \n | campus                  = 72 acres (297,314&nbsp;m\u00b2)\n | ceeb                    = 671616\n | district                = [[Dehradun district|Dehradun District]]\n | student_union           = [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n | affiliation             = [[International Baccalaureate|IB]]<br>[[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examination|CISCE]]<br>[[International General Certificate of Secondary Education|IGCSE]]\n | publication             = ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]''\n | free_label2             = Annual fees\n | free_text2              = {{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1025000}} (home students)<br>{{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1281000}} (international)\n | free_label              = Former pupils\n | free_text               = [[List of The Doon School alumni|Doscos]]\n | website                 = [http://www.doonschool.com/ www.doonschool.com]\n}}\n\n'''The Doon School''' (informally '''Doon School''' or '''Doon''') is a boys-only private [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]], [[Selective school|academically selective]] boarding school in Dehradun, Uttarakhand, India, established in 1935. It was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a [[Kolkata]] lawyer, who prevised a school modelled on the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]], but conscious of Indian ambitions and desires. Soon after initiating the funding scheme for Doon, Das, considered the school's founder, died in 1928. The school's first [[Head teacher|headmaster]] was [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], an Englishman who had spent nine years as a science master at [[Eton College]], England.<ref>{{cite book|year=1979|chapter=FOOT, Arthur Edward|title=Who Was Who 1961\u20131970|location=London|publisher=A. & C. Black|isbn=0-7136-2008-0}}</ref> The last headmaster, [[Matthew Raggett]], who resigned in January 2020, was the fourth British headmaster in Doon's history, and a member of [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]], [[UK]].\n\nThe school houses roughly 500 pupils aged 12 to 18, and admission is based on a competitive entrance examination and an interview with the headmaster. Every year boys are admitted in only two year groups: [[seventh grade]] in January and [[eighth grade]] in April. The school is fully residential, and boys and most teachers live on campus. In tenth grade, students take the [[IGCSE|Cambridge IGCSE]] examinations, and for the final two years can choose between [[Indian School Certificate]] or [[International Baccalaureate]] curriculum. A wide range of extra-curricular activities, numbering around 80, are offered to the boys, and early British masters such as [[R.L. Holdsworth]], [[J.A.K. Martyn]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] established a strong tradition of [[Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering|mountaineering at school]]. The school occupies the former site of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] and is home to diverse flora and fauna. Doon remains a boys-only school despite continued pressure from political leaders to become [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/old-boys-want-doon-to-stay-as-it-is/cid/473019|title=Old boys want Doon to stay as it is|website=www.telegraphindia.com}}</ref> [[Old boy network|Old boys]] of the school are known as 'Doscos'. \n\nDoon has been consistently ranked the best all-boys residential school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/17-schools-from-u---khand-secure-top-10-positions-in-ewisr.html|title=17 schools from U\u2019khand secure Top 10 positions in EWISR|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> Although the school has often been cited as 'Eton of India' by media outlets such as the [[BBC]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02c3zgq|title=BBC World Service - Witness, India's Eton|website=BBC}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|author=STEVEN R. WEISMAN, Special to the New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/12/world/india-s-old-school-tie-harrow-by-the-himalayas.html |title=India'S Old School Tie - Harrow By The Himalayas |location=Dehra Dun (India); India |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=12 November 1985 |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/aug/13/fiction.arundhatiroy|title=The lost sub-continent|first=William|last=Dalrymple|date=13 August 2005|website=the Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Spectator]]'',<ref name=\"Spectator UK\">{{cite web|author=Read |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/put-him-down-for-doon |title=It's a spartan life at 'the Eton of India' |publisher=The Spectator |date= |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/alastair-sooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html|title=The rise & rise of Anish Kapoor Inc.|first=Alastair|last=Sooke|date=2 April 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> and ''[[Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Remnick |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/10/20/rajiv-gandhi-and-the-mantle-unsought/779cee82-b666-4248-8116-278d6134a002/ |title=Rajiv Gandhi And The Mantle Unsought |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1987-10-20 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> it eschews the label.<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Doon-of-India-wants-to-conquer-the-globe/articleshow/6800690.cms |title=\u2018Doon of India\u2019 wants to conquer the globe - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has educated a wide range of notable alumni, including politicians, diplomats, artists, writers and business leaders.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709213757/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=For wannabe Doons, don from hills is a boon |newspaper=Times of India |date=30 December 2002 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> Among the former pupils of Doon are the late Indian prime minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]], artist [[Anish Kapoor]], novelists [[Vikram Seth]] and [[Amitav Ghosh]], fashion designer [[Tarun Tahiliani]], mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] and social activist [[Bunker Roy]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:The Doon School main building (then FRI) - 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|Main building of Doon in 1917, when it was part of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].]]\n\nDoon was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a lawyer from Calcutta and advocate-general of Bengal, who in 1927 became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council]] of [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Irwin]] on the condition that he would use the prestige of this position to raise funds for a new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"auto\">MacDougall2006, p.100</ref> He decided to name the new school \"Doon\", as it was situated in the [[Doon Valley]]. He travelled widely in [[India]] with the goal of collecting {{Indian Rupee}}4&nbsp;million, but at the time of his death in 1928 had raised only {{Indian Rupee}}1 million in cash and a further {{Indian Rupee}}1&nbsp;million in promises. With the money, Das formed the Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which had the objective of founding new public schools in [[India]] that would admit students regardless of caste, creed or social status.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=360 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n\nAfter Das's death, the IPSS accomplished little, and by 1934 some of the original lenders had begun to inquire about the return of their money.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> To solve this problem, [[J. W. Bhore|Sir Joseph Bhore]], then Railway Minister of [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|Lord Willingdon's]] Council, became IPSS chairman and, with [[Akbar Hydari|Sir Akbar Hydari]] as secretary, worked to obtain the former estate of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]], in [[Dehradun]], from the government on favourable terms.<ref>''The Indian Year Book'', vol. 29 (1942), p. 419: \"Doon School&nbsp;\u2013 This school which is established in the Chand Bagh and Skinner's Estates at Dehra Doon owes its origin to the initiative and enthusiasm of the late SR Das.\"</ref> Sir Frank Noyce also joined the team. [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], then President of the British Board of Education, led a selection committee that nominated [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], a science teacher at [[Eton College]], to be the first headmaster. On 27 October, 1935, the [[Viceroy]], [[Lord Willingdon]], presided over the formal opening of the school. Seventy boys enrolled in the first [[Academic term|term]], and 110 more signed up for the second.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 203 (Note 12): \"...from Willingdon's inaugural address on 27 October 1935\"</ref>\n\n===Early years:1935\u20131970===\n\nFoot had never visited [[India]] before accepting the position of headmaster. He noted that the school appeared to be surrounded by forests and close to mountains, and the possibilities of outdoor recreation and mountaineering seem to have influenced his decision as much as the chance to create a completely new type of school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=359 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Foot's first action upon being offered the position was to recruit [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J.A.K. (John) Martyn]] from [[Harrow School]] as his deputy. Doon's ethos and guiding principles were determined early in its life by Foot, Martyn, [[R. L. Holdsworth|R.L. Holdsworth]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]], who went on to become principal of [[Mayo College]].<ref>{{cite web|author=site admin |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19851115-book-review-sumer-singh-doon-the-story-of-a-school-mady-martyn-martyn-sahib-802174-2014-01-16 |title=Where East meets West - Society & The Arts News - Issue Date: Nov 15, 1985 |publisher=Indiatoday.in |date=1985-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> They were soon joined in their efforts by Indians such as the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]] (the school's first art teacher, who had trained previously in [[Santiniketan]]) and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], a noted mountaineer who taught at Doon for several decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-sundaymagazine/climb-every-mountain/article28515581.ece |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> In an essay entitled ''The Objects of Education'' published in the school magazine, Foot offered a template for a complete education for boys, which included teaching them to form a habit of choosing good over evil, think logically, express their thoughts and views clearly, and maintain a healthy body.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" /> At the opening of the school, he said, \"Our boys should leave The Doon School as members of an aristocracy, but it must be an aristocracy of service inspired by the ideals of unselfishness, not one of privilege, wealth or position\".<ref>''The Doon School Sixty Years On'', 1936, p.4</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/interview_doon-school-is-popular-for-building-an-aristocracy-of-service_1392063 |title=Doon School is popular for building an 'aristocracy of service'&nbsp;\u2013 Academy|work=DNA |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> The annual school fees in 1935 was {{Indian Rupee}}1,375, and by September 1946, it had risen to {{Indian Rupee}}1,800.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> In 1947, there were around 300 boys studying at Doon, out of which 50-60 were [[Muslims]], 15-20 [[Sikhs]], 15-20 [[Parsees]], 6-7 Christians, and the remaining two-thirds Hindu.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=365 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n[[File:Main Gate, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main gate of the Doon School.]]\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =...&nbsp;By 14 he should have learnt all the ordinary principles of social behaviour. He should know how to stand up and speak to a variety of different types of people&nbsp;\u2013 to his own mother, to someone else's mother, to his father, to his schoolmasters, to servants, to Mahatma Gandhi or to the Viceroy, and to do this without any self-consciousness&nbsp;...At 17 must come another quality, less instinctive and requiring a maturer mind: he must acquire a capacity of judgement.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\">{{cite book|title=The Doon School Sixty Years On |publisher=Doon School Old Boys' Society|date=October 1996}}</ref>&nbsp;...\n |source = <small>Arthur Foot, 1946, ''The Objects of Education''</small>\n |align  = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]], about 65 Doon students served in the [[Indian Army during World War II|Army]], [[Royal Indian Navy|Navy]] or [[Indian Air Force|Air Force]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=369 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Martyn, who became the second headmaster in 1948, acknowledged the influence of German educator [[Kurt Hahn]] in the development of the school's ethos. Although Martyn had not visited India before, he immediately accepted Foot's offer because of the opportunity it afforded to implement Hahn's ideas, which he had not been able to do at Harrow.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=38|quote=When John wrote to Hahn to tell him we was going to India, Hahn replied that he had been waiting to be able to offer him a place at Gordonstoun...}}</ref> While Foot and Martyn were determined to model Doon on Eton and Harrow, they both agreed that Doon should cater primarily for Indian boys\u2014and not the sons of British expatriates\u2014in order to create a uniquely Indian public school rather than a transplanted British institution. Foot did not want Doon to be considered elitist. In a paper surveying the new school, presented to the [[Royal Society of Arts]], London in 1947, Foot wrote: \"In language we have never intended to base our instruction on the Classics in the way that Latin is still the centre pin of the English Public School. The great majority of boys take Urdu or Hindi.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=361 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n\n===Middle years: 1970\u20132000===\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-right:1em; font-size:85%; background:#ffc; color:black; width:20em; max-width:25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Headmasters\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n* [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], 1935\u20131948\n* [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J. A. K. Martyn]], 1948\u20131966\n* [[C. J. Miller]], 1966\u20131970\n* [[Eric Simeon|Eric J. Simeon]], 1970\u20131979\n* [[Gulab Ramchandani]], 1979\u20131988\n* [[Shomie Das]], 1988\u20131996\n* [[John Mason (Schoolmaster)|John A. Mason]], 1996\u20132003\n* [[Kanti Bajpai]], 2003\u20132009\n* [[Peter McLaughlin]], 2009\u20132016\n* [[Matthew Raggett]], 2016\u20132020 \n|}\n\nThe school's first Indian headmaster was [[Eric Simeon]], appointed in 1970. He came from a military background and laid great emphasis on disciplined living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/schooled-for-life/32471/|title=Schooled for life - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/Lt.-Col.-Eric-Joseph-Simeon-dead/article14764255.ece |title=Lt. Col. Eric Joseph Simeon dead |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> Simeon's tenure of nine years was marked with financial difficulties for the school and the estate suffered, as the funds were not enough to maintain buildings and facilities. <ref>https://www.doonschool.com/weekly/May%2019%202007.pdf</ref> In 1971, Simeon introduced the 'Scholar's Blazer', an academic equivalent of the pre-existing prize 'Games Blazer', so that boys accorded academic excellence the same level of prestige as they did sporting achievements.<ref name=\"Back to School\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/KaranThapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104092100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/karanthapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2010 |last=Thapar|first=Karan|title=Back to School |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1979, [[Gulab Ramchandani]] became the first alumnus to be appointed headmaster, and during his term the school regained financial stability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/ramchandani-old-boy-and-workaholic-headmaster-who-transformed-doon-school/articleshow/58185206.cms|title=Ramchandani: Old Boy and \u2018workaholic\u2019 headmaster who transformed Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> In 1988, [[Shomie Das]], another alumnus and the grandson of school founder Satish Ranjan Das, became headmaster. Das's focus was on upgrading the school infrastructure, and during his time the Oberoi house was added to the original four houses. The next headmaster, [[John Mason (schoolmaster)|John Mason]], appointed in 1996, planned on making Doon more affordable to school pupils. The school did not raise its fees while Mason was in office. \n\n====Criticism of Rajiv Gandhi administration====\n\nIn the 1980s, the then [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Rajiv Gandhi]], an alumnus, drew criticism from the media for appointing many old boys to his administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0724/eindia.html|title=Bootstrap steps for Gandhi|date=24 July 1987|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> His inner circle was labelled a \"Doon Cabinet\"<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /> or \"Dosco Mafia\",<ref>''Indian Tales of the Raj'' by Zareer Masani, p.152</ref> and ''Washington Post'' reported, \"The catch phrase around Delhi these days is that the 'Doon School runs India,' but that is too simple an analysis for a complex, chaotic country with so many competing spheres of influence.\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\">{{cite web|last=Bumiller |first=Elisabeth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1985/11/24/where-indias-elite-were-boys-together/0579f3d9-1835-4441-b1b1-a55e3111bdc3/ |title=Where India's Elite Were Boys Together |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1985-11-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Steven R. Weisman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/20/magazine/the-rajiv-generation.html |title=THE RAJIV GENERATION - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1986-04-20 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gandhi's reliance on Doon alumni for political advice later led Prime Minister [[Morarji Desai]] to remark, \"If I had anything to do with this place, I'd close it down\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\"/> Although any alumnus seldom held public office for some time afterward, this changed with the political ascendance of Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia, Naveen Patnaik, and Rahul Gandhi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707070626/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Naveen Patnaik sets stage for GeNext Doscos |newspaper=The Times of India |date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Recent years: 2000\u2013present===\n[[Kanti Bajpai]] was the third old boy, after Gulab Ramchandani and Shomie Das, to become headmaster, when appointed to the post in 2003. He introduced numerous punishments, notably \"yellow cards\", to control an outburst of bullying at Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03cgg70 |title=BBC World Service - Path to Power, Educating India's Elite |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1994-10-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> In 2006, Bajpai found himself embroiled in a controversy when the parents of Hindu and Sikh students complained on discovering that the school's dining hall only serves [[halal]] meat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bad-blood-over-meat-served-at-Doon-School/articleshow/1516879.cms|title=Bad blood over meat served at Doon School &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The fact came to light after a visiting Pakistani delegation was assured of their meal's halal status. Despite mounting pressure, the school's board of governors appealed for maintaining the status quo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/doon-debates-meaty-matters/story-mQ4y1Lt1fXLI3DiW2cV3XI.html|title=Doon debates meaty matters|date=3 May 2006|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> As of 2016, the school was serving both halal and non-halal (''[[jhatka]]'') meat varieties in the dining hall.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2434-FINAL.pdf</ref> In 2009, [[Peter McLaughlin]], an Irish academic, was chosen to lead the school, becoming the first non-Indian headmaster in almost four decades.\n\n====2010 Founder's Day celebrations and film controversy====\n[[File:President of India speaking at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]] speaking at the school's 75th Founder's Day in October 2010.]]\n\nFounder's Day is a three-four day event in the autumn term, usually October, that marks the school's founding and draws many ex-pupils from all parts of the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/item/40943-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref> The chief guest is usually a prominent person, and the events include exhibitions, productions of plays, yoga sessions, live bands, a fete and an orchestral concert given by members of the school's Music Society.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/how-indias-renowned-doon-school-is-embracing-change-to-retain-its-exclusivity/articleshow/45006985.cms?from=mdr |title=How India's renowned Doon School is embracing change to retain its exclusivity - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-11-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Datta |first=Sravasti |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523113538/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 May 2011 |title=Life & Style / Metroplus : All boarders on board |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 February 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon celebrated its 75th Founder's Day in 2010 and programmed events on an unprecedented scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/doon-school-to-celebrate-its-75th-anniversary-from-oct-21/articleshow/6712783.cms?from=mdr|title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21|date=8 October 2010|via=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/boys-will-be-boys/story-UxdKhDLhEGUVHIwaXe2e7H.html|title=Boys will be boys |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The event was christened ''DS-75''.<ref name=\"Doon school\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-08/news/27591639_1_celebrations-doon-school-chief-guest |title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21 |publisher=[[The Times Group]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School\">{{cite news|title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/15930-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |newspaper=Daily Pioneer|date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Among the chief guests were the then President of India [[Pratibha Patil]], King [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]] of Bhutan, and [[Kapil Sibal]], then minister of [[Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)|Human Resource Development]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bhutanjournals.com/monarchy/hms-address-at-doon-school-dehradun-india/ |title=HM's Address at Doon School, Dehradun, India|newspaper=Bhutan Journals |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Pratibha Patil, in her address, urged the school authorities to make Doon a co-educational institution.<ref name=\"telegraphindia1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/dame-dilemma-for-doon-president-s-co-ed-suggestion-evokes-mixed-reaction/cid/473014 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|title=Dame dilemma for Doon&nbsp;\u2013 President's co-ed suggestion evokes mixed reaction |date=25 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> One of the main events was a discussion, dubbed the \"Chandbagh Debate\", held between alumni including [[Vikram Seth]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Manpreet Singh Badal]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] and retired headmaster Kanti Bajpai, on the topic ''Can India lead?''. It was moderated by television commentator [[Karan Thapar]], an alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+matter+of+debate+at+Doon+School+platinum+jubilee.-a0240443417 |title=A matter of debate at Doon School platinum jubilee|newspaper=[[India Today]] |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Ashvin Kumar]], an alumnus and Oscar-nominated director, made the film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'' for the celebrations, using pupils for the cast and crew. Most of it was shot in June and July during the summer break, and those scenes which required the entire student body were filmed after the school reopened in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imaginox.co.uk/course/1718 |title=Making 'Dazed in Doon' |publisher=Imaginox |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> It was screened on the final day of celebrations to a gathering of over 2000 people, including guests, students, parents and alumni.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-School-bans-Ashvin-Kumars-film/articleshow/6919672.cms|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The day after screening, the school objected to the film and its distribution, labelling the bullying scenes \"defamatory\", and obtained a court order to delay its release. The DVD sales on campus were immediately halted.<ref name=fallout>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-film-fallout/articleshow/6941433.cms|title=Doon film fallout!|newspaper=The Times of India|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The dispute  remains unresolved between the director and school authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Ex-students-film-celebrating-Doon-draws-schools-ire/articleshow/7159525.cms|title=Ex-student's film 'celebrating' Doon draws school's ire &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> On 22 October 2010, a commemorative postage stamp depicting the school's main building was released by the [[Indian Postal Service]] to mark the occasion of the 75th Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101009/dplus.htm#5 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Detail of The Doon School Main Gate.jpg|thumb|200px|In March 2020, the school closed for the first time since its founding, following the [[COVID-19 outbreak]].]]\n\n====Present day====\n\nIn June 2016, the school announced the appointment of Matthew Raggett, principal of the [[Leipzig International School]]'s secondary department, to succeed Peter McLaughlin as headmaster. Until the start of McLaughlin's headmastership, the student demographic was dominated by boys hailing from the [[North Indian]] states. To make the school more diverse, Raggett continued McLaughlin's outreach initiative of inviting more applications from boys in [[South Indian|South]] and [[Northeast India]]n states.<ref name=\"indiatimes2\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/doon-school-looks-for-more-boys-from-south/articleshow/57725021.cms|title=Doon School: Doon School looks for more boys from south &#124; Bengaluru News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/doons-bonds-with-hyderabad/article7072329.ece|title=Doon\u2019s bonds with Hyderabad|first=R. Ravikanth|last=Reddy|date=6 April 2015|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> He also introduced a group discussion as part of the admissions process to test for critical thinking and peer interaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/dehradun/after-8-decades-doon-school-looks-to-south-east-for-students/story-4uYQRMF8qalW61HFHuB0xM.html|title=After 8 decades, Doon School looks to South, East for students|date=3 July 2017|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> The school was the subject of a 2018 [[Channel 4]] documentary series called ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', which was based on a social experiment to see if five under-performing British boys would thrive in Doon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/indian-summer-school|title=Indian Summer School: Indian Summer School|website=Channel 4}}</ref> In January 2020, Matthew Raggett stepped down as the tenth headmaster citing personal reasons. In March 2020, the school was shut down for the first time since its founding in 1935, and boys were sent home due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]] and the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|Indian lockdown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/three-city-based-boarding-schools-close/articleshow/74662334.cms|title=Coronavirus scare: Three city-based boarding schools close &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Online classes are being conducted for students through video conferencing apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-launch-online-classes-to-complete-syllabus/articleshow/74781758.cms|title=Schools launch online classes to complete syllabus in parts of Uttarakhand &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Governance and organisation==\n\nThe school is owned by the [[non-profit]] entity Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which was registered by S.R. Das in 1928 with the aim of establishing public schools in India. Under the IPSS, the Board of Governors supervises all matters of Doon.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 41: \"...the body founded by Das for the purposes of establishing the Doon School, the Indian Public Schools Society\"</ref> The current board comprises thirteen members and is chaired by [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], an alumnus. The president of [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]] has a seat on the board to represent the views and interests of the alumni.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> At the intramural level, the School Council, comprising the headmaster, heads of department, staff and student representatives from each house, is responsible for legislating and discussing school policies. Every house holds a vote to send four student representatives to the council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/leadership/|title=Leadership|website=Doon School}}</ref> Each house is run by a housemaster or a housemistress, along with a house captain and a team of [[School prefect|prefects]]. The housemistress is assisted by a [[matron]] known as \"The Dame\", who provides [[pastoral care]] for pupils, some of whom take several weeks to adjust fully to life in a boarding school, particularly given Doon's monastic lifestyle and strict routine.<ref name=\"outlookindia2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/class-up-at-doon/230938 |title=Class Up At Doon &#124; Anjali Puri |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Futehally\"> {{cite book |last1=Futehally |first1=Laeeq |title=The Last Englishman: The Life and Times of Jack Gibson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iw1CgAAQBAJ&dq=the+last+englishman+jack+gibson&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2015 |publisher=Hachette UK |location=London |language= |isbn=9789350099698 |page= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= The food and linen was the responsibility of the Dame (Matron)}}</ref> The homes of housemasters and housemistresses are adjacent or physically attached to their houses to enable close supervision and support. One senior boy serves as [[school captain]], chosen by teachers and students at the start of the year by voting in a [[secret ballot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-lad-is-Doon-School-captain/articleshow/18424444.cms |title=Ludhiana lad is Doon School captain &#124; Ludhiana News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-02-10 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>   \n\n===Houses===\n[[File:TataHouseQuadinDoon.jpg|thumb|right|East wing of Tata House and the quad.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:80%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | House name and Colours\n|-\n! House\n! Colour\n! Swatch\n|-\n|Kashmir || Yellow || {{colour box|#fecb00}}\n|-\n|Oberoi || Sky blue || {{colour box|#00add0}}\n|-\n|Tata || Red || {{colour box|#c60c30}}\n|-\n|Jaipur || Green || {{colour box|#007934}}\n|-\n|Hyderabad || Navy Blue || {{colour box|#003359}}\n|-\n|Martyn || || {{colour box|#496c60}}\n|-\n|Foot || ||{{colour box|#589199}}\n|}\n\nDoon follows the [[house system]]; there are five main houses (Hyderabad, Jaipur, Kashmir, Tata and Oberoi) and two 'holding houses' (Foot and Martyn, named after former headmasters), for boys in their first year.<ref name=\"Boarding at Doon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/pastoral-care/boarding-at-doon/|title=Boarding at Doon|website=Doon School}}</ref> The original four houses (Oberoi was added in 1991) were named after the largest initial donors: Hyderabad House was named after [[Akbar Hydari]], who secured a contribution from [[Nizam of Hyderabad]]'s government; Kashmir, after [[Maharajah]] [[Hari Singh]], then ruler of [[Jammu and Kashmir]]; Tata, after the [[Tata family|Tata]] Trusts; and Jaipur, after [[Rai Bahadur]] Amarnath Atal arranged for contributions from the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] of [[Jaipur]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 197 (Appendix 1): \"Donors to the Indian Public Schools' Society prior to 1936\"</ref> Boys are assigned to houses at the time of admission and develop great loyalty to them, since all [[intramural sports]] involve fierce competition between houses. Those who have a family history with a particular house are assigned to the same house. All houses have rooms, dormitories, kitchen, library, study rooms, and a Common Room for recreation.\n\n===Fees and financial aid===\nAs of April 2020, the annual school fees for Indian students was {{Indian Rupee}}10,25,000, and {{Indian Rupee}}12,81,000 for foreign nationals or [[non-resident Indians]]. Once admission is secured after clearing the entrance examination and interview, a student can apply for around 25 scholarships or awards on offer. Some are reserved for boys proficient in sports or arts, and those from an [[Indian Armed Forces|armed forces]] background. The monetary value of financial aid ranges from fifty percent of the tuition fee to being fully funded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/admissions/scholarships/|title=Scholarship Programme Offered by The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> In the media, the school has been described as a \"grooming ground for India's wealthy kids\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/10/28/the-doon-school-grooming-ground-for-indias-wealthy-kids/|title=The Doon School: Grooming Ground For India's Wealthy Kids|first=Forbes|last=Staff|website=Forbes}}</ref> The last headmaster, Matthew Raggett, has stated that over 25% of Doon's students receive needs-based bursaries, and the school is working towards a completely [[need-blind admission|needs-blind admission]] policy.<ref name=\"indiatimes2\"/>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:FC Barcelona camp at Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|Main Field of the school with Kashmir and Hyderabad houses in the background.]]\n\nThe school is spread across a single campus covering approximately {{convert|72|acre|m2}} flanked by Chakrata Road and Mall Road in the [[Dehradun Cantonment]] area of Dehradun city, [[Uttarakhand]], India.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114929995090170584 |title=The Andover of India? |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Anita|last=Raghavan|date=24 June 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To house the school, the IPSS acquired Chandbagh Estate in Dehradun from the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] (FRI). Part of the estate was once a deer park. The IPSS also acquired an adjoining estate, now known as Skinner's Field, from the descendants of [[James Skinner (East India Company officer)|James Skinner]]. The buildings on campus include the Main Building, which houses offices and classrooms, structures for sports facilities, science blocks, music school, library, arts and media centre, auditorium, amphitheatre, dining hall, wellness centre, recycling and waste-treatment plants, and masters' residences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412|title=Premium schools &#124; Outlook Business|website=www.outlookbusiness.com}}</ref>\n\n===Architecture===\n[[File:Rose Bowl amphitheatre, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|The school's [[amphitheatre]], known as Rose Bowl, was constructed by the boys and masters in the early-1930s over two years. It was refurbished in 2009.]]\nThe construction of the Main Building, then in FRI, was carried out by Imperial Public Works Department, and finished in 1911. Its Renaissance-style architecture was inspired by [[Basilica Palladiana]] in [[Vicenza]], Italy.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\" /> Many buildings on the campus have been designed by notable Indian architects or firms.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\" /> The library was designed by Romi Khosla, the Biology block by Ram Sharma, teachers' residences by Anagram Architects, and the new Arts and Media Centre, which was inaugurated in October 2010 and shortlisted for the 2010 World Architecture News Education Award, by alumnus Sandeep Khosla <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/5-schools-india-teach-lesson-design-architecture-pune-mumbai/|title=5 schools in India that offer a quick course in sensitive design and architecture|date=10 January 2020|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sandeep Khosla, Principal Architect , Khosla Associates |url=https://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/article/1507033/making-cut |title=Making the cut |publisher=Worldarchitecturenews.com |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Arts and Media Centre houses painting, ceramic, sculpture, and textile studios, along with a lecture hall, film and photography studio, publications' room and exhibition galleries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/86476/arts-and-media-centre-at-the-doon-school-khosla-associates/|title=Arts and Media Centre at the Doon School / Khosla Associates|date=4 November 2010|website=ArchDaily}}</ref> In 2016, the school's Main Building received the \"Honourable Mention\" under the [[UNESCO Asia Pacific Heritage Awards|UNESCO Asia-Pacific Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation]], following the conservation work carried out by Aishwarya Tipnis Architects on the more than a century-old building.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/doon-school-campus-extension-anagram-architects/|title=Take a tour of India\u2019s most elite private school, The Doon School campus|date=21 March 2018|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.one.un.org/page/restoration-of-prayer-hall-at-japan-shrine-wins-top-honor-in-unesco-asia-pacific-heritage-awards/ |title=Restoration of prayer hall at Japan shrine wins top honor in UNESCO Asia- Pacific Heritage Awards - UN India |publisher=In.one.un.org |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Natural environment===\nThe school estate, known as Chandbagh, lies in the green zone of the city and occupies the former site of the Imperial Forest Research Institute, now [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School'' (London: Routledge, 1998), p.65: \"The estate chosen by Noyce and Bhore to be the campus of the future Doon School was not, however, just an arrangement of buildings for the dissemination of serious knowledge. It was also a well planted garden...The Forest Service planted many different shrubs and trees [on the school campus] and these remain for our enjoyment and instruction.\"</ref> A wide variety of [[flora]] and [[fauna]] are found on campus, including many rare trees that date back to the days of the FRI.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\">{{cite web|url=https://fountainink.in/essay/no-common-or-garden-affair |title=No common or garden affair &#124; Fountain Ink |publisher=Fountainink.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\" /> The school has over 150 species of trees on its campus, and the formal gardens attract a variety of birds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashant |first=Shishir |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/doon-school-s-etp-may-be-trendsetter-111031400040_1.html |title=Doon school's ETP may be trendsetter |newspaper=[[Business Standard]] |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1996, a book titled ''Trees of Chandbagh'' was released which provided a comprehensive account of vegetation found on Doon's campus.<ref name=\"TreesofChandbagh\">{{cite book|last=Sahni|first=K. C.|title=Trees of Chandbagh: Doon's national heritage|year=1996|publisher=Konark Publishers|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-220-0457-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> Along similar lines, the illustrated book ''Birds of Chandbagh: A Guide To Birding at The Doon School'' was released in 2019, featuring photographs, illustrations and [[QR codes]] documenting the [[bird calls]] of the species found on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.in/BIRDS-CHANDBAGH-guide-birding-School/dp/B084HG4R87 |title=Buy BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Book Online at Low Prices in India &#124; BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Reviews & Ratings |publisher=Amazon.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has devised an Architectural and Projects Committee, which ensures that any construction taking place on campus is done without disturbing the ecological balance of the wooded school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/7-days/studies-in-style/cid/598008 |title=Studies in style |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2017-10-30 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:Main Building corridor at Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Ground-floor corridor of the school's Main Building, which houses classrooms and offices.]]\nThe school practices a five-and-a-half-day week consisting of 40 periods (or \"schools\"), each of 40 minutes. The school day begins with \"first bell\" soon after 6:15&nbsp;am. The boys have [[chhota haazri]] before doing [[calisthenics]] outdoors on the playing fields, which is then followed by classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Chhota-Hazri-bell-tolls-for-desi-Etons/articleshow/764209.cms |title=Chhota Hazri bell tolls for desi Etons|newspaper=The Times of India |date=4 July 2004 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> On Sundays, boys are free to pursue any activity or sport, or go into town for leisure.<ref name=\"Boarding at Doon\" /> The student-teacher ratio at the school is 10:1.<ref name=\"excellence\">{{cite journal|title=Excellence personified |journal=Frontline |date=12 February 2011 |volume=28 |issue=4 |url=http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313163529/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> Doon pupils take the [[International General Certificate of Secondary Education]] (IGCSE) exams in [[tenth grade]], which replaced [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] in 2017, and are thereafter offered two strands for the final two years: [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) or [[Indian School Certificate]] (ISC).<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibo.org/en/school/002603 |title=The Doon School - International Baccalaureate\u00ae |publisher=Ibo.org |date=2006-08-28 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year has three terms: spring, summer and autumn. The autumn term runs from August to the year-end final examinations in November, after which the boys are promoted to the new class in February.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kapoor |first=Jaskiran |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/class-apart/601507/0 |title=Class Apart |publisher=Indian Express |date=11 April 2010 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> Each term has a \"test week\" and end-of-term examinations known as \"trials\". Boys meet their tutors every week to discuss any matter, and are able to visit teachers, most of whom live on campus, for further academic help. Subjects on offer include geography, economics, environmental studies, art and design, psychology, music, English, Hindi, Sanskrit, and [[STEM subjects]]. Doon's foreign language offerings include French, German and Spanish. There is a career's department that offers pupils guidance on career paths, college applications, and entrance exams like the [[SAT]]. In recent years, boys have increasingly chosen foreign universities over Indian colleges, sometimes due to the hyper-competitiveness of the [[Higher education in India|Indian higher education system]] that calls for extremely high school-leaving scores for admissions.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/education/it-is-an-elite-school-not-elitist/article23029951.ece|title=\u2018It is an elite school, not elitist\u2019|first=Jaideep Deo|last=Bhanj|date=11 March 2018|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n\n===Traditions===\nThe early headmasters and teachers at Doon came from traditional British public schools, and the jargon introduced by them is still in use. For example, the weekly masters' meeting, started by Foot, is called ''Chambers'', a term taken from Eton, and evening \"prep\" (the boarding-school equivalent of homework) is called ''toye-time'', a term taken from [[Winchester College]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Charles |last1=Stevens|first2=Christopher|last2=Stray|title=Winchester notions: the English dialect of Winchester College|publisher=Athlone Press|year=1998|page=294|quote=Toy-time, or toytime recorded from 1831 as the evening hours of preparation, called 'prep' elsewhere&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB917469665815143000 |title=Language Lessons: For India's Elite English Is the Past -- and the Future\n|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The school songs were deliberately chosen to include both [[Urdu poetry]] and Hindu [[bhajan]]s as a way of emphasising Doon's secular ethos; similarly, the school prayers include a mix of Anglican hymns and Indian poetry.<ref>The Doon School Prayer book p.02-26</ref> Attendance at the morning assembly is required of all pupils and teachers. It traditionally begins with a song from the school's song book, which contains poetry, hymns and [[bhajans]], including ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''Chisti Ne Jis Zamin Mein'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]], ''Anand Loke'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''[[Lab Pe Aati Hai Dua]]'' by Muhammad Iqbal, ''Ghungat Ke Pat Khol Re'' (attributed to [[Meerabai]]), ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' (from a poem by [[Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay]]). Although ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' is India's [[National anthem]], it is traditionally referred to as \"Song No. 1\" at Doon since it was adopted as the school song in 1935, fifteen years before it  became India's national anthem.<ref>Bathla, Sanjeev<''Chotta Hazri:A Dosco's yatra'' p.32</ref><ref name=\"srivastava\">{{cite book|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School (p.82)|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref> Social work, known formally as \"Socially Useful Productive Work\", is also part of school life. All boys of the school must complete a mandatory quota of social service hours every term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/nation-education/article/doon-school-scouts-tamil-nadu-students |title=Doon School scouts for Tamil Nadu students |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon also oversees a Panchayat Ghar teaching impoverished children, and many building projects and workshops for the local community. Pupils and alumni have frequently helped local villages of organised efforts across India to assist people affected by natural disasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roundsquare.org/educational-insights/the-doon-school-a-village-service-partnership/ |title=The Doon School: A Village Service Partnership |publisher=Round Square |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> During the [[1991 Uttarkashi earthquake]], the school's amateur radio club was used by the government for communication purposes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gautam|first=Ashutosh|title=Earthquake: A Natural Disaster|year=2008|publisher=APH Publishing|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-313-0337-5|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSbTJDwMFgAC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=doon+school+uttarkashi+earthquake#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20uttarkashi%20earthquake&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\n{{Anchor|Athletics}}\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Cricket at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|A cricket game in progress on the Main Field.]]\n\nSports are compulsory for pupils. The school has over {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of playing fields, the largest of which are Skinner's Field and the Main Field. Cricket and hockey dominate the sports calendar in spring term, while football, athletics and boxing are played in autumn term. Other sports such as tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, basketball, swimming and gymnastics are played all-year round. Inter-house matches are played in cricket, hockey, football and basketball. Sports facilities include a 25-metre swimming pool, a boxing ring and a multi-purpose hall with a gymnasium, yoga studio, and facilities for indoor badminton, basketball and table tennis. There are two [[artificial turf]] cricket pitches, five basketball courts, four tennis courts, four squash courts, eight cricket nets, seven fields for hockey and football (which can be converted to four cricket pitches to accommodate seasonal sports), a modern cricket pavilion and two 400-metre athletics tracks. In 2014, the school inaugurated a shooting range on campus. Golf is offered to boys in partnership with local golf courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/departments/sports/|title=Sports|website=Doon School}}</ref> Doon hosts the annual Afzal Khan Memorial Basketball Tournament, an inter-school tournament that draws all major school basketball teams of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/features/the-asian-school-bag-bball-trophy-233461 |title=The Asian School bag b\u2019ball trophy |publisher=The Tribune India |date=2016-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/inside-the-hoop-dreams-of-21-boys-at-nbas-first-academy-in-india/articleshow/58979953.cms?from=mdr |title=NBA: Inside the hoop dreams of 21 boys at NBA\u2019s first academy in India - The Economic Times |date=2017-06-04 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020504/ncr3.htm |title=Tribune Online Edition, May 4, 2002 |work=The Tribune |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys visit other schools and academies from time to time to take part in various tournaments. For skill improvement, the school often invites professional sports bodies to hold training camps, which are usually open to students from across India. In 2013, a football coaching camp was held in association with Bar\u00e7a Academy, the official training school of [[FC Barcelona]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/f-c-barcelona-at-doon-july-2013/|title=F.C. Barcelona at Doon - July 2013|date=20 September 2013|website=Doon School}}</ref> and in January 2015, coaches from the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] held a week-long cricket training camp on the school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pitchvision.com/exclusive-inside-mcc-lords-club-india-coaching-camp-drills |title=Live Local Matches &#124; Tips & Techniques &#124; Articles & Podcasts |publisher=PitchVision |date=2017-07-24 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://educationworld.in//EWIssue.aspx|title=India's best boys boarding school|website=EducationWorld.in}}</ref>\n\n===Clubs and societies===\n{{See|The Doon School Model United Nations}}\n[[File:The Doon School Weekly.jpg|thumb|''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication of Doon. It is produced by the boys and distributed every Saturday morning.]]\n\nExtracurricular activities are also a compulsory element of school life.  There are around 70-80 clubs and societies, including astronomy, business, [[The Doon School Model United Nations]], quiz, photography and film, [[Model aircraft|aeromodelling]], robotics, paper recycling, weather reporting, pottery, carpentry, [[amateur radio]] and birdwatching, among others.<ref>{{cite web|author=\" + arr[2] + \" |url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412 |title=Premium schools |publisher=Outlook Business |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> In many societies pupils come together to discuss a particular topic, presided over by a schoolmaster and often including a guest speaker. The school has often invited prominent figures to give speeches and talks to the students; these have included heads of state, politicians, ornithologists, naturalists, artists, writers, economists, diplomats and industrialists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/category/events/visiting-speakers/|title=Visiting Speakers Archives|website=Doon School}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/600-mn-to-be-enrolled-in-uidai-in-next-4-years-nilekani/714784 |title=600 Mn to be Enrolled in UIDAI in Next 4 Years: Nilekani |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nBoys can write for, or join the editorial board of, a number of school magazines that are published in English or Hindi. ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication and the official school newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/34/42/obituary/ |title=OBITUARY : Himalayan Journal vol.34/42 |publisher=Himalayanclub.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> Distributed every Saturday morning, and edited by pupils, it chronicles school activities and is a platform for creative, political or humorous writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The publication aims to represent the views of the school community as well as Old Boys, and include satire and criticism of school policies. More subversive publications, critical of teachers and the school establishment, have occasionally been produced without official sponsorship. Other magazines include ''The Yearbook'', a heavily illustrated publication for recording all highlights of the school year, and ''The Doon School Information Review'' for cultural criticism. Specialist publications by academic departments include '' Vibgyor'' (Art), ''Echo'' (Science), ''The Econocrat'' (Economics), ''Infinity'' (Mathematics), ''Grand Slam'' (Sports) and ''The Circle'' (History and Political Science).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/|title=Publications|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n===Mountaineering===\n{{Main|Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering}}\n\n[[File:Mt. Everest Base Camp Expedition - 2008, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|2008 expedition to the [[Mount Everest Base Camp]] and [[Kala Patthar]].]]\n\nHalfway through each term, the boys go on a one-week \"midterm\", an expedition through the [[Siwalik Hills]] or [[Himalayas]]. Senior boys make treks of up to five days, unaccompanied by teachers, camping out in tents and cooking their own food. The trips are planned by students themselves. Alumni have recalled these midterms as being among their most formative and character-building experiences.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/how-the-playing-fields-of-doon-nurture-india-incs-best-leaders/articleshow/6872417.cms|title=How the playing fields of Doon nurture India Inc's best leaders |newspaper=The Times of India |date=5 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon has been credited with pioneering mountaineering in India, due to the accomplishments of masters such as [[R.L. Holdsworth]], [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], and alumni like [[Narendra Dhar Jayal|Nandu Jayal]], who later became the founder principal of [[Himalayan Mountaineering Institute]].<ref name=\"Kohli\"> {{cite book |last1=Kohli |first1=M.S. |title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure and Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Mountains_of_India.html?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&redir_esc=y |date=2002 |publisher=Indus |location= |language= |isbn=9788173871351 |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |page=209 |quote= p.290, Much of the credit for early interest in mountaineering among Indians goes to the Doon School, largely because of some distinguished British mountaineers on its staff like J.A.K. Martyn, J.T.M. Gibson, R.L. Holdsworth...In 1951, Gurdial Singh of the Doon School climbed the 7,120 metres high Trisul. This was the first Indian summit.}}</ref> Notable climbs by staff and alumni include [[Bandarpunch]] (6,316&nbsp;m) in 1950, Kala Nag (6,387&nbsp;m) in 1956, [[Trisul]] (7,120&nbsp;m) in 1951, [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m) in 1955, [[Abi Gamin]] (7,355&nbsp;m) in 1953 and 1955, Mrigthuni (6,855&nbsp;m) in 1958 and Jaonli (6,632 metres) in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/62/16/early-years-of-indian-mountaineering/ |title=Early Years of Indian Mountaineering |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> Some of these expeditions have been noted for their idiosyncrasies. After Gurdial Singh led a successful climb of Trisul, he performed a headstand [[asana]] on the summit as a tribute to the Hindu god [[Shiva]], who is said to abide there. Holdsworth smoked a pipe on reaching the summit of [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m), during its first ascent in 1931.<ref name=\"Harish Kapadia\"> {{cite book |last1=Kapadia |first1=Harish |title=Across Peaks and Passes in Garhwal Himalaya |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Across_Peaks_Passes_in_Garhwal_Himalaya.html?id=KptmxrqhKl4C |date=1999 |publisher=Indus Publishing |location=London |language=English |isbn=9788173870972 |page=17 |quote=The peak of Kamet was attempted several times and finally in 1931 Frank Smythe and Eric Shipton reached the summit along with some others. R.L. Holdsworth, who was with them, smoked a pipe on the summit, which I believe still remains a height record for smokers.}}</ref> Two Doon pupils climbed the [[Matterhorn]] in 1951 wearing cricket boots.<ref name=\"alpinejournal\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Richard|title=Climbing with the Doon School|journal=Alpine Journal|year=2001|pages=197\u2013201|url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2001_files/AJ%202001%20197-201%20Anderson%20Doon%20School.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and music===\n[[File:Waiting for Godot in Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' being staged in the open-air theatre, Rose Bowl.]]\nAn [[amphitheatre]] known as the Rose Bowl was built largely by pupils in two years during the 1930s<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=130|quote=It took two years to complete the open air theatre. The first play staged on it was \"The Merchant of Venice prodcued by Jack Gibson, and he had all his actors dressed in Indian costumes.\"}}</ref> and underwent a major structural change in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Santayana|first=Vivek|title=Losing a Kidney|journal=The Doon School Weekly|date=24 October 2009|issue=2232|url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66UfGMuG8?url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It can seat up to 2,000 people and has been the setting for numerous [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays and other classics of western theatre, as well as musical performances and speeches during school ceremonies such as Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805061511/http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=Doon Online&nbsp;\u2013 Vikram Seth |publisher=Mtholyoke.edu |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Multi-Purpose Hall is a more modern indoor theatre that can accommodate approximately 2,000 people. Plays are regularly staged in [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]], with 8\u20139 productions each year including 2 major productions as part of the Founder's Day celebrations. The Inter House Once-Act Play competition is held each year, alternatively in English and Hindi. Many of the plays historically have been joint productions with the Welham Girls' School in [[Dehradun]].\n\nIn 2001, a new music school was built beside the Rose Bowl. It houses a [[music library]], a [[concert hall]] and several practice and teaching rooms where students learn various western and Indian instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/stas-and-activities/music/|title=Music Programme and Facilities at The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> Pupils of the school have an option to appear for the [[Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations, conducted by [[Trinity College London]], in [[piano]], [[violin]], drums and classical guitar. In 2002, the school choir raised {{Indian Rupee}}2&nbsp;million for victims of the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] by organising a charity concert with the title ''Concerto 2000'', in which drummer [[Sivamani]] also took part.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/raga-meets-rhythm/article28369860.ece |title=Raga meets rhythm |newspaper=The Hindu |date=11 April 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-life/doon-tunes/article28596325.ece |title=Doon tunes |newspaper=The Hindu |date=30 March 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To commemorate its 75th Founder's Day in 2010, the school launched a music album, called ''Spirit of Doon'' in collaboration with [[EMI]]. The tracks were written by the lyricist [[Gulzar]] and were sung by the school choir, [[Sonu Nigam]], Shayan Italia and [[Bhajan Sopori]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Doon-goes-musical/articleshow/6919938.cms |title=Doon goes musical|newspaper=The Times of India |date=14 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations and partnerships==\n\nFrom its foundation in 1937 until the early 1980s, [[Welham Boys' School]] was a [[feeder school]] for Doon School and Mayo College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/31886-welham-boys-school-to-celebrate-platinum-jubilee-year.html |title=Welham Boys' School to celebrate platinum jubilee year |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> This ended when Surendra Kandhari, an old boy and former housemaster at Doon, became principal of Welham and transformed it into a high school. Families who send their sons to Doon often send their daughters to [[Welham Girls' School]], and many Doon alumni have married alumnae of Welham.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070121/ttlife1.htm |title=The Tribune Lifestyle |newspaper=The Tribune |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The two schools hold an annual \"dance social\", and their alumni sometimes collaborate in organising events. Pakistani ex-pupils from Doon established the [[Chand Bagh School]] 40&nbsp;km north of [[Lahore]], Pakistan, in 1998, modelling it on the general structure of Doon.<ref>{{cite web|author=Azhar M. A. Qureshi |url=http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611010826/http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2009 |title=Chand Bagh School |publisher=Chandbagh.edu.pk |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> \n\nDoon also has exchange programmes with a number of overseas schools, such as Eton College, Harrow School, [[St. Albans School (Washington, D.C.)|St. Albans School, Washington DC]], [[Millfield]], [[Schule Schloss Salem]], [[The Armidale School]], [[Bridge House School]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[King's Academy]], [[Stowe School]], [[Scotch College, Melbourne]], [[The Hutchins School]] and [[St. Mark's School (Texas)]]. In 2011 Doon twinned with [[The Thomas Hardye School]], Dorchester, [[England]], through a cultural exchange project organised by the [[BBC]] and [[British Council]] in light of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] held in the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9451296.stm|title=Schools Spotlight on Team Abhinav Bindra|publisher=BBC|date=8 April 2011|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> The Doon School is a member of the following organisations: [[G20 Schools]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gold |first=Adam |url=http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073515/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 October 2007 |title=Move over G8\u2014this is G20 > Harvard Westlake Chronicle Online |publisher=Students.hw.com |date=8 November 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Round Square]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925000935/http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 September 2012 |title=Doon School India |publisher=RoundSquare |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/ |title=HMC Schools : International Members |publisher=Hmc.org.uk |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[International Boys' Schools Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theibsc.org/page.cfm?p=1440&start=1 |title=International Boys' Schools Coalition: Member Directory |publisher=Theibsc.org |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Indian Public Schools' Conference]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ipsc.co.in/member.php|title=Indian Public Schools' Conference|website=www.ipsc.co.in}}</ref> [[Rashtriya Life Saving Society (India)|Rashtriya Life Saving Society]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lifesavingindia.com/rlssi_user/centres.html|title=RLSS(I)&#124;Centres & Licensees|website=www.lifesavingindia.com}}</ref> and [[International Award Association]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Pioneer |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/doon-school-becomes-first-indian-school-to-start-iayp-online.html |title=Doon School becomes first Indian school to start IAYP online |publisher=Dailypioneer.com |date=2014-08-06 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The school is the regional test centre for [[University of Cambridge ESOL Examinations]] and [[SAT]] Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivyzone.com/category/sat/test-centre/ |title=SAT l STUDY ABROAD l VISA I IvyZone.com &#124; Test-centre |publisher=Ivyzone.com |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Schools with similar names===\nAs private schools became more widespread in [[India]], several other schools used \"Doon\" as part of their names, causing some confusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-using-doon-in-their-names-to-cash-the-popularity-of-the-doon-school/articleshow/69224014.cms |title=Schools using Doon in their names to cash the popularity of The Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Among them are Doon Global School, Doon Presidency School, [[Doon International School (Palia Kalan)|Doon International School]], Doon Preparatory School, Doon Cambridge School, Doon Girls School, [[Doon Public School]] (in West Delhi, not the Doon Valley) and the Doon College of Spoken English. None of them are related to The Doon School.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-toi/special-report/Is-the-old-school-tie-wearing-thin/articleshow/6800680.cms?referral=PM |title=Is the old school tie wearing thin?|newspaper=The Times of India |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n[[File:DoonSchoolStamp.jpg|thumb|A commemorative postal stamp depicting the school's Main Building was released by [[India Post]] on 22 October, 2010, to mark Doon's 75th Founder's Day.]]\n;Doon in films & television\n{{main|Dazed in Doon}}\n{{main|Indian Summer School}}\n\n* The film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'', which was commissioned by the school on the occasion of its 75th anniversary and produced by old boy Ashvin Kumar, was banned by the school authorities because it \"doesn't give the school a good name\". The dispute remains unresolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-path-not-taken/article2924231.ece|title=The path not taken|first=Sudhish|last=Kamath|date=23 February 2012|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n* In September 2010, [[BBC Sport]] made a documentary on the Doon School for the ''World Olympic Dreams'' Project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9075650.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 The school that breeds Indian medal winners |publisher=BBC News |date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The purpose of the documentary, produced in association with the [[British Council]], was to show where [[Abhinav Bindra]], the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, spent his formative years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 Abhinav Bindra, India |publisher=BBC News |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2017, [[Channel 4]] of UK commissioned a 3-part documentary, ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', where five working-class boys from the UK were given a chance to study at Doon for a term to see if they would benefit from the experience. The filming began in August 2017, and the programmes were broadcast in March\u2013April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/29/indian-summer-school-review-five-terrible-teens-are-sent-to-indias-equivalent-of-eton |title=Indian Summer School review \u2013 five terrible teens are sent to India\u2019s equivalent of Eton &#124; Television & radio |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n;Doon in literature\n* [[Vikram Seth]] used his own experiences of being bullied at Doon to model the character of Tapan in ''[[A Suitable Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Huang |first1=Guiyou |title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Asian American Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Greenwood_Encyclopedia_of_Asian_Amer.html?id=d5RxDwAAQBAJ |date=2009 |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]] |location=Westport, Connecticut |language= |isbn=9781567207361 |page=860 |quote=...as a boarder at the prestigious Doon School, known as \"the Eton of India\" on Dehradun. Whilst at school, Seth encountered abuse and bullying from many of his fellow classmates, an experience that he later evokes by the character Tapan, the youngest of the Chaterjees, in ''A Suitable Boy''.}}</ref>\n* In [[Salman Rushdie]]'s short-story anthology [[East, West]], the protagonists Zulu and Chekhov are Doscos.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Damrosch |first1=David |title=How to Read World Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/How_to_Read_World_Literature.html?id=1VYsDwAAQBAJ |date=2017 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Son]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781119009245 |page=172 |quote=Chekhov and Zulu became ''Star Trek'' devotees while still in school in India...Significantly, they are enrolled in the Doon School, an elite British-style academy established in the waning years of British Raj.}}</ref>\n* In [[Tenzing Norgay]]'s autobiography ''Man of Everest'', he refers to [[Bandarpunch]] as \"The Doon School mountain\" as the mountain was frequented by two Doon School teachers, [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John Martyn]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norgay |first1=Tenzing |title=Man of Everest \u2013 The Autobiography of Tenzing |url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=90IPAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=doon+school+mountain |date=1955 |publisher=[[George G. Harrap and Co.]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781447400288 |page=154 |quote= It was to Garhwal. Back to Bandar Punch, \"the Doon School mountain,\" with my old friend Mr Gibson. }}</ref>\n* In [[Ruskin Bond]]'s novella ''Strangers in the Night'', character Jai Shankar is from Doon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bond |first1=Ruskin |title=Strangers in the Night |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Strangers_on_the_Roof.html?id=58nqMgEACAAJ |date=1994 |publisher=[[Penguin Books India]] |location= |language= |isbn=9780140240658 |page=4 |quote=William and Jai did not trail me to this place, as it was a little lowbrow for them (William being Swiss and Jai being Doon School).}}</ref>\n* [[Penguin Books|Penguin's]] ''The Great Speeches of Modern India'' (2011) included Vikram Seth's 1992 Founder's Day address, which being confessional surprised the school community, and [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]'s 2007 speech, which was noted for its wit and humour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7dCH_IYbt8C&q=doon+school#v=snippet&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=The Great Speeches of Modern India - Rudranghsu Mukherjee - Google Books |date= October 2011|accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9788184002348 |last1=Mukherjee |first1=Rudranghsu }}</ref>\n\n;Doon in research\n* ''Doon School Chronicles'' is the first of five [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] films, called the ''Doon School Quintet'', made by David MacDougall between 1997 and 2000 about the culture of the school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raifilm.org.uk/films/doon-school-chronicles/|title=Film : \u201cDoon School Chronicles\u201d \u2013 RAI Ethnographic Film Catalogue}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220001143/http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 February 2006 |title=Berkeley Media LLC: Catalog: Doon School Chronicles |publisher=Berkeleymedia.com |accessdate=20 February 2012 }}</ref> Macdougall has written of a tendency of some alumni to idealise a ''[[Golden age (metaphor)|Golden Age]]'' set in the first decade of the school's life, which sometimes makes them resistant to change.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\">{{citation|last=MacDougall|first=David|title=The corporeal image: film, ethnography, and the senses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&pg=PA107|accessdate=31 March 2012|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12156-7|pages=107\u2013108}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|first=David|last=MacDougall|url=http://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/526/doon-school-chronicles.html |title=DOON SCHOOL CHRONICLES|publisher=Ronin Films|accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School'' by Sanjay Srivastva is a detailed [[Sociology|sociological]] study of the school's culture and how it has influenced India's national character.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva}}</ref>\n* ''{{'}}Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools'', a 2005 report by the Institute of Social Studies Trust, discusses why the Doon School has no [[Reservation in India|reservations]] (quotas for specific social groups) in its admissions process. The post quotes an unnamed student who explains, \"passing the Doon School entrance exam means that you have proved yourself worthy of the school. Reserving seats for students seems to imply that the school must prove itself worthy of you.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Mallica |title='Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools |url=http://www.isst-india.org/PDF/Poor%20children%20in%20Rich%20school.pdf |publisher=Institute of Social Studies Trust |accessdate=30 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1969, [[Asian Survey]] (then Asian Review) - an Asian studies [[academic journal]] of [[University of California, Berkeley]] - produced a report on The Doon School as a part of their project which documented Indian history after the entry of [[East India Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sh4sAQAAIAAJ&q=doon+school&dq=doon+school |title=Asian review&nbsp;\u2014 Demetrius Charles Boulger, East India Association (London, England), Oriental Institute (Woking, England)  |accessdate=30 March 2013|last1=Boulger |first1=Demetrius Charles |year=1969 }}</ref>\n* In ''Indian Tales of the Raj'', Zareer Masani studies how Doon School's alumni affected the Indian political scene in the '60s.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Lm4FVb54_oUC&pg=PA152&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=Indian Tales of the Raj&nbsp;\u2014 Zareer Masani  |accessdate=30 March 2013|isbn=9780520071278 |last1=Masani |first1=Zareer |year=1988 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n{{Main|List of The Doon School alumni}}\n{{multiple image|align=right|direction=horizontal|header= |header_align=center\n |header_background =\n | footer =\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width =\n | image1=Vikram Seth, in Oxfordshire.jpg|width1=114|caption1=[[Vikram Seth]] (Class of 1969), novelist and poet, author of ''[[A Suitable Boy]]'' and ''[[The Golden Gate (Seth novel)|The Golden Gate]]''|image2=Amitav Ghosh by Gage Skidmore.jpg|width2=114|caption2=[[Amitav Ghosh]] (Class of 1972), author of the ''[[Ibis trilogy]]'' and ''[[The Hungry Tide]]''}}\n\nPupils are known as \"Doscos\", a contraction of \"Doon\" and \"school\". The vast majority of alumni are Indians, but a dwindling number are from Pakistan having studied at Doon before the [[Partition of India]] forced them to leave in 1947. Relations between Indian and Pakistani alumni have remained warm over the years, despite the long history of conflict between the two countries.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101024/dplus.htm#2 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys from Bangladesh and Nepal continue to study at Doon. Pupils of Doon have achieved prominence in politics, government service, the armed forces of India and Pakistan, commerce, journalism, the arts and literature.<ref name=\"suitablejoy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/mar/27/books.guardianreview1 |title=A suitable joy|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 March 1999 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book&nbsp;\u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1993 |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref> In politics, they include [[Union Cabinet of India|cabinet ministers]], [[Chief minister (India)|chief ministers]], several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] and [[Legislative Assembly|state Legislative Assemblies]], diplomats, and former heads of the Indian and Pakistani Air Forces.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/Seven-Doon-alumni-in-15th-Lok-Sabha/article16568183.ece |title=Other States / Uttaranchal News : Seven Doon alumni in 15th Lok Sabha |newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Former Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]] was educated at Doon.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/13/magazine/mrs-gandhi-grooms-another-son.html|title=Mrs. Gandhi Grooms Another Son|first=Michael T.|last=Kaufman|date=13 June 1982|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]], the former Defence Secretary of Pakistan [[Ghulam Jilani Khan]], [[Kamal Nath]] and [[Rahul Gandhi]] were at school, and [[Naveen Patnaik]], the [[Chief Minister of Odisha]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]], politican and poet [[Karan Singh]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Allana |first=Alia |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/doon-squad/464930 |title=The Doon School Squad|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> \n{{multiple image|align=left|direction=horizontal|header= |header_align=center\n |header_background =\n | footer =\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width =\n | image1=Sanjit Bunker Roy at Time 2010.jpg|width1=129|caption1=[[Bunker Roy]] (Class of 1962), founder, [[Barefoot College]]|image2=Chief Minister Naveen Patnaik - TeachAIDS (13566478155).jpg|width2=129|caption2=[[Naveen Patnaik]] (Class of 1964), [[Chief Minister of Odisha]]}}\n\nIn the field of literature, Doon alumni include novelists [[Amitav Ghosh]], [[Vikram Seth]], [[Ardashir Vakil]], and historian [[Ramachandra Guha]];<ref>{{cite news|author=Elisabeth Bumiller |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/29/books/a-novelist-beginning-with-a-bang.html |title=A Novelist Beginning With a Bang - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1997-07-29 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> and in journalism, [[Prannoy Roy]], founder of [[NDTV]]; [[Aroon Purie]], founder of ''[[India Today]]'', [[Karan Thapar]], [[Virendra Prabhakar]] and [[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/microsoft-s-new-boss-is-a-window-on-a-better-school-system-9115621.html|title=Microsoft\u2019s new boss is a window on a better school system|date=7 February 2014|website=The Independent}}</ref> India's first [[Rhodes scholar]], [[Lovraj Kumar]], was an alumnus.<ref>{{cite news|author=I. M. D. Little |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lovraj-kumar-1367199.html |title=Obituary: Lovraj Kumar|newspaper=The Independent |date=1 April 1994 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Abhinav Bindra]], India's first Olympic gold medallist, and the mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] studied at the school.<ref>{{cite news|author=BBC Sports Desk |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=Abhinav Bindra Indian Olympic Medallist|publisher=BBC |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> In arts and entertainment, Doon's alumni include [[Ali Fazal]], [[Roshan Seth]], [[Himani Shivpuri]], [[Chandrachur Singh]], [[Satyadeep Mishra]], and art collector [[Abhishek Poddar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/features/The-Abhishek-and-Radhika-Poddar-collection-of-Indian-Modern-and-Contemporary-Art-7960-1.aspx |title=How Abhishek and Radhika Poddar built their collection of Indian art &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date=2016-12-18 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[Turner Prize]]-winning sculptor [[Anish Kapoor]] and artist [[Vivan Sundaram]] also attended Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jun/07/anish-kapoor-sculpture-versailles-controversy |title=Anish Kapoor: superstar sculptor who loves to court scandal &#124; Observer profile &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n{{multiple image|align=right|direction=horizontal|header= |header_align=center\n |header_background =\n | footer =\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width =\n | image1=Anish Kapoor 2017.jpg|width1=114|caption1=[[Anish Kapoor]] (Class of 1970), artist. Designed Chicago's ''[[Cloud Gate]]'' and [[ArcelorMittal Orbit]], [[Olympic Park, London]]|image2=Narendra (Nandu) D. Jayal.jpg|width2=114|caption2=[[Nandu Jayal]] (Class of 1942), mountaineer, founder principal of [[Himalayan Mountaineering Institute]]}}\n\nIn business, the Doon alumni include [[Analjit Singh]] of Max Group, [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], chairman of [[Hero MotoCorp]]; [[Rahul Akerkar]], restaurateur and founder of Indigo and Qualia; father and son [[Vikram Lal]] and [[Siddhartha Lal]] of [[Eicher Motors]]; [[A. Vellayan]], chairman of the [[Murugappa Group]], [[Ajit Narain Haksar]], the first Indian chairman of [[ITC Limited]]; [[R.C. Bhargava]], chairman of [[Maruti Suzuki]]; [[Ajay S. Shriram]], managing director of [[DCM Shriram group]], and [[Sharan Pasricha]], CEO of Ennismore hospitality developer and founder of [[The Hoxton]] and [[Gleneagles Hotel|Gleneagles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/gleneagles-is-a-sleeping-giant-well-make-it-the-best-hotel-in-the-world-lbhjf75z0|title=\u2018Gleneagles is a sleeping giant. We\u2019ll make it the best hotel in the world\u2019|first=Dominic|last=Walsh|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Faculty===\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School faculty}}\nIn the early years, many teachers came from British schools, including [[Peter Lawrence (teacher)|Peter Lawrence]] from Eton College,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4309213.stm|title=Eton, the Raj and modern India|date=9 March 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] from [[Ripon Grammar School]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20041207/edit.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Opinions|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John A. K. Martyn]] and [[R. L. Holdsworth]] from Harrow.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> The school's first art teacher was the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]], from [[Visva-Bharati University|Shantiniketan]], who joined in 1936 and remained at school for twenty years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/bonfire-of-vanities/267708 |title=Bonfire of Vanities &#124; Vishvjit P. Singh |publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> Many sculptures and murals on the campus today were created by him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jnaf.org/artist/sudhir-khastgir/|title=Sudhir Khastgir - JNAF}}</ref> The film director [[Chetan Anand (director)|Chetan Anand]] taught briefly at the school from 1940 to 1944.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/arts/dev-anand-chetan-anand-doon-school-dehradun/story/1/19703.html|title=How Doon School inspired the inimitable Dev Anand style|website=www.dailyo.in}}</ref> Mountaineer [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] joined in 1946 as a geography teacher and led the boys on many expeditions.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/50-years-later-its-happily-Everest-after/articleshow/46893756.cms|title=50 years later, it's happily Everest after &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The cricketer and mathematics teacher, [[Sheel Vohra]], joined in 1959 and became the longest-serving master in school's history when he retired in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/remembering-sheel-vohra-doon-schools-beloved-bond.html|title=Remembering Sheel Vohra, Doon School's beloved 'Bond'|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> The [[Fiji-Indian]] academic [[Satendra Nandan]] taught history at school in the early 1960s, and the [[sarod]] player [[Ashok Roy]] headed the music department from 1977 to 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/25/its-time-goodbye-comrades/|title=It's Time: Goodbye, COMRADES - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref> [[Popular science]] author and theoretical physicist, [[Simon Singh]], taught science at Doon in 1987 before embarking on his academic and writing career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/there-s-math-in-simpsons-simon-says/story-czEcewcbqXaAuE38U6oF2K.html|title=There's math in Simpsons, Simon says|date=11 January 2014|work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Schools|Education}}\n* [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ ''Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School''] by Mady Martin, Dass Media, 1985, ASIN B0000CQHYY\n* [https://archive.is/20121219012747/http://fullcirclebooks.in/content/chhota-hazri-days-doscos-yatra ''Chhota Hazri Days: A Dosco's Yatra''] by Sanjiv Bathla, [[Rupa & Co.]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-81-291-1694-9}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130323003553/http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/sahibs-who-loved-india ''Sahibs who Loved India''] by [[Khushwant Singh]], [[Penguin Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-14-341580-0}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&q=Doon+School&dq=the+doon+school+sixty+years+on+pushpinder&source=gbs_word_cloud_r&cad=5#v=snippet&q=Doon%20School&f=false ''The Corporeal Image''] by David McDougall, [[Princeton University Press]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-691-12156-7}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Trees of Chandbagh''] by K.C. Sinha, Konark Publishers, 1996, {{ISBN|978-81-220-0457-1}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=3sVlHQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''For Hills To Climb''] by Gurdial Singh and Nalni Dhar, The Doon School Old Boys' Society, 2001\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=NEdmQgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Doon, The Story of a School''], edited by Sumer Singh, Indian Public Schools' Society, 1985, ASIN B0006ENF66\n* [http://dsobs.net/currentrb/current_rosebowl.php ''The Rose Bowl''], newsletter by The Doon School Old Boys' Society\n* [https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School, ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School''] by Sanjay Srivastva, [[Routledge]], 1998, {{ISBN|0-203-98027-1}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=The Doon School |s=Category:The Doon School |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School }}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.doonschool.com/|name = Official website}}\n* [http://www.dsobs.net/ Website of the Doon School Old Boys' Society]\n* [http://store.doonschool.com/ The Doon School - Gift Store]\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School}}\n[[Category:The Doon School| ]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Round Square schools]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in India]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in India]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in India]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|Boys' boarding school in Dehradun, India}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | image                   = The Doon School.jpg\n | caption                 = Main Building at The Doon School\n | image_size              = 300px\n | name                    = The Doon School\n | logo                    = The Doon School, Dehradun - logo.png\n | logo_size               = 150px\n | colours                 = Blue & White {{color box|#005293}} {{color box|white}}\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30.333|78.030|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n | pushpin_map             = India Uttarakhand#India\n | location                = The Doon School<br>Mall Road<br>[[Dehradun]]&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;248001<br>India<br>([https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/The+Doon+School/@30.3350253,78.0298105,17z Google Map], [https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/158385701 OpenStreetMap])\n | specialist              = \n | schooltype              = Private [[boarding school]]\n | motto                   = '' Knowledge our Light''\n | sister_school           = [[Welham Girls' School]]\n | established             = \n | founded                 = {{Start date and age|1935|09|10}}\n | founder                 = [[Satish Ranjan Das]]\n | head_name               = Founder Headmaster\n | head                    = [[Arthur Foot|Arthur Edward Foot]]\n | gender                  = Boys\n | lower_age               = 12\n | upper_age               = 18\n | headmaster              = Post vacant \n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governors\n | chair                   = [[Sunil Kant Munjal]]\n | pupils                  = c. 600\n | faculty                 = 70\n | houses                  = 5 \n | campus                  = 72 acres (297,314&nbsp;m\u00b2)\n | ceeb                    = 671616\n | district                = [[Dehradun district|Dehradun District]]\n | student_union           = [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n | affiliation             = [[International Baccalaureate|IB]]<br>[[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examination|CISCE]]<br>[[International General Certificate of Secondary Education|IGCSE]]\n | publication             = ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]''\n | free_label2             = Annual fees\n | free_text2              = {{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1025000}} (home students)<br>{{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1281000}} (international)\n | free_label              = Former pupils\n | free_text               = [[List of The Doon School alumni|Doscos]]\n | website                 = [http://www.doonschool.com/ www.doonschool.com]\n}}\n\n'''The Doon School''' (informally '''Doon School''' or '''Doon''') is a boys-only private [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]], [[Selective school|academically selective]] boarding school in Dehradun, Uttarakhand, India, established in 1935. It was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a [[Kolkata]] lawyer, who prevised a school modelled on the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]], but conscious of Indian ambitions and desires. Soon after initiating the funding scheme for Doon, Das, considered the school's founder, died in 1928. The school's first [[Head teacher|headmaster]] was [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], an Englishman who had spent nine years as a science master at [[Eton College]], England.<ref>{{cite book|year=1979|chapter=FOOT, Arthur Edward|title=Who Was Who 1961\u20131970|location=London|publisher=A. & C. Black|isbn=0-7136-2008-0}}</ref> The last headmaster, [[Matthew Raggett]], who resigned in January 2020, was the fourth British headmaster in Doon's history, and a member of [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]], [[UK]].\n\nThe school houses roughly 500 pupils aged 12 to 18, and admission is based on a competitive entrance examination and an interview with the headmaster. Every year boys are admitted in only two year groups: [[seventh grade]] in January and [[eighth grade]] in April. The school is fully residential, and boys and most teachers live on campus. In tenth grade, students take the [[IGCSE|Cambridge IGCSE]] examinations, and for the final two years can choose between [[Indian School Certificate]] or [[International Baccalaureate]] curriculum. A wide range of extra-curricular activities, numbering around 80, are offered to the boys, and early British masters such as [[R.L. Holsworth]], [[J.A.K. Martyn]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] established a strong tradition of [[Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering|mountaineering at school]]. The school occupies the former site of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] and is home to diverse flora and fauna. Doon remains a boys-only school despite continued pressure from political leaders to become [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/old-boys-want-doon-to-stay-as-it-is/cid/473019|title=Old boys want Doon to stay as it is|website=www.telegraphindia.com}}</ref> [[Old boy network|Old boys]] of the school are known as 'Doscos'. \n\nDoon has been consistently ranked the best all-boys residential school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/17-schools-from-u---khand-secure-top-10-positions-in-ewisr.html|title=17 schools from U\u2019khand secure Top 10 positions in EWISR|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> Although the school has often been cited as 'Eton of India' by media outlets such as the [[BBC]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02c3zgq|title=BBC World Service - Witness, India's Eton|website=BBC}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|author=STEVEN R. WEISMAN, Special to the New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/12/world/india-s-old-school-tie-harrow-by-the-himalayas.html |title=India'S Old School Tie - Harrow By The Himalayas |location=Dehra Dun (India); India |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=12 November 1985 |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/aug/13/fiction.arundhatiroy|title=The lost sub-continent|first=William|last=Dalrymple|date=13 August 2005|website=the Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Spectator]]'',<ref name=\"Spectator UK\">{{cite web|author=Read |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/put-him-down-for-doon |title=It's a spartan life at 'the Eton of India' |publisher=The Spectator |date= |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/alastair-sooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html|title=The rise & rise of Anish Kapoor Inc.|first=Alastair|last=Sooke|date=2 April 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> and ''[[Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Remnick |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/10/20/rajiv-gandhi-and-the-mantle-unsought/779cee82-b666-4248-8116-278d6134a002/ |title=Rajiv Gandhi And The Mantle Unsought |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1987-10-20 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> it eschews the label.<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Doon-of-India-wants-to-conquer-the-globe/articleshow/6800690.cms |title=\u2018Doon of India\u2019 wants to conquer the globe - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has educated a wide range of notable alumni, including politicians, diplomats, artists, writers and business leaders.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709213757/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=For wannabe Doons, don from hills is a boon |newspaper=Times of India |date=30 December 2002 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> Among the former pupils of Doon are the late Indian prime minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]], artist [[Anish Kapoor]], novelists [[Vikram Seth]] and [[Amitav Ghosh]], fashion designer [[Tarun Tahiliani]], mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] and social activist [[Bunker Roy]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:The Doon School main building (then FRI) - 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|Main building of Doon in 1917, when it was part of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].]]\n\nDoon was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a lawyer from Calcutta and advocate-general of Bengal, who in 1927 became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council]] of [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Irwin]] on the condition that he would use the prestige of this position to raise funds for a new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"auto\">MacDougall2006, p.100</ref> He decided to name the new school \"Doon\", as it was situated in the [[Doon Valley]]. He travelled widely in [[India]] with the goal of collecting {{Indian Rupee}}4&nbsp;million, but at the time of his death in 1928 had raised only {{Indian Rupee}}1 million in cash and a further {{Indian Rupee}}1&nbsp;million in promises. With the money, Das formed the Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which had the objective of founding new public schools in [[India]] that would admit students regardless of caste, creed or social status.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=360 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n\nAfter Das's death, the IPSS accomplished little, and by 1934 some of the original lenders had begun to inquire about the return of their money.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> To solve this problem, [[J. W. Bhore|Sir Joseph Bhore]], then Railway Minister of [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|Lord Willingdon's]] Council, became IPSS chairman and, with [[Akbar Hydari|Sir Akbar Hydari]] as secretary, worked to obtain the former estate of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]], in [[Dehradun]], from the government on favourable terms.<ref>''The Indian Year Book'', vol. 29 (1942), p. 419: \"Doon School&nbsp;\u2013 This school which is established in the Chand Bagh and Skinner's Estates at Dehra Doon owes its origin to the initiative and enthusiasm of the late SR Das.\"</ref> Sir Frank Noyce also joined the team. [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], then President of the British Board of Education, led a selection committee that nominated [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], a science teacher at [[Eton College]], to be the first headmaster. On 27 October, 1935, the [[Viceroy]], [[Lord Willingdon]], presided over the formal opening of the school. Seventy boys enrolled in the first [[Academic term|term]], and 110 more signed up for the second.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 203 (Note 12): \"...from Willingdon's inaugural address on 27 October 1935\"</ref>\n\n===Early years:1935\u20131970===\n\nFoot had never visited [[India]] before accepting the position of headmaster. He noted that the school appeared to be surrounded by forests and close to mountains, and the possibilities of outdoor recreation and mountaineering seem to have influenced his decision as much as the chance to create a completely new type of school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=359 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Foot's first action upon being offered the position was to recruit [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J.A.K. (John) Martyn]] from [[Harrow School]] as his deputy. Doon's ethos and guiding principles were determined early in its life by Foot, Martyn, [[R. L. Holdsworth|R.L. Holdsworth]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]], who went on to become principal of [[Mayo College]].<ref>{{cite web|author=site admin |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19851115-book-review-sumer-singh-doon-the-story-of-a-school-mady-martyn-martyn-sahib-802174-2014-01-16 |title=Where East meets West - Society & The Arts News - Issue Date: Nov 15, 1985 |publisher=Indiatoday.in |date=1985-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> They were soon joined in their efforts by Indians such as the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]] (the school's first art teacher, who had trained previously in [[Santiniketan]]) and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], a noted mountaineer who taught at Doon for several decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-sundaymagazine/climb-every-mountain/article28515581.ece |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> In an essay entitled ''The Objects of Education'' published in the school magazine, Foot offered a template for a complete education for boys, which included teaching them to form a habit of choosing good over evil, think logically, express their thoughts and views clearly, and maintain a healthy body.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" /> At the opening of the school, he said, \"Our boys should leave The Doon School as members of an aristocracy, but it must be an aristocracy of service inspired by the ideals of unselfishness, not one of privilege, wealth or position\".<ref>''The Doon School Sixty Years On'', 1936, p.4</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/interview_doon-school-is-popular-for-building-an-aristocracy-of-service_1392063 |title=Doon School is popular for building an 'aristocracy of service'&nbsp;\u2013 Academy|work=DNA |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> The annual school fees in 1935 was {{Indian Rupee}}1,375, and by September 1946, it had risen to {{Indian Rupee}}1,800.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> In 1947, there were around 300 boys studying at Doon, out of which 50-60 were [[Muslims]], 15-20 [[Sikhs]], 15-20 [[Parsees]], 6-7 Christians, and the remaining two-thirds Hindu.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=365 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n[[File:Main Gate, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main gate of the Doon School.]]\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =...&nbsp;By 14 he should have learnt all the ordinary principles of social behaviour. He should know how to stand up and speak to a variety of different types of people&nbsp;\u2013 to his own mother, to someone else's mother, to his father, to his schoolmasters, to servants, to Mahatma Gandhi or to the Viceroy, and to do this without any self-consciousness&nbsp;...At 17 must come another quality, less instinctive and requiring a maturer mind: he must acquire a capacity of judgement.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\">{{cite book|title=The Doon School Sixty Years On |publisher=Doon School Old Boys' Society|date=October 1996}}</ref>&nbsp;...\n |source = <small>Arthur Foot, 1946, ''The Objects of Education''</small>\n |align  = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]], about 65 Doon students served in the [[Indian Army during World War II|Army]], [[Royal Indian Navy|Navy]] or [[Indian Air Force|Air Force]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=369 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Martyn, who became the second headmaster in 1948, acknowledged the influence of German educator [[Kurt Hahn]] in the development of the school's ethos. Although Martyn had not visited India before, he immediately accepted Foot's offer because of the opportunity it afforded to implement Hahn's ideas, which he had not been able to do at Harrow.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=38|quote=When John wrote to Hahn to tell him we was going to India, Hahn replied that he had been waiting to be able to offer him a place at Gordonstoun...}}</ref> While Foot and Martyn were determined to model Doon on Eton and Harrow, they both agreed that Doon should cater primarily for Indian boys\u2014and not the sons of British expatriates\u2014in order to create a uniquely Indian public school rather than a transplanted British institution. Foot did not want Doon to be considered elitist. In a paper surveying the new school, presented to the [[Royal Society of Arts]], London in 1947, Foot wrote: \"In language we have never intended to base our instruction on the Classics in the way that Latin is still the centre pin of the English Public School. The great majority of boys take Urdu or Hindi.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=361 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n\n===Middle years: 1970\u20132000===\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-right:1em; font-size:85%; background:#ffc; color:black; width:20em; max-width:25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Headmasters\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n* [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], 1935\u20131948\n* [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J. A. K. Martyn]], 1948\u20131966\n* [[C. J. Miller]], 1966\u20131970\n* [[Eric Simeon|Eric J. Simeon]], 1970\u20131979\n* [[Gulab Ramchandani]], 1979\u20131988\n* [[Shomie Das]], 1988\u20131996\n* [[John Mason (Schoolmaster)|John A. Mason]], 1996\u20132003\n* [[Kanti Bajpai]], 2003\u20132009\n* [[Peter McLaughlin]], 2009\u20132016\n* [[Matthew Raggett]], 2016\u20132020 \n|}\n\nThe school's first Indian headmaster was [[Eric Simeon]], appointed in 1970. He came from a military background and laid great emphasis on disciplined living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/schooled-for-life/32471/|title=Schooled for life - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/Lt.-Col.-Eric-Joseph-Simeon-dead/article14764255.ece |title=Lt. Col. Eric Joseph Simeon dead |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> Simeon's tenure of nine years was marked with financial difficulties for the school and the estate suffered, as the funds were not enough to maintain buildings and facilities. <ref>https://www.doonschool.com/weekly/May%2019%202007.pdf</ref> In 1971, Simeon introduced the 'Scholar's Blazer', an academic equivalent of the pre-existing prize 'Games Blazer', so that boys accorded academic excellence the same level of prestige as they did sporting achievements.<ref name=\"Back to School\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/KaranThapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104092100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/karanthapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2010 |last=Thapar|first=Karan|title=Back to School |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1979, [[Gulab Ramchandani]] became the first alumnus to be appointed headmaster, and during his term the school regained financial stability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/ramchandani-old-boy-and-workaholic-headmaster-who-transformed-doon-school/articleshow/58185206.cms|title=Ramchandani: Old Boy and \u2018workaholic\u2019 headmaster who transformed Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> In 1988, [[Shomie Das]], another alumnus and the grandson of school founder Satish Ranjan Das, became headmaster. Das's focus was on upgrading the school infrastructure, and during his time the Oberoi house was added to the original four houses. The next headmaster, [[John Mason (schoolmaster)|John Mason]], appointed in 1996, planned on making Doon more affordable to school pupils. The school did not raise its fees while Mason was in office. \n\n====Criticism of Rajiv Gandhi administration====\n\nIn the 1980s, the then [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Rajiv Gandhi]], an alumnus, drew criticism from the media for appointing many old boys to his administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0724/eindia.html|title=Bootstrap steps for Gandhi|date=24 July 1987|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> His inner circle was labelled a \"Doon Cabinet\"<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /> or \"Dosco Mafia\",<ref>''Indian Tales of the Raj'' by Zareer Masani, p.152</ref> and ''Washington Post'' reported, \"The catch phrase around Delhi these days is that the 'Doon School runs India,' but that is too simple an analysis for a complex, chaotic country with so many competing spheres of influence.\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\">{{cite web|last=Bumiller |first=Elisabeth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1985/11/24/where-indias-elite-were-boys-together/0579f3d9-1835-4441-b1b1-a55e3111bdc3/ |title=Where India's Elite Were Boys Together |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1985-11-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Steven R. Weisman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/20/magazine/the-rajiv-generation.html |title=THE RAJIV GENERATION - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1986-04-20 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gandhi's reliance on Doon alumni for political advice later led Prime Minister [[Morarji Desai]] to remark, \"If I had anything to do with this place, I'd close it down\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\"/> Although any alumnus seldom held public office for some time afterward, this changed with the political ascendance of Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia, Naveen Patnaik, and Rahul Gandhi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707070626/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Naveen Patnaik sets stage for GeNext Doscos |newspaper=The Times of India |date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Recent years: 2000\u2013present===\n[[Kanti Bajpai]] was the third old boy, after Gulab Ramchandani and Shomie Das, to become headmaster, when appointed to the post in 2003. He introduced numerous punishments, notably \"yellow cards\", to control an outburst of bullying at Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03cgg70 |title=BBC World Service - Path to Power, Educating India's Elite |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1994-10-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> In 2006, Bajpai found himself embroiled in a controversy when the parents of Hindu and Sikh students complained on discovering that the school's dining hall only serves [[halal]] meat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bad-blood-over-meat-served-at-Doon-School/articleshow/1516879.cms|title=Bad blood over meat served at Doon School &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The fact came to light after a visiting Pakistani delegation was assured of their meal's halal status. Despite mounting pressure, the school's board of governors appealed for maintaining the status quo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/doon-debates-meaty-matters/story-mQ4y1Lt1fXLI3DiW2cV3XI.html|title=Doon debates meaty matters|date=3 May 2006|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> As of 2016, the school was serving both halal and non-halal (''[[jhatka]]'') meat varieties in the dining hall.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2434-FINAL.pdf</ref> In 2009, [[Peter McLaughlin]], an Irish academic, was chosen to lead the school, becoming the first non-Indian headmaster in almost four decades.\n\n====2010 Founder's Day celebrations and film controversy====\n[[File:President of India speaking at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]] speaking at the school's 75th Founder's Day in October 2010.]]\n\nFounder's Day is a three-four day event in the autumn term, usually October, that marks the school's founding and draws many ex-pupils from all parts of the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/item/40943-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref> The chief guest is usually a prominent person, and the events include exhibitions, productions of plays, yoga sessions, live bands, a fete and an orchestral concert given by members of the school's Music Society.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/how-indias-renowned-doon-school-is-embracing-change-to-retain-its-exclusivity/articleshow/45006985.cms?from=mdr |title=How India's renowned Doon School is embracing change to retain its exclusivity - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-11-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Datta |first=Sravasti |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523113538/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 May 2011 |title=Life & Style / Metroplus : All boarders on board |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 February 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon celebrated its 75th Founder's Day in 2010 and programmed events on an unprecedented scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/doon-school-to-celebrate-its-75th-anniversary-from-oct-21/articleshow/6712783.cms?from=mdr|title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21|date=8 October 2010|via=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/boys-will-be-boys/story-UxdKhDLhEGUVHIwaXe2e7H.html|title=Boys will be boys |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The event was christened ''DS-75''.<ref name=\"Doon school\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-08/news/27591639_1_celebrations-doon-school-chief-guest |title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21 |publisher=[[The Times Group]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School\">{{cite news|title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/15930-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |newspaper=Daily Pioneer|date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Among the chief guests were the then President of India [[Pratibha Patil]], King [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]] of Bhutan, and [[Kapil Sibal]], then minister of [[Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)|Human Resource Development]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bhutanjournals.com/monarchy/hms-address-at-doon-school-dehradun-india/ |title=HM's Address at Doon School, Dehradun, India|newspaper=Bhutan Journals |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Pratibha Patil, in her address, urged the school authorities to make Doon a co-educational institution.<ref name=\"telegraphindia1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/dame-dilemma-for-doon-president-s-co-ed-suggestion-evokes-mixed-reaction/cid/473014 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|title=Dame dilemma for Doon&nbsp;\u2013 President's co-ed suggestion evokes mixed reaction |date=25 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> One of the main events was a discussion, dubbed the \"Chandbagh Debate\", held between alumni including [[Vikram Seth]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Manpreet Singh Badal]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] and retired headmaster Kanti Bajpai, on the topic ''Can India lead?''. It was moderated by television commentator [[Karan Thapar]], an alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+matter+of+debate+at+Doon+School+platinum+jubilee.-a0240443417 |title=A matter of debate at Doon School platinum jubilee|newspaper=[[India Today]] |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Ashvin Kumar]], an alumnus and Oscar-nominated director, made the film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'' for the celebrations, using pupils for the cast and crew. Most of it was shot in June and July during the summer break, and those scenes which required the entire student body were filmed after the school reopened in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imaginox.co.uk/course/1718 |title=Making 'Dazed in Doon' |publisher=Imaginox |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> It was screened on the final day of celebrations to a gathering of over 2000 people, including guests, students, parents and alumni.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-School-bans-Ashvin-Kumars-film/articleshow/6919672.cms|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The day after screening, the school objected to the film and its distribution, labelling the bullying scenes \"defamatory\", and obtained a court order to delay its release. The DVD sales on campus were immediately halted.<ref name=fallout>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-film-fallout/articleshow/6941433.cms|title=Doon film fallout!|newspaper=The Times of India|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The dispute  remains unresolved between the director and school authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Ex-students-film-celebrating-Doon-draws-schools-ire/articleshow/7159525.cms|title=Ex-student's film 'celebrating' Doon draws school's ire &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> On 22 October 2010, a commemorative postage stamp depicting the school's main building was released by the [[Indian Postal Service]] to mark the occasion of the 75th Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101009/dplus.htm#5 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Detail of The Doon School Main Gate.jpg|thumb|200px|In March 2020, the school closed for the first time since its founding, following the [[COVID-19 outbreak]].]]\n\n====Present day====\n\nIn June 2016, the school announced the appointment of Matthew Raggett, principal of the [[Leipzig International School]]'s secondary department, to succeed Peter McLaughlin as headmaster. Until the start of McLaughlin's headmastership, the student demographic was dominated by boys hailing from the [[North Indian]] states. To make the school more diverse, Raggett continued McLaughlin's outreach initiative of inviting more applications from boys in [[South Indian|South]] and [[Northeast India]]n states.<ref name=\"indiatimes2\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/doon-school-looks-for-more-boys-from-south/articleshow/57725021.cms|title=Doon School: Doon School looks for more boys from south &#124; Bengaluru News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/doons-bonds-with-hyderabad/article7072329.ece|title=Doon\u2019s bonds with Hyderabad|first=R. Ravikanth|last=Reddy|date=6 April 2015|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> He also introduced a group discussion as part of the admissions process to test for critical thinking and peer interaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/dehradun/after-8-decades-doon-school-looks-to-south-east-for-students/story-4uYQRMF8qalW61HFHuB0xM.html|title=After 8 decades, Doon School looks to South, East for students|date=3 July 2017|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> The school was the subject of a 2018 [[Channel 4]] documentary series called ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', which was based on a social experiment to see if five under-performing British boys would thrive in Doon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/indian-summer-school|title=Indian Summer School: Indian Summer School|website=Channel 4}}</ref> In January 2020, Matthew Raggett stepped down as the tenth headmaster citing personal reasons. In March 2020, the school was shut down for the first time since its founding in 1935, and boys were sent home due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]] and the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|Indian lockdown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/three-city-based-boarding-schools-close/articleshow/74662334.cms|title=Coronavirus scare: Three city-based boarding schools close &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Online classes are being conducted for students through video conferencing apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-launch-online-classes-to-complete-syllabus/articleshow/74781758.cms|title=Schools launch online classes to complete syllabus in parts of Uttarakhand &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Governance and organisation==\n\nThe school is owned by the [[non-profit]] entity Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which was registered by S.R. Das in 1928 with the aim of establishing public schools in India. Under the IPSS, the Board of Governors supervises all matters of Doon.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 41: \"...the body founded by Das for the purposes of establishing the Doon School, the Indian Public Schools Society\"</ref> The current board comprises thirteen members and is chaired by [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], an alumnus. The president of [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]] has a seat on the board to represent the views and interests of the alumni.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> At the intramural level, the School Council, comprising the headmaster, heads of department, staff and student representatives from each house, is responsible for legislating and discussing school policies. Every house holds a vote to send four student representatives to the council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/leadership/|title=Leadership|website=Doon School}}</ref> Each house is run by a housemaster or a housemistress, along with a house captain and a team of [[School prefect|prefects]]. The housemistress is assisted by a [[matron]] known as \"The Dame\", who provides [[pastoral care]] for pupils, some of whom take several weeks to adjust fully to life in a boarding school, particularly given Doon's monastic lifestyle and strict routine.<ref name=\"outlookindia2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/class-up-at-doon/230938 |title=Class Up At Doon &#124; Anjali Puri |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Futehally\"> {{cite book |last1=Futehally |first1=Laeeq |title=The Last Englishman: The Life and Times of Jack Gibson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iw1CgAAQBAJ&dq=the+last+englishman+jack+gibson&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2015 |publisher=Hachette UK |location=London |language= |isbn=9789350099698 |page= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= The food and linen was the responsibility of the Dame (Matron)}}</ref> The homes of housemasters and housemistresses are adjacent or physically attached to their houses to enable close supervision and support. One senior boy serves as [[school captain]], chosen by teachers and students at the start of the year by voting in a [[secret ballot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-lad-is-Doon-School-captain/articleshow/18424444.cms |title=Ludhiana lad is Doon School captain &#124; Ludhiana News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-02-10 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>   \n\n===Houses===\n[[File:TataHouseQuadinDoon.jpg|thumb|right|East wing of Tata House and the quad.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:80%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | House name and Colours\n|-\n! House\n! Colour\n! Swatch\n|-\n|Kashmir || Yellow || {{colour box|#fecb00}}\n|-\n|Oberoi || Sky blue || {{colour box|#00add0}}\n|-\n|Tata || Red || {{colour box|#c60c30}}\n|-\n|Jaipur || Green || {{colour box|#007934}}\n|-\n|Hyderabad || Navy Blue || {{colour box|#003359}}\n|-\n|Martyn || || {{colour box|#496c60}}\n|-\n|Foot || ||{{colour box|#589199}}\n|}\n\nDoon follows the [[house system]]; there are five main houses (Hyderabad, Jaipur, Kashmir, Tata and Oberoi) and two 'holding houses' (Foot and Martyn, named after former headmasters), for boys in their first year.<ref name=\"Boarding at Doon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/pastoral-care/boarding-at-doon/|title=Boarding at Doon|website=Doon School}}</ref> The original four houses (Oberoi was added in 1991) were named after the largest initial donors: Hyderabad House was named after [[Akbar Hydari]], who secured a contribution from [[Nizam of Hyderabad]]'s government; Kashmir, after [[Maharajah]] [[Hari Singh]], then ruler of [[Jammu and Kashmir]]; Tata, after the [[Tata family|Tata]] Trusts; and Jaipur, after [[Rai Bahadur]] Amarnath Atal arranged for contributions from the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] of [[Jaipur]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 197 (Appendix 1): \"Donors to the Indian Public Schools' Society prior to 1936\"</ref> Boys are assigned to houses at the time of admission and develop great loyalty to them, since all [[intramural sports]] involve fierce competition between houses. Those who have a family history with a particular house are assigned to the same house. All houses have rooms, dormitories, kitchen, library, study rooms, and a Common Room for recreation.\n\n===Fees and financial aid===\nAs of April 2020, the annual school fees for Indian students was {{Indian Rupee}}10,25,000, and {{Indian Rupee}}12,81,000 for foreign nationals or [[non-resident Indians]]. Once admission is secured after clearing the entrance examination and interview, a student can apply for around 25 scholarships or awards on offer. Some are reserved for boys proficient in sports or arts, and those from an [[Indian Armed Forces|armed forces]] background. The monetary value of financial aid ranges from fifty percent of the tuition fee to being fully funded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/admissions/scholarships/|title=Scholarship Programme Offered by The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> In the media, the school has been described as a \"grooming ground for India's wealthy kids\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/10/28/the-doon-school-grooming-ground-for-indias-wealthy-kids/|title=The Doon School: Grooming Ground For India's Wealthy Kids|first=Forbes|last=Staff|website=Forbes}}</ref> The last headmaster, Matthew Raggett, has stated that over 25% of Doon's students receive needs-based bursaries, and the school is working towards a completely [[need-blind admission|needs-blind admission]] policy.<ref name=\"indiatimes2\"/>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:FC Barcelona camp at Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|Main Field of the school with Kashmir and Hyderabad houses in the background.]]\n\nThe school is spread across a single campus covering approximately {{convert|72|acre|m2}} flanked by Chakrata Road and Mall Road in the [[Dehradun Cantonment]] area of Dehradun city, [[Uttarakhand]], India.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114929995090170584 |title=The Andover of India? |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Anita|last=Raghavan|date=24 June 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To house the school, the IPSS acquired Chandbagh Estate in Dehradun from the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] (FRI). Part of the estate was once a deer park. The IPSS also acquired an adjoining estate, now known as Skinner's Field, from the descendants of [[James Skinner (East India Company officer)|James Skinner]]. The buildings on campus include the Main Building, which houses offices and classrooms, structures for sports facilities, science blocks, music school, library, arts and media centre, auditorium, amphitheatre, dining hall, wellness centre, recycling and waste-treatment plants, and masters' residences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412|title=Premium schools &#124; Outlook Business|website=www.outlookbusiness.com}}</ref>\n\n===Architecture===\n[[File:Rose Bowl amphitheatre, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|The school's [[amphitheatre]], known as Rose Bowl, was constructed by the boys and masters in the early-1930s over two years. It was refurbished in 2009.]]\nThe construction of the Main Building, then in FRI, was carried out by Imperial Public Works Department, and finished in 1911. Its Renaissance-style architecture was inspired by [[Basilica Palladiana]] in [[Vicenza]], Italy.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\" /> Many buildings on the campus have been designed by notable Indian architects or firms.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\" /> The library was designed by Romi Khosla, the Biology block by Ram Sharma, teachers' residences by Anagram Architects, and the new Arts and Media Centre, which was inaugurated in October 2010 and shortlisted for the 2010 World Architecture News Education Award, by alumnus Sandeep Khosla <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/5-schools-india-teach-lesson-design-architecture-pune-mumbai/|title=5 schools in India that offer a quick course in sensitive design and architecture|date=10 January 2020|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sandeep Khosla, Principal Architect , Khosla Associates |url=https://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/article/1507033/making-cut |title=Making the cut |publisher=Worldarchitecturenews.com |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Arts and Media Centre houses painting, ceramic, sculpture, and textile studios, along with a lecture hall, film and photography studio, publications' room and exhibition galleries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/86476/arts-and-media-centre-at-the-doon-school-khosla-associates/|title=Arts and Media Centre at the Doon School / Khosla Associates|date=4 November 2010|website=ArchDaily}}</ref> In 2016, the school's Main Building received the \"Honourable Mention\" under the [[UNESCO Asia Pacific Heritage Awards|UNESCO Asia-Pacific Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation]], following the conservation work carried out by Aishwarya Tipnis Architects on the more than a century-old building.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/doon-school-campus-extension-anagram-architects/|title=Take a tour of India\u2019s most elite private school, The Doon School campus|date=21 March 2018|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.one.un.org/page/restoration-of-prayer-hall-at-japan-shrine-wins-top-honor-in-unesco-asia-pacific-heritage-awards/ |title=Restoration of prayer hall at Japan shrine wins top honor in UNESCO Asia- Pacific Heritage Awards - UN India |publisher=In.one.un.org |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Natural environment===\nThe school estate, known as Chandbagh, lies in the green zone of the city and occupies the former site of the Imperial Forest Research Institute, now [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School'' (London: Routledge, 1998), p.65: \"The estate chosen by Noyce and Bhore to be the campus of the future Doon School was not, however, just an arrangement of buildings for the dissemination of serious knowledge. It was also a well planted garden...The Forest Service planted many different shrubs and trees [on the school campus] and these remain for our enjoyment and instruction.\"</ref> A wide variety of [[flora]] and [[fauna]] are found on campus, including many rare trees that date back to the days of the FRI.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\">{{cite web|url=https://fountainink.in/essay/no-common-or-garden-affair |title=No common or garden affair &#124; Fountain Ink |publisher=Fountainink.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\" /> The school has over 150 species of trees on its campus, and the formal gardens attract a variety of birds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashant |first=Shishir |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/doon-school-s-etp-may-be-trendsetter-111031400040_1.html |title=Doon school's ETP may be trendsetter |newspaper=[[Business Standard]] |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1996, a book titled ''Trees of Chandbagh'' was released which provided a comprehensive account of vegetation found on Doon's campus.<ref name=\"TreesofChandbagh\">{{cite book|last=Sahni|first=K. C.|title=Trees of Chandbagh: Doon's national heritage|year=1996|publisher=Konark Publishers|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-220-0457-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> Along similar lines, the illustrated book ''Birds of Chandbagh: A Guide To Birding at The Doon School'' was released in 2019, featuring photographs, illustrations and [[QR codes]] documenting the [[bird calls]] of the species found on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.in/BIRDS-CHANDBAGH-guide-birding-School/dp/B084HG4R87 |title=Buy BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Book Online at Low Prices in India &#124; BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Reviews & Ratings |publisher=Amazon.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has devised an Architectural and Projects Committee, which ensures that any construction taking place on campus is done without disturbing the ecological balance of the wooded school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/7-days/studies-in-style/cid/598008 |title=Studies in style |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2017-10-30 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:Main Building corridor at Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Ground-floor corridor of the school's Main Building, which houses classrooms and offices.]]\nThe school practices a five-and-a-half-day week consisting of 40 periods (or \"schools\"), each of 40 minutes. The school day begins with \"first bell\" soon after 6:15&nbsp;am. The boys have [[chhota haazri]] before doing [[calisthenics]] outdoors on the playing fields, which is then followed by classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Chhota-Hazri-bell-tolls-for-desi-Etons/articleshow/764209.cms |title=Chhota Hazri bell tolls for desi Etons|newspaper=The Times of India |date=4 July 2004 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> On Sundays, boys are free to pursue any activity or sport, or go into town for leisure.<ref name=\"Boarding at Doon\" /> The student-teacher ratio at the school is 10:1.<ref name=\"excellence\">{{cite journal|title=Excellence personified |journal=Frontline |date=12 February 2011 |volume=28 |issue=4 |url=http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313163529/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> Doon pupils take the [[International General Certificate of Secondary Education]] (IGCSE) exams in [[tenth grade]], which replaced [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] in 2017, and are thereafter offered two strands for the final two years: [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) or [[Indian School Certificate]] (ISC).<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibo.org/en/school/002603 |title=The Doon School - International Baccalaureate\u00ae |publisher=Ibo.org |date=2006-08-28 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year has three terms: spring, summer and autumn. The autumn term runs from August to the year-end final examinations in November, after which the boys are promoted to the new class in February.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kapoor |first=Jaskiran |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/class-apart/601507/0 |title=Class Apart |publisher=Indian Express |date=11 April 2010 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> Each term has a \"test week\" and end-of-term examinations known as \"trials\". Boys meet their tutors every week to discuss any matter, and are able to visit teachers, most of whom live on campus, for further academic help. Subjects on offer include geography, economics, environmental studies, art and design, psychology, music, English, Hindi, Sanskrit, and [[STEM subjects]]. Doon's foreign language offerings include French, German and Spanish. There is a career's department that offers pupils guidance on career paths, college applications, and entrance exams like the [[SAT]]. In recent years, boys have increasingly chosen foreign universities over Indian colleges, sometimes due to the hyper-competitiveness of the [[Higher education in India|Indian higher education system]] that calls for extremely high school-leaving scores for admissions.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/education/it-is-an-elite-school-not-elitist/article23029951.ece|title=\u2018It is an elite school, not elitist\u2019|first=Jaideep Deo|last=Bhanj|date=11 March 2018|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n\n===Traditions===\nThe early headmasters and teachers at Doon came from traditional British public schools, and the jargon introduced by them is still in use. For example, the weekly masters' meeting, started by Foot, is called ''Chambers'', a term taken from Eton, and evening \"prep\" (the boarding-school equivalent of homework) is called ''toye-time'', a term taken from [[Winchester College]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Charles |last1=Stevens|first2=Christopher|last2=Stray|title=Winchester notions: the English dialect of Winchester College|publisher=Athlone Press|year=1998|page=294|quote=Toy-time, or toytime recorded from 1831 as the evening hours of preparation, called 'prep' elsewhere&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB917469665815143000 |title=Language Lessons: For India's Elite English Is the Past -- and the Future\n|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The school songs were deliberately chosen to include both [[Urdu poetry]] and Hindu [[bhajan]]s as a way of emphasising Doon's secular ethos; similarly, the school prayers include a mix of Anglican hymns and Indian poetry.<ref>The Doon School Prayer book p.02-26</ref> Attendance at the morning assembly is required of all pupils and teachers. It traditionally begins with a song from the school's song book, which contains poetry, hymns and [[bhajans]], including ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''Chisti Ne Jis Zamin Mein'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]], ''Anand Loke'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''[[Lab Pe Aati Hai Dua]]'' by Muhammad Iqbal, ''Ghungat Ke Pat Khol Re'' (attributed to [[Meerabai]]), ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' (from a poem by [[Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay]]). Although ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' is India's [[National anthem]], it is traditionally referred to as \"Song No. 1\" at Doon since it was adopted as the school song in 1935, fifteen years before it  became India's national anthem.<ref>Bathla, Sanjeev<''Chotta Hazri:A Dosco's yatra'' p.32</ref><ref name=\"srivastava\">{{cite book|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School (p.82)|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref> Social work, known formally as \"Socially Useful Productive Work\", is also part of school life. All boys of the school must complete a mandatory quota of social service hours every term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/nation-education/article/doon-school-scouts-tamil-nadu-students |title=Doon School scouts for Tamil Nadu students |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon also oversees a Panchayat Ghar teaching impoverished children, and many building projects and workshops for the local community. Pupils and alumni have frequently helped local villages of organised efforts across India to assist people affected by natural disasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roundsquare.org/educational-insights/the-doon-school-a-village-service-partnership/ |title=The Doon School: A Village Service Partnership |publisher=Round Square |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> During the [[1991 Uttarkashi earthquake]], the school's amateur radio club was used by the government for communication purposes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gautam|first=Ashutosh|title=Earthquake: A Natural Disaster|year=2008|publisher=APH Publishing|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-313-0337-5|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSbTJDwMFgAC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=doon+school+uttarkashi+earthquake#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20uttarkashi%20earthquake&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\n{{Anchor|Athletics}}\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Cricket at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|A cricket game in progress on the Main Field.]]\n\nSports are compulsory for pupils. The school has over {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of playing fields, the largest of which are Skinner's Field and the Main Field. Cricket and hockey dominate the sports calendar in spring term, while football, athletics and boxing are played in autumn term. Other sports such as tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, basketball, swimming and gymnastics are played all-year round. Inter-house matches are played in cricket, hockey, football and basketball. Sports facilities include a 25-metre swimming pool, a boxing ring and a multi-purpose hall with a gymnasium, yoga studio, and facilities for indoor badminton, basketball and table tennis. There are two [[artificial turf]] cricket pitches, five basketball courts, four tennis courts, four squash courts, eight cricket nets, seven fields for hockey and football (which can be converted to four cricket pitches to accommodate seasonal sports), a modern cricket pavilion and two 400-metre athletics tracks. In 2014, the school inaugurated a shooting range on campus. Golf is offered to boys in partnership with local golf courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/departments/sports/|title=Sports|website=Doon School}}</ref> Doon hosts the annual Afzal Khan Memorial Basketball Tournament, an inter-school tournament that draws all major school basketball teams of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/features/the-asian-school-bag-bball-trophy-233461 |title=The Asian School bag b\u2019ball trophy |publisher=The Tribune India |date=2016-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/inside-the-hoop-dreams-of-21-boys-at-nbas-first-academy-in-india/articleshow/58979953.cms?from=mdr |title=NBA: Inside the hoop dreams of 21 boys at NBA\u2019s first academy in India - The Economic Times |date=2017-06-04 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020504/ncr3.htm |title=Tribune Online Edition, May 4, 2002 |work=The Tribune |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys visit other schools and academies from time to time to take part in various tournaments. For skill improvement, the school often invites professional sports bodies to hold training camps, which are usually open to students from across India. In 2013, a football coaching camp was held in association with Bar\u00e7a Academy, the official training school of [[FC Barcelona]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/f-c-barcelona-at-doon-july-2013/|title=F.C. Barcelona at Doon - July 2013|date=20 September 2013|website=Doon School}}</ref> and in January 2015, coaches from the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] held a week-long cricket training camp on the school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pitchvision.com/exclusive-inside-mcc-lords-club-india-coaching-camp-drills |title=Live Local Matches &#124; Tips & Techniques &#124; Articles & Podcasts |publisher=PitchVision |date=2017-07-24 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://educationworld.in//EWIssue.aspx|title=India's best boys boarding school|website=EducationWorld.in}}</ref>\n\n===Clubs and societies===\n{{See|The Doon School Model United Nations}}\n[[File:The Doon School Weekly.jpg|thumb|''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication of Doon. It is produced by the boys and distributed every Saturday morning.]]\n\nExtracurricular activities are also a compulsory element of school life.  There are around 70-80 clubs and societies, including astronomy, business, [[The Doon School Model United Nations]], quiz, photography and film, [[Model aircraft|aeromodelling]], robotics, paper recycling, weather reporting, pottery, carpentry, [[amateur radio]] and birdwatching, among others.<ref>{{cite web|author=\" + arr[2] + \" |url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412 |title=Premium schools |publisher=Outlook Business |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> In many societies pupils come together to discuss a particular topic, presided over by a schoolmaster and often including a guest speaker. The school has often invited prominent figures to give speeches and talks to the students; these have included heads of state, politicians, ornithologists, naturalists, artists, writers, economists, diplomats and industrialists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/category/events/visiting-speakers/|title=Visiting Speakers Archives|website=Doon School}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/600-mn-to-be-enrolled-in-uidai-in-next-4-years-nilekani/714784 |title=600 Mn to be Enrolled in UIDAI in Next 4 Years: Nilekani |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nBoys can write for, or join the editorial board of, a number of school magazines that are published in English or Hindi. ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication and the official school newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/34/42/obituary/ |title=OBITUARY : Himalayan Journal vol.34/42 |publisher=Himalayanclub.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> Distributed every Saturday morning, and edited by pupils, it chronicles school activities and is a platform for creative, political or humorous writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The publication aims to represent the views of the school community as well as Old Boys, and include satire and criticism of school policies. More subversive publications, critical of teachers and the school establishment, have occasionally been produced without official sponsorship. Other magazines include ''The Yearbook'', a heavily illustrated publication for recording all highlights of the school year, and ''The Doon School Information Review'' for cultural criticism. Specialist publications by academic departments include '' Vibgyor'' (Art), ''Echo'' (Science), ''The Econocrat'' (Economics), ''Infinity'' (Mathematics), ''Grand Slam'' (Sports) and ''The Circle'' (History and Political Science).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/|title=Publications|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n===Mountaineering===\n{{Main|Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering}}\n\n[[File:Mt. Everest Base Camp Expedition - 2008, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|2008 expedition to the [[Mount Everest Base Camp]] and [[Kala Patthar]].]]\n\nHalfway through each term, the boys go on a one-week \"midterm\", an expedition through the [[Siwalik Hills]] or [[Himalayas]]. Senior boys make treks of up to five days, unaccompanied by teachers, camping out in tents and cooking their own food. The trips are planned by students themselves. Alumni have recalled these midterms as being among their most formative and character-building experiences.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/how-the-playing-fields-of-doon-nurture-india-incs-best-leaders/articleshow/6872417.cms|title=How the playing fields of Doon nurture India Inc's best leaders |newspaper=The Times of India |date=5 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon has been credited with pioneering mountaineering in India, due to the accomplishments of masters such as [[R.L. Holdsworth]], [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], and alumni like [[Narendra Dhar Jayal|Nandu Jayal]], who later became the founder principal of [[Himalayan Mountaineering Institute]].<ref name=\"Kohli\"> {{cite book |last1=Kohli |first1=M.S. |title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure and Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Mountains_of_India.html?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&redir_esc=y |date=2002 |publisher=Indus |location= |language= |isbn=9788173871351 |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |page=209 |quote= p.290, Much of the credit for early interest in mountaineering among Indians goes to the Doon School, largely because of some distinguished British mountaineers on its staff like J.A.K. Martyn, J.T.M. Gibson, R.L. Holdsworth...In 1951, Gurdial Singh of the Doon School climbed the 7,120 metres high Trisul. This was the first Indian summit.}}</ref> Notable climbs by staff and alumni include [[Bandarpunch]] (6,316&nbsp;m) in 1950, Kala Nag (6,387&nbsp;m) in 1956, [[Trisul]] (7,120&nbsp;m) in 1951, [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m) in 1955, [[Abi Gamin]] (7,355&nbsp;m) in 1953 and 1955, Mrigthuni (6,855&nbsp;m) in 1958 and Jaonli (6,632 metres) in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/62/16/early-years-of-indian-mountaineering/ |title=Early Years of Indian Mountaineering |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> Some of these expeditions have been noted for their idiosyncrasies. After Gurdial Singh led a successful climb of Trisul, he performed a headstand [[asana]] on the summit as a tribute to the Hindu god [[Shiva]], who is said to abide there. Holdsworth smoked a pipe on reaching the summit of [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m), during its first ascent in 1931.<ref name=\"Harish Kapadia\"> {{cite book |last1=Kapadia |first1=Harish |title=Across Peaks and Passes in Garhwal Himalaya |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Across_Peaks_Passes_in_Garhwal_Himalaya.html?id=KptmxrqhKl4C |date=1999 |publisher=Indus Publishing |location=London |language=English |isbn=9788173870972 |page=17 |quote=The peak of Kamet was attempted several times and finally in 1931 Frank Smythe and Eric Shipton reached the summit along with some others. R.L. Holdsworth, who was with them, smoked a pipe on the summit, which I believe still remains a height record for smokers.}}</ref> Two Doon pupils climbed the [[Matterhorn]] in 1951 wearing cricket boots.<ref name=\"alpinejournal\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Richard|title=Climbing with the Doon School|journal=Alpine Journal|year=2001|pages=197\u2013201|url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2001_files/AJ%202001%20197-201%20Anderson%20Doon%20School.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and music===\n[[File:Waiting for Godot in Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' being staged in the open-air theatre, Rose Bowl.]]\nAn [[amphitheatre]] known as the Rose Bowl was built largely by pupils in two years during the 1930s<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=130|quote=It took two years to complete the open air theatre. The first play staged on it was \"The Merchant of Venice prodcued by Jack Gibson, and he had all his actors dressed in Indian costumes.\"}}</ref> and underwent a major structural change in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Santayana|first=Vivek|title=Losing a Kidney|journal=The Doon School Weekly|date=24 October 2009|issue=2232|url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66UfGMuG8?url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It can seat up to 2,000 people and has been the setting for numerous [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays and other classics of western theatre, as well as musical performances and speeches during school ceremonies such as Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805061511/http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=Doon Online&nbsp;\u2013 Vikram Seth |publisher=Mtholyoke.edu |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Multi-Purpose Hall is a more modern indoor theatre that can accommodate approximately 2,000 people. Plays are regularly staged in [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]], with 8\u20139 productions each year including 2 major productions as part of the Founder's Day celebrations. The Inter House Once-Act Play competition is held each year, alternatively in English and Hindi. Many of the plays historically have been joint productions with the Welham Girls' School in [[Dehradun]].\n\nIn 2001, a new music school was built beside the Rose Bowl. It houses a [[music library]], a [[concert hall]] and several practice and teaching rooms where students learn various western and Indian instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/stas-and-activities/music/|title=Music Programme and Facilities at The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> Pupils of the school have an option to appear for the [[Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations, conducted by [[Trinity College London]], in [[piano]], [[violin]], drums and classical guitar. In 2002, the school choir raised {{Indian Rupee}}2&nbsp;million for victims of the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] by organising a charity concert with the title ''Concerto 2000'', in which drummer [[Sivamani]] also took part.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/raga-meets-rhythm/article28369860.ece |title=Raga meets rhythm |newspaper=The Hindu |date=11 April 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-life/doon-tunes/article28596325.ece |title=Doon tunes |newspaper=The Hindu |date=30 March 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To commemorate its 75th Founder's Day in 2010, the school launched a music album, called ''Spirit of Doon'' in collaboration with [[EMI]]. The tracks were written by the lyricist [[Gulzar]] and were sung by the school choir, [[Sonu Nigam]], Shayan Italia and [[Bhajan Sopori]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Doon-goes-musical/articleshow/6919938.cms |title=Doon goes musical|newspaper=The Times of India |date=14 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations and partnerships==\n\nFrom its foundation in 1937 until the early 1980s, [[Welham Boys' School]] was a [[feeder school]] for Doon School and Mayo College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/31886-welham-boys-school-to-celebrate-platinum-jubilee-year.html |title=Welham Boys' School to celebrate platinum jubilee year |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> This ended when Surendra Kandhari, an old boy and former housemaster at Doon, became principal of Welham and transformed it into a high school. Families who send their sons to Doon often send their daughters to [[Welham Girls' School]], and many Doon alumni have married alumnae of Welham.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070121/ttlife1.htm |title=The Tribune Lifestyle |newspaper=The Tribune |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The two schools hold an annual \"dance social\", and their alumni sometimes collaborate in organising events. Pakistani ex-pupils from Doon established the [[Chand Bagh School]] 40&nbsp;km north of [[Lahore]], Pakistan, in 1998, modelling it on the general structure of Doon.<ref>{{cite web|author=Azhar M. A. Qureshi |url=http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611010826/http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2009 |title=Chand Bagh School |publisher=Chandbagh.edu.pk |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> \n\nDoon also has exchange programmes with a number of overseas schools, such as Eton College, Harrow School, [[St. Albans School (Washington, D.C.)|St. Albans School, Washington DC]], [[Millfield]], [[Schule Schloss Salem]], [[The Armidale School]], [[Bridge House School]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[King's Academy]], [[Stowe School]], [[Scotch College, Melbourne]], [[The Hutchins School]] and [[St. Mark's School (Texas)]]. In 2011 Doon twinned with [[The Thomas Hardye School]], Dorchester, [[England]], through a cultural exchange project organised by the [[BBC]] and [[British Council]] in light of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] held in the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9451296.stm|title=Schools Spotlight on Team Abhinav Bindra|publisher=BBC|date=8 April 2011|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> The Doon School is a member of the following organisations: [[G20 Schools]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gold |first=Adam |url=http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073515/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 October 2007 |title=Move over G8\u2014this is G20 > Harvard Westlake Chronicle Online |publisher=Students.hw.com |date=8 November 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Round Square]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925000935/http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 September 2012 |title=Doon School India |publisher=RoundSquare |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/ |title=HMC Schools : International Members |publisher=Hmc.org.uk |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[International Boys' Schools Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theibsc.org/page.cfm?p=1440&start=1 |title=International Boys' Schools Coalition: Member Directory |publisher=Theibsc.org |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Indian Public Schools' Conference]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ipsc.co.in/member.php|title=Indian Public Schools' Conference|website=www.ipsc.co.in}}</ref> [[Rashtriya Life Saving Society (India)|Rashtriya Life Saving Society]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lifesavingindia.com/rlssi_user/centres.html|title=RLSS(I)&#124;Centres & Licensees|website=www.lifesavingindia.com}}</ref> and [[International Award Association]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Pioneer |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/doon-school-becomes-first-indian-school-to-start-iayp-online.html |title=Doon School becomes first Indian school to start IAYP online |publisher=Dailypioneer.com |date=2014-08-06 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The school is the regional test centre for [[University of Cambridge ESOL Examinations]] and [[SAT]] Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivyzone.com/category/sat/test-centre/ |title=SAT l STUDY ABROAD l VISA I IvyZone.com &#124; Test-centre |publisher=Ivyzone.com |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Schools with similar names===\nAs private schools became more widespread in [[India]], several other schools used \"Doon\" as part of their names, causing some confusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-using-doon-in-their-names-to-cash-the-popularity-of-the-doon-school/articleshow/69224014.cms |title=Schools using Doon in their names to cash the popularity of The Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Among them are Doon Global School, Doon Presidency School, [[Doon International School (Palia Kalan)|Doon International School]], Doon Preparatory School, Doon Cambridge School, Doon Girls School, [[Doon Public School]] (in West Delhi, not the Doon Valley) and the Doon College of Spoken English. None of them are related to The Doon School.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-toi/special-report/Is-the-old-school-tie-wearing-thin/articleshow/6800680.cms?referral=PM |title=Is the old school tie wearing thin?|newspaper=The Times of India |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n[[File:DoonSchoolStamp.jpg|thumb|A commemorative postal stamp depicting the school's Main Building was released by [[India Post]] on 22 October, 2010, to mark Doon's 75th Founder's Day.]]\n;Doon in films & television\n{{main|Dazed in Doon}}\n{{main|Indian Summer School}}\n\n* The film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'', which was commissioned by the school on the occasion of its 75th anniversary and produced by old boy Ashvin Kumar, was banned by the school authorities because it \"doesn't give the school a good name\". The dispute remains unresolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-path-not-taken/article2924231.ece|title=The path not taken|first=Sudhish|last=Kamath|date=23 February 2012|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n* In September 2010, [[BBC Sport]] made a documentary on the Doon School for the ''World Olympic Dreams'' Project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9075650.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 The school that breeds Indian medal winners |publisher=BBC News |date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The purpose of the documentary, produced in association with the [[British Council]], was to show where [[Abhinav Bindra]], the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, spent his formative years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 Abhinav Bindra, India |publisher=BBC News |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2017, [[Channel 4]] of UK commissioned a 3-part documentary, ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', where five working-class boys from the UK were given a chance to study at Doon for a term to see if they would benefit from the experience. The filming began in August 2017, and the programmes were broadcast in March\u2013April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/29/indian-summer-school-review-five-terrible-teens-are-sent-to-indias-equivalent-of-eton |title=Indian Summer School review \u2013 five terrible teens are sent to India\u2019s equivalent of Eton &#124; Television & radio |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n;Doon in literature\n* [[Vikram Seth]] used his own experiences of being bullied at Doon to model the character of Tapan in ''[[A Suitable Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Huang |first1=Guiyou |title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Asian American Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Greenwood_Encyclopedia_of_Asian_Amer.html?id=d5RxDwAAQBAJ |date=2009 |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]] |location=Westport, Connecticut |language= |isbn=9781567207361 |page=860 |quote=...as a boarder at the prestigious Doon School, known as \"the Eton of India\" on Dehradun. Whilst at school, Seth encountered abuse and bullying from many of his fellow classmates, an experience that he later evokes by the character Tapan, the youngest of the Chaterjees, in ''A Suitable Boy''.}}</ref>\n* In [[Salman Rushdie]]'s short-story anthology [[East, West]], the protagonists Zulu and Chekhov are Doscos.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Damrosch |first1=David |title=How to Read World Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/How_to_Read_World_Literature.html?id=1VYsDwAAQBAJ |date=2017 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Son]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781119009245 |page=172 |quote=Chekhov and Zulu became ''Star Trek'' devotees while still in school in India...Significantly, they are enrolled in the Doon School, an elite British-style academy established in the waning years of British Raj.}}</ref>\n* In [[Tenzing Norgay]]'s autobiography ''Man of Everest'', he refers to [[Bandarpunch]] as \"The Doon School mountain\" as the mountain was frequented by two Doon School teachers, [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John Martyn]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norgay |first1=Tenzing |title=Man of Everest \u2013 The Autobiography of Tenzing |url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=90IPAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=doon+school+mountain |date=1955 |publisher=[[George G. Harrap and Co.]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781447400288 |page=154 |quote= It was to Garhwal. Back to Bandar Punch, \"the Doon School mountain,\" with my old friend Mr Gibson. }}</ref>\n* In [[Ruskin Bond]]'s novella ''Strangers in the Night'', character Jai Shankar is from Doon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bond |first1=Ruskin |title=Strangers in the Night |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Strangers_on_the_Roof.html?id=58nqMgEACAAJ |date=1994 |publisher=[[Penguin Books India]] |location= |language= |isbn=9780140240658 |page=4 |quote=William and Jai did not trail me to this place, as it was a little lowbrow for them (William being Swiss and Jai being Doon School).}}</ref>\n* [[Penguin Books|Penguin's]] ''The Great Speeches of Modern India'' (2011) included Vikram Seth's 1992 Founder's Day address, which being confessional surprised the school community, and [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]'s 2007 speech, which was noted for its wit and humour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7dCH_IYbt8C&q=doon+school#v=snippet&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=The Great Speeches of Modern India - Rudranghsu Mukherjee - Google Books |date= October 2011|accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9788184002348 |last1=Mukherjee |first1=Rudranghsu }}</ref>\n\n;Doon in research\n* ''Doon School Chronicles'' is the first of five [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] films, called the ''Doon School Quintet'', made by David MacDougall between 1997 and 2000 about the culture of the school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raifilm.org.uk/films/doon-school-chronicles/|title=Film : \u201cDoon School Chronicles\u201d \u2013 RAI Ethnographic Film Catalogue}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220001143/http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 February 2006 |title=Berkeley Media LLC: Catalog: Doon School Chronicles |publisher=Berkeleymedia.com |accessdate=20 February 2012 }}</ref> Macdougall has written of a tendency of some alumni to idealise a ''[[Golden age (metaphor)|Golden Age]]'' set in the first decade of the school's life, which sometimes makes them resistant to change.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\">{{citation|last=MacDougall|first=David|title=The corporeal image: film, ethnography, and the senses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&pg=PA107|accessdate=31 March 2012|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12156-7|pages=107\u2013108}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|first=David|last=MacDougall|url=http://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/526/doon-school-chronicles.html |title=DOON SCHOOL CHRONICLES|publisher=Ronin Films|accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School'' by Sanjay Srivastva is a detailed [[Sociology|sociological]] study of the school's culture and how it has influenced India's national character.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva}}</ref>\n* ''{{'}}Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools'', a 2005 report by the Institute of Social Studies Trust, discusses why the Doon School has no [[Reservation in India|reservations]] (quotas for specific social groups) in its admissions process. The post quotes an unnamed student who explains, \"passing the Doon School entrance exam means that you have proved yourself worthy of the school. Reserving seats for students seems to imply that the school must prove itself worthy of you.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Mallica |title='Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools |url=http://www.isst-india.org/PDF/Poor%20children%20in%20Rich%20school.pdf |publisher=Institute of Social Studies Trust |accessdate=30 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1969, [[Asian Survey]] (then Asian Review) - an Asian studies [[academic journal]] of [[University of California, Berkeley]] - produced a report on The Doon School as a part of their project which documented Indian history after the entry of [[East India Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sh4sAQAAIAAJ&q=doon+school&dq=doon+school |title=Asian review&nbsp;\u2014 Demetrius Charles Boulger, East India Association (London, England), Oriental Institute (Woking, England)  |accessdate=30 March 2013|last1=Boulger |first1=Demetrius Charles |year=1969 }}</ref>\n* In ''Indian Tales of the Raj'', Zareer Masani studies how Doon School's alumni affected the Indian political scene in the '60s.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Lm4FVb54_oUC&pg=PA152&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=Indian Tales of the Raj&nbsp;\u2014 Zareer Masani  |accessdate=30 March 2013|isbn=9780520071278 |last1=Masani |first1=Zareer |year=1988 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n{{Main|List of The Doon School alumni}}\n{{multiple image|align=right|direction=horizontal|header= |header_align=center\n |header_background =\n | footer =\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width =\n | image1=Vikram Seth, in Oxfordshire.jpg|width1=114|caption1=[[Vikram Seth]] (Class of 1969), novelist and poet, author of ''[[A Suitable Boy]]'' and ''[[The Golden Gate (Seth novel)|The Golden Gate]]''|image2=Amitav Ghosh by Gage Skidmore.jpg|width2=114|caption2=[[Amitav Ghosh]] (Class of 1972), author of the ''[[Ibis trilogy]]'' and ''[[The Hungry Tide]]''}}\n\nPupils are known as \"Doscos\", a contraction of \"Doon\" and \"school\". The vast majority of alumni are Indians, but a dwindling number are from Pakistan having studied at Doon before the [[Partition of India]] forced them to leave in 1947. Relations between Indian and Pakistani alumni have remained warm over the years, despite the long history of conflict between the two countries.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101024/dplus.htm#2 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys from Bangladesh and Nepal continue to study at Doon. Pupils of Doon have achieved prominence in politics, government service, the armed forces of India and Pakistan, commerce, journalism, the arts and literature.<ref name=\"suitablejoy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/mar/27/books.guardianreview1 |title=A suitable joy|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 March 1999 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book&nbsp;\u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1993 |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref> In politics, they include [[Union Cabinet of India|cabinet ministers]], [[Chief minister (India)|chief ministers]], several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] and [[Legislative Assembly|state Legislative Assemblies]], diplomats, and former heads of the Indian and Pakistani Air Forces.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/Seven-Doon-alumni-in-15th-Lok-Sabha/article16568183.ece |title=Other States / Uttaranchal News : Seven Doon alumni in 15th Lok Sabha |newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Former Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]] was educated at Doon.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/13/magazine/mrs-gandhi-grooms-another-son.html|title=Mrs. Gandhi Grooms Another Son|first=Michael T.|last=Kaufman|date=13 June 1982|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]], the former Defence Secretary of Pakistan [[Ghulam Jilani Khan]], [[Kamal Nath]] and [[Rahul Gandhi]] were at school, and [[Naveen Patnaik]], the [[Chief Minister of Odisha]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]], politican and poet [[Karan Singh]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Allana |first=Alia |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/doon-squad/464930 |title=The Doon School Squad|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> \n{{multiple image|align=left|direction=horizontal|header= |header_align=center\n |header_background =\n | footer =\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width =\n | image1=Sanjit Bunker Roy at Time 2010.jpg|width1=129|caption1=[[Bunker Roy]] (Class of 1962), founder, [[Barefoot College]]|image2=Chief Minister Naveen Patnaik - TeachAIDS (13566478155).jpg|width2=129|caption2=[[Naveen Patnaik]] (Class of 1964), [[Chief Minister of Odisha]]}}\n\nIn the field of literature, Doon alumni include novelists [[Amitav Ghosh]], [[Vikram Seth]], [[Ardashir Vakil]], and historian [[Ramachandra Guha]];<ref>{{cite news|author=Elisabeth Bumiller |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/29/books/a-novelist-beginning-with-a-bang.html |title=A Novelist Beginning With a Bang - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1997-07-29 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> and in journalism, [[Prannoy Roy]], founder of [[NDTV]]; [[Aroon Purie]], founder of ''[[India Today]]'', [[Karan Thapar]], [[Virendra Prabhakar]] and [[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/microsoft-s-new-boss-is-a-window-on-a-better-school-system-9115621.html|title=Microsoft\u2019s new boss is a window on a better school system|date=7 February 2014|website=The Independent}}</ref> India's first [[Rhodes scholar]], [[Lovraj Kumar]], was an alumnus.<ref>{{cite news|author=I. M. D. Little |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lovraj-kumar-1367199.html |title=Obituary: Lovraj Kumar|newspaper=The Independent |date=1 April 1994 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Abhinav Bindra]], India's first Olympic gold medallist, and the mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] studied at the school.<ref>{{cite news|author=BBC Sports Desk |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=Abhinav Bindra Indian Olympic Medallist|publisher=BBC |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> In arts and entertainment, Doon's alumni include [[Ali Fazal]], [[Roshan Seth]], [[Himani Shivpuri]], [[Chandrachur Singh]], [[Satyadeep Mishra]], and art collector [[Abhishek Poddar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/features/The-Abhishek-and-Radhika-Poddar-collection-of-Indian-Modern-and-Contemporary-Art-7960-1.aspx |title=How Abhishek and Radhika Poddar built their collection of Indian art &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date=2016-12-18 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[Turner Prize]]-winning sculptor [[Anish Kapoor]] and artist [[Vivan Sundaram]] also attended Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jun/07/anish-kapoor-sculpture-versailles-controversy |title=Anish Kapoor: superstar sculptor who loves to court scandal &#124; Observer profile &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n{{multiple image|align=right|direction=horizontal|header= |header_align=center\n |header_background =\n | footer =\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width =\n | image1=Anish Kapoor 2017.jpg|width1=114|caption1=[[Anish Kapoor]] (Class of 1970), artist. Designed Chicago's ''[[Cloud Gate]]'' and [[ArcelorMittal Orbit]], [[Olympic Park, London]]|image2=Narendra (Nandu) D. Jayal.jpg|width2=114|caption2=[[Nandu Jayal]] (Class of 1942), mountaineer, founder principal of [[Himalayan Mountaineering Institute]]}}\n\nIn business, the Doon alumni include [[Analjit Singh]] of Max Group, [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], chairman of [[Hero MotoCorp]]; [[Rahul Akerkar]], restaurateur and founder of Indigo and Qualia; father and son [[Vikram Lal]] and [[Siddhartha Lal]] of [[Eicher Motors]]; [[A. Vellayan]], chairman of the [[Murugappa Group]], [[Ajit Narain Haksar]], the first Indian chairman of [[ITC Limited]]; [[R.C. Bhargava]], chairman of [[Maruti Suzuki]]; [[Ajay S. Shriram]], managing director of [[DCM Shriram group]], and [[Sharan Pasricha]], CEO of Ennismore hospitality developer and founder of [[The Hoxton]] and [[Gleneagles Hotel|Gleneagles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/gleneagles-is-a-sleeping-giant-well-make-it-the-best-hotel-in-the-world-lbhjf75z0|title=\u2018Gleneagles is a sleeping giant. We\u2019ll make it the best hotel in the world\u2019|first=Dominic|last=Walsh|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Faculty===\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School faculty}}\nIn the early years, many teachers came from British schools, including [[Peter Lawrence (teacher)|Peter Lawrence]] from Eton College,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4309213.stm|title=Eton, the Raj and modern India|date=9 March 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] from [[Ripon Grammar School]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20041207/edit.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Opinions|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John A. K. Martyn]] and [[R. L. Holdsworth]] from Harrow.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> The school's first art teacher was the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]], from [[Visva-Bharati University|Shantiniketan]], who joined in 1936 and remained at school for twenty years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/bonfire-of-vanities/267708 |title=Bonfire of Vanities &#124; Vishvjit P. Singh |publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> Many sculptures and murals on the campus today were created by him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jnaf.org/artist/sudhir-khastgir/|title=Sudhir Khastgir - JNAF}}</ref> The film director [[Chetan Anand (director)|Chetan Anand]] taught briefly at the school from 1940 to 1944.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/arts/dev-anand-chetan-anand-doon-school-dehradun/story/1/19703.html|title=How Doon School inspired the inimitable Dev Anand style|website=www.dailyo.in}}</ref> Mountaineer [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] joined in 1946 as a geography teacher and led the boys on many expeditions.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/50-years-later-its-happily-Everest-after/articleshow/46893756.cms|title=50 years later, it's happily Everest after &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The cricketer and mathematics teacher, [[Sheel Vohra]], joined in 1959 and became the longest-serving master in school's history when he retired in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/remembering-sheel-vohra-doon-schools-beloved-bond.html|title=Remembering Sheel Vohra, Doon School's beloved 'Bond'|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> The [[Fiji-Indian]] academic [[Satendra Nandan]] taught history at school in the early 1960s, and the [[sarod]] player [[Ashok Roy]] headed the music department from 1977 to 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/25/its-time-goodbye-comrades/|title=It's Time: Goodbye, COMRADES - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref> [[Popular science]] author and theoretical physicist, [[Simon Singh]], taught science at Doon in 1987 before embarking on his academic and writing career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/there-s-math-in-simpsons-simon-says/story-czEcewcbqXaAuE38U6oF2K.html|title=There's math in Simpsons, Simon says|date=11 January 2014|work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Schools|Education}}\n* [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ ''Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School''] by Mady Martin, Dass Media, 1985, ASIN B0000CQHYY\n* [https://archive.is/20121219012747/http://fullcirclebooks.in/content/chhota-hazri-days-doscos-yatra ''Chhota Hazri Days: A Dosco's Yatra''] by Sanjiv Bathla, [[Rupa & Co.]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-81-291-1694-9}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130323003553/http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/sahibs-who-loved-india ''Sahibs who Loved India''] by [[Khushwant Singh]], [[Penguin Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-14-341580-0}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&q=Doon+School&dq=the+doon+school+sixty+years+on+pushpinder&source=gbs_word_cloud_r&cad=5#v=snippet&q=Doon%20School&f=false ''The Corporeal Image''] by David McDougall, [[Princeton University Press]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-691-12156-7}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Trees of Chandbagh''] by K.C. Sinha, Konark Publishers, 1996, {{ISBN|978-81-220-0457-1}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=3sVlHQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''For Hills To Climb''] by Gurdial Singh and Nalni Dhar, The Doon School Old Boys' Society, 2001\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=NEdmQgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Doon, The Story of a School''], edited by Sumer Singh, Indian Public Schools' Society, 1985, ASIN B0006ENF66\n* [http://dsobs.net/currentrb/current_rosebowl.php ''The Rose Bowl''], newsletter by The Doon School Old Boys' Society\n* [https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School, ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School''] by Sanjay Srivastva, [[Routledge]], 1998, {{ISBN|0-203-98027-1}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=The Doon School |s=Category:The Doon School |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School }}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.doonschool.com/|name = Official website}}\n* [http://www.dsobs.net/ Website of the Doon School Old Boys' Society]\n* [http://store.doonschool.com/ The Doon School - Gift Store]\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School}}\n[[Category:The Doon School| ]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Round Square schools]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in India]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in India]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in India]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "LeadFixer", "label": "safe", "comment": "name spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Doo